<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Not Offended by Disagreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Denying reports of friction, President Clinton  
said Thursday that ``I will take no offense'' if Vice President Al 
Gore -- or likely Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton for that 
matter -- disagrees with him in the heat of political campaigning. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be a dreary world indeed if we all agreed on  
everything,'' the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	He claimed to be ``frankly bewildered'' by recurring stories  
that he is hurt and angry that Gore has distanced himself on 
questions of Clinton's moral character and ``the wasted time'' of 
the long impeachment ordeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton complimented Gore as the most experienced Democratic  
candidate for president in terms of foreign policy, arms control 
and domestic policy ideas that ``have made America a better 
place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president said, ``I have nothing bad to say'' about former  
Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's Democratic rival. But at the same time 
Clinton did not offer any praise, either. 
</P>
<P>
	The president spoke at a news conference with visiting Egyptian  
President Hosni Mubarak in the Old Executive Office Building next 
to the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the front-runner for the  
Republican presidential nomination, would be marching in step with 
other GOP leaders if he declined to accept federal campaign money 
and the spending limits that go with it. ``The leadership of the 
Republican Party in general are unanimously hostile to campaign 
finance reform,'' the president said. ``They don't believe in it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reports of White House friction have exposed tensions between  
Clinton's and Gore's staffs as the vice president tries to 
establish his political identity for the 2000 race. After a series 
of stories, White House chief of staff John Podesta told Clinton's 
aides to remain silent if they have a problem about Gore's campaign 
or an opinion about his relationship with the president. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have been frankly bewildered by those reports ... and I  
honestly do not know what the source of the stories are but they 
are not in my heart or my mind,'' the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	Praising Gore as the only candidate who has stated his views on  
issues, Clinton gave the vice president a pass to express 
differences. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want him to get out there, and if he disagrees with a  
decision that I make as president during the next year and a half, 
then of course he will have to say so, and I will take no offense 
at that,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the first lady may have to state publicly where she has  
disagreed privately with him if she runs for the Senate from New 
York. ``That's the way democracy works,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	He left an opening for Mrs. Clinton to disagree with  
administration-backed Medicare belt-tightening measures that have 
pinched New York teaching hospitals and other health care 
providers. Clinton suggested that New York lawmakers and others 
concerned with the problem should raise their concerns ``because I 
do think that's a legitimate issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore, formally beginning his race for the White House, told  
Tennessee reporters last month that there have been many occasions 
when he disagreed with Clinton over the past 6 1/2 years. Clinton said 
that ``I didn't ask Al Gore to become vice president so that he 
would agree with me on everything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said of Gore, ``There is nobody in the race who is  
running or who could run who has had as much experience in as many 
different ways. ... No one has had anything like that level of 
experience with that level of positive impact on the people of our 
country.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
