<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FAA Investigating Wing-Clipping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Two American Airlines jets clipped wings on the  
ground at O'Hare International Airport, causing minor damage to the 
planes. No one was hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	Damage on one of the Boeing 767s delayed 173 passengers bound  
for Sweden overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened as the Federal Aviation Administration  
began a four-month review of safety and pilot training at American, 
the nation's second-largest airline. 
</P>
<P>
	The review was prompted by six fatal accidents and other serious  
incidents, including the June 1 crash of an American plane in 
Little Rock, Ark., that killed 11 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said the accident at O'Hare on Tuesday night  
apparently happened when American Flight 80, bound for Stockholm, 
swiped the wing of another plane as it was taxiing toward the 
runway. 
</P>
<P>
	The second plane was carrying no passengers and was being driven  
by mechanics who were working on it. It was standing still in an 
authorized ramp area but apparently accidentally had one wing 
protruding into the taxiway that Flight 80 was using. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
