<HEADLINE> U.N.: World Economy Growing Slowly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Despite the recovery of most financial  
markets and clear signs of stability in Asia, the world economy is 
still growing slowly and the poorest countries continue to suffer 
the most, according to a U.N. report released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	With Japan still in recession, economic growth in North America  
and Europe have kept the world economy going, though overall world 
growth is only expected to be 2 percent in 1999, said Nitin Desai, 
U.N. undersecretary-general for economic and social affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	The slowdown has essentially stopped signs of growth that were  
evident in the first half of the 1990s in sub-Saharan Africa and 
some of the growth in the so-called transition economies of Eastern 
Europe, he told a press conference to launch ``The World Economy in 
1999.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, economic growth this year in developing nations is on  
track to be lower than any year this decade, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The report suggest that a per capita growth rate of about 3  
percent a year needs to be sustained to allow progress in raising 
living standards and reducing poverty. Only 13 developing countries 
are forecast to meet that benchmark in 1999, compared to 39 
countries in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	And 32 countries are forecast to see per capita output fall in  
1999. 
</P>
<P>
	``The financial crises of the past two years, and ensuing  
economic slowdowns, have dealt a stunning blow to world development 
prospects,'' Desai said. 
</P>
<P>
	There were ``clear signs of recovery in Asia,'' Desai said. But  
weakness was registered in Latin American and the former Soviet 
republics known as Commonwealth of Independent States. 
</P>
<P>
	The growth rate in developing countries is expected to be 2.5  
percent this year compared to 1.7 percent in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	But excluding China and India, which didn't experience a  
slowdown this year, ``the picture looks extremely bleak,'' for 
developing countries, Desai told a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	The transition economies have lost their momentum after  
achieving an average growth rate of 2.4 percent in 1997, the report 
found. 
</P>
<P>
	World growth, expected to be 2 percent in 1999, was 1.9 percent  
a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	The report follows an appeal from Secretary-General Kofi Annan  
to the world's industrialized powers to shore up international 
financial structures and take greater account of the needs of the 
world's poor. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
