<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Starr Turns Attention Elsewhere </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With Whitewater officially over, Independent  
Counsel Kenneth Starr is trying to wrap up two other parts of his 
investigation -- the White House travel office firings and 
accusations by presidential accuser Kathleen Willey, according to 
legal sources familiar with the probe. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr ended his nearly five-year Whitewater probe Wednesday by  
obtaining a pair of guilty pleas from presidential friend Webster 
Hubbell, who was sentenced to a year's probation by U.S. District 
Judge James Robertson, a Clinton appointee. 
</P>
<P>
	With Mrs. Clinton considering a Senate bid and no longer facing  
a possible court appearance at Hubbell's now-scuttled August trial, 
supporters of the president and first lady cheered the end of 
Whitewater. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ken Starr has finally acknowledged after all this time and all  
this money that there was never anything there in Whitewater, 
despite Republican accusations and innuendo over the last five 
years,'' former White House special counsel Lanny Davis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr now turns his attention elsewhere. Legal sources familiar  
with the investigation, speaking on condition of anonymity, said 
his office was dealing with: 
</P>
<P>
	--The 1993 purge of the White House travel office and whether  
Mrs. Clinton directed the firings. She says she did not. 
</P>
<P>
	--Nathan Landow, a Maryland developer and Democratic Party  
contributor. A recently released FBI polygraph report says Kathleen 
Willey, who has accused Clinton of groping her at the White House, 
has alleged that Landow suggested possible testimony she could give 
in the Paula Jones sexual harassment case. Landow denies any 
wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	A defiant Hubbell, the former No. 3 official at the Justice  
Department, insisted Wednesday that ``what I pleaded to has nothing 
to do with Mrs. Clinton,'' even though the broadly worded felony 
charge to which he pleaded guilty accuses him of concealing legal 
work he and the first lady performed on a fraudulent Arkansas land 
project in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	In the plea agreement, the single specific listed by Hubbell was  
failing to disclose a potential conflict of interest to federal 
regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr prosecutor Robert Ray said in court that ``proof'' at a  
Hubbell trial would have reflected the concealment of work by ``the 
1985-86 billing partner,'' a reference to Mrs. Clinton. Starr 
underscored that later, issuing a written statement saying the 
wide-ranging charge to which Hubbell pleaded guilty concerned his 
and ``Hillary Rodham Clinton's relationship'' with a real estate 
project. Federal regulators say it was riddled with sham 
transactions and fictitious land sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Hubbell also pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor count of failing to  
pay income tax in a deal that also dropped tax charges against his 
wife, his accountant and his tax attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	``After five years, it's over,'' Hubbell said outside the  
federal courthouse. ``The office of independent counsel has finally 
agreed to leave me, my family and my friends alone. And our lives 
can begin again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Starr said the guilty pleas ended the Arkansas phase of his  
investigation that looked at the Clintons' Whitewater real estate 
investment and other business and private dealings. He said he was 
trying to wrap up other aspects in an ``orderly fashion'' but that 
a federal grand jury was still looking into certain allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's efforts have resulted in convictions of 14 people,  
including the Clintons' Whitewater business partners James and 
Susan McDougal and then-Arkansas Gov. Jim Guy Tucker, and led to 
the president's impeachment by the House last winter on charges 
related to the Monica Lewinsky sex and cover-up scandal. Clinton 
was acquitted by the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	At Hubbell's sentencing that immediately followed his guilty  
pleas, Starr acknowledged that incessant criticism of his $40 
million investigation played a role in his decision to reach a deal 
with the former associate attorney general. He told the judge that 
the controversy had ``found its way into the hearts and minds of 
prospective jurors'' and could have affected Hubbell's trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr also cited the end of the independent counsel law, which  
expired Wednesday because Congress did not renew it. Under a 
grandfather clause, Starr can keep investigating. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
