<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wohlers Needs Elbow Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Reliever Mark Wohlers, trying to find the  
strike zone and resurrect his career with the Cincinnati Reds, has 
torn an elbow ligament and will have reconstructive surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers, 29, will be sidelined for up to 18 months after  
completely tearing the ulnar collateral ligament while throwing a 
pitch in a minor league game last week. 
</P>
<P>
	He felt a burning sensation after the pitch and became concerned  
when the elbow didn't improve in the last few days. A magnetic 
resonance imaging test detected the career-threatening injury. 
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers was the closer on the Atlanta Braves' World Series  
championship club in 1995, but lost his ability to throw strikes 
last season. He was traded to the Reds for John Hudek on April 16 
and was trying to regain his control and a place in the majors. 
</P>
<P>
	``What else can happen to the guy?'' said starter Denny Neagle,  
who was a teammate in Atlanta. ``I feel for him. People say you're 
only given as much as you can handle, but how much can one person 
handle?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers struggled to keep his emotions in check Thursday after  
the injury was disclosed. He thought he'd improved during a minor 
league rehabilitation assignment and was close to a callup. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what's so frustrating,'' he said, averting his eyes  
from reporters. ``I had made tremendous strides. I was at a point 
where I was on the mound and feeling good about myself and making 
good pitches and everything was feeling fine emotionally, 
physically and mentally. I felt I was a few appearances away from 
coming up here. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've climbed bigger hurdles in my life. It's just another bump  
in the road that I'm just going to have to meet head on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. James Andrews will replace the torn ligament with one from  
another part of Wohlers' body -- so-called Tommy John surgery. 
Wohlers could begin throwing in four months and is expected to be 
out for 12-18 months. 
</P>
<P>
	``The positive thing is that Mark's hopefully got a lot of life  
left in his arm,'' Dr. Timothy Kremchek said. 
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers hopes the Reds give him the chance to try for a  
comeback. Otherwise, he intends to retire. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they don't want me, I don't want to play anywhere else,''  
Wohlers said. ``That will just be it. Hopefully, they'll bear with 
me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers' voice wavered as he mentioned the possibility his  
career could be over. General manager Jim Bowden said there were 
tears when the two of them met in his office late Wednesday night 
to discuss the MRI findings. 
</P>
<P>
	``He and I were sharing tears in my office last night,'' Bowden  
said. ``It's a shame because Mark worked so hard to come back. He's 
only 29 years old and the way those surgeries are today, a lot of 
those guys come back. He's made it clear he wants to do it with the 
Reds and I think that's great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wohlers set a Braves record with 39 saves in 1996 and had 33 the  
following season. He pulled a muscle in his left side early last 
year and lost his control in May. 
</P>
<P>
	He was sent to Triple-A Richmond twice to try to regain his  
touch, but never found it. Wohlers seemed to be back on track 
during spring training, but started struggling once the season 
started. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Braves tried to send him back to the minors, he  
declined the assignment, prompting the trade to the Reds. The 
Braves agreed to pay Wohlers' $5.2 million salary this season and 
the $800,000 buyout for next year, the last on his contract. 
</P>
<P>
	After the trade, Wohlers was put on the disabled list with  
anxiety disorder and tried to work out flaws in his delivery. He 
was pitching for Double-A Chattanooga when he suffered the injury, 
which was initially thought to be tendinitis. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
