<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Major Exchanges Agree To Coordinate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Leaders of the major U.S. stock markets appear  
ready to cooperate with one another, to appease regulators, as they 
move to extend stock trading into the late evening and early 
morning hours. 
</P>
<P>
	At a summit in Wall Street's back yard Wednesday, Securities and  
Exchange Commission chairman Arthur Levitt stressed that all U.S. 
markets should open and close at the same time, despite varying 
proposals from the Nasdaq Stock Market and the New York Stock 
Exchange. Levitt said it would be too confusing for investors to 
have different exchanges open different hours. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is our collective goal to maintain the integrity of the  
markets and to protect investors,'' Levitt said. 
</P>
<P>
	The leading markets also may pick the same date to launch longer  
sessions. That means Nasdaq may have to push back its aggressive 
September time frame to match the NYSE's more conservative target 
of the third quarter next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank Zarb, head of the National Association of Securities  
Dealers which governs the Nasdaq, indicated he would be willing to 
apply the brakes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We generally agree on the principle that the industry should  
do this in a coordinated way,'' Zarb said. ``It is very likely we 
would aspire to a uniform date.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Regulators and stock market officials attending the summit  
formed four working groups to study the effect of extended hours on 
the finance industry and investors. Preliminary recommendations are 
expected within 10 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	For Wall Street firms and employees, the longer hours will be  
nothing short of a revolution. And some workers worry they won't 
have much time for family dinners or tucking the kids into bed. 
</P>
<P>
	With U.S. markets' current hours of 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m. Eastern  
time, investors on the West Coast get shut out after lunch. Between 
20 percent to 25 percent of online trades by individual investors 
are placed after hours. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial markets around the world are moving toward  
round-the-clock trading and electronic trading businesses are 
offering added competition online to the U.S. markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Extending hours is expected to put additional stress on the  
financial service industry, which is currently scrambling to fix 
any potential Year 2000 computer problems and switch next year to 
stock prices quoted in decimals instead of fractions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990701.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 20:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nemechek Captures Daytona Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- In better days, they called him  
``Front Row Joe.'' The nickname fits once again for Joe Nemechek, 
who won the pole position for the Pepsi 400 Thursday night, his 
first top qualifying effort in more than two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Nemechek took his Chevy around Daytona International Speedway's  
2.5-mile trioval at 194.860 mph early in the qualifying session for 
Saturday's race. It was reminiscent of his successful 1997 season, 
in which Nemechek earned his nickname by winning two poles and 
qualifying second three times. 
</P>
<P>
	Nemechek has made 170 Winston Cup starts without a victory. Like  
any driver, he would like to break that string at NASCAR's most 
famous track. Of course, he knows that qualifying and the actual 
race are always different at Daytona, one of two tracks that 
require carburetor restrictor plates to reduce speeds. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's two separate deals,'' Nemechek said. ``You go fast with a  
qualifying package for basically two laps. For racing, you've got 
to get a package where you can hold the pedal down for a whole 
run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On the outside pole will be Ricky Rudd, an owner-driver who  
qualified at 194.574 mph just hours after learning his nine-year 
sponsorship deal with Tide will be terminated after this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I guess this doesn't hurt anything,'' Rudd said of his effort  
to find a new sponsor. ``It's good advertising. What I'm proud 
about is that I took a pretty bad slap in the face for our team 
effort. The guys on our team are good. We just need time to 
mature.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In third was Mark Martin, who qualified at 194.376 mph. Martin  
is seeking his first restrictor-plate victory since 1997 at 
Talladega, when his Ford, helped by an aerodynamic edge, averaged 
188.354 mph in an accident-free race on the circuit's fastest 
track. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really feel like we've got the best shot at a race at  
Daytona that we've ever had,'' said Martin, who has never won a 
main event at the track. ``We've got great horsepower. This is the 
most I've had on any restrictor plate that I can ever remember.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Next to Martin will be Chad Little (193.690 mph), with Rusty  
Wallace and Tony Stewart in the third row. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Gordon, who won the pole and the Daytona 500 in February,  
qualified 11th. Dale Earnhardt was 10th and series points leader 
Dale Jarrett was 12th. 
</P>
<P>
	They'll all be chasing Nemechek, who has endured a difficult  
year, falling to 37th in the driver standings and with just one 
top-10 finish over the first half of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	The successful qualifying coincides with team owner Felix  
Sabates' decision to put team manager Tony Glover back in charge of 
Nemechek's car, after moving Nemechek's former chief, Scott 
Eggleston, onto teammate Sterling Marlin's crew. 
</P>
<P>
	The results showed immediately, with Nemechek's pole coming two  
weeks after Marlin won the pole in Pocono. 
</P>
<P>
	``Felix walked into the shop and said we were going to make some  
changes, some big changes,'' Nemechek said. ``All of the sudden, we 
were swapping crew chiefs. Getting hooked back up with Tony is 
good. At the end of 1997, we ran strong. Tony and I really started 
clicking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 25 fastest qualifiers locked up starting spots in the 43-car  
field, with the rest of the lineup to be set Friday in the final 
round of time trials. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the drivers who failed to make the top 25 and will have to  
either try again Friday or stand on their first-day laps were Terry 
Labonte, who was 39th, and Steve Park, last among the 44 who made a 
qualifying attempt. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenny Wallace also failed to qualify. He had to use an untested  
car after getting into an accident in practice. Wallace was able to 
drive in qualifying, but the car did not survive the accident. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990701.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 15:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Ryan Ready for Hall Induction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Saying he's tired of being introduced as  
a future Hall of Famer, Nolan Ryan is looking forward to his 
induction on July 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan said Thursday he'll take about 150 people to the ceremony,  
including more than 100 aboard a special Southwest Airlines flight 
dubbed the ``Nolan Ryan Express.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reminiscing on his long career in the majors, Ryan said he  
regretted never having pitched to Ted Williams or playing on 
Cincinnati's ``Big Red Machine'' of the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	But he has plenty of special memories from his time with four  
teams. Ryan won a World Series title with the 1969 New York Mets, 
pitched four no-hitters for the California Angels, commuted from 
home and pitched his fifth no-hitter during nine years with the 
Houston Astros, then reached 5,000 strikeouts and 300 wins during 
five seasons with the Texas Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan also pitched his sixth and seventh no-hitters while he was  
with the Rangers. 
</P>
<P>
	Of all the accomplishments, Ryan's favorites were the seventh  
no-hitter and the 5,000th strikeout, ``because they happened here 
and the way the fans reacted and supported me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan, who leaves for Cooperstown, N.Y., on July 23, already has  
been given a guided tour of the Hall. He said ``it was a neat 
feeling'' seeing an exhibit of seven caps from his seven 
no-hitters, and said he never really thought about getting into the 
Hall until Don Sutton won his 250th game in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's never been a 300-game winner that didn't make the  
Hall,'' Sutton told Ryan. 
</P>
<P>
	``It got me to thinking about how they do view Hall of Famers  
and what criteria that people use when they vote,'' Ryan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan appeared on 98.79 percent of the ballots cast by 10-year  
members of the Baseball Writers' Association of America, well above 
the 75 percent needed, 
</P>
<P>
	Ryan's tailor has made him a new suit for the induction, but the  
pitcher said he hasn't written an acceptance speech. He said it 
would run ``somewhere between 2 minutes and an hour.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He looks forward to meeting other Hall of Famers, including  
players he faced decades ago. As for fellow Hall inductees George 
Brett and Robin Yount, he called them two of the best hitters he 
ever faced. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990701.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 15:26:00 </DATE_TIME>
