<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U S West To Discuss Qwest Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- U S West Inc., the Denver-based Baby Bell phone  
company at the heart of a three-week takeover battle, said Thursday 
it would explore a $34.7 billion offer from Qwest Communications 
International Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	U S West's decision follows a similar move Monday by Frontier  
Corp., the fifth-largest long-distance company, which is weighing a 
$11.8 billion takeover bid from Denver-based Qwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, however, both U S West and Frontier have merger  
agreements with Global Crossing Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Thursday Global Crossing gave U S West permission to  
provide information to Qwest so that they can discuss the rival 
offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Sol Trujillo, U S West chairman, president and CEO said in a  
statement, ``The Board remains committed to acting in the best 
interests of U S West shareholders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Global Crossing and Qwest are building worldwide networks to  
carry high-speed Internet traffic. They are fighting for U S West 
and Frontier in order to secure the customers and sales to drive 
their business plans. 
</P>
<P>
	This is just the latest in a series of recent bidding wars in  
the communications industry. In May, AT&AMP;T Corp., the nation's 
largest long-distance company, won a bidding war against Comcast 
Corp. for MediaOne, a large cable company. And in Europe, upstart 
Olivetti SpA won a fight with Deutsche Telekom for control of 
Telecom Italia SpA. 
</P>
<P>
	Behind the aggressive offers is a sea change in technology,  
which is forcing telephone, cable TV and computer companies to 
offer many of the same services. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest chairman and CEO Joseph P. Nacchio said the company hopes  
to begin discussions with U S West as soon as possible. 
</P>
<P>
	``We firmly believe a combination of U S West and Qwest will  
significantly benefit the shareholders, customers and employees of 
each of our companies,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Global Crossing, based in Bermuda, offered $10.9 billion in cash  
and stock for Rochester, N.Y.-based Frontier and about $31 billion 
in stock for U S West. The deal with U S West, however, hangs on 
the success of the Frontier acquisition. If Frontier backs out, it 
could scuttle Global Crossing's plans to buy U S West. 
</P>
<P>
	If Qwest is the victor, Frontier and U S West would have to pay  
about $1 billion in breakup fees to Global Crossing. 
</P>
<P>
	U S West's announcement came after the markets closed. The  
company's stock ended the day unchanged at $58.75 on the New York 
Stock Exchange, where Frontier's shares rose 31 1/4 cents to $58.93 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest's stock rose 31 1/4 cents to $33.37 1/2 on the Nasdaq Stock  
Market, where Global Crossing's shares fell $2.65 1/4 to $40. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990701.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 09:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Contenders Salute N.H. Primary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. John Kasich proclaimed the joys of  
dogsled racing. Pat Buchanan pleaded not to be sent back to 
``Crossfire.'' And Sen. Bob Smith whipped together a Christmas 
jingle, just in case the first-in-the-nation primary comes before 
the millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	It was all part of a tribute to the political tradition of the  
state of New Hampshire -- or ``Nuevo Hampshire'' as Vice President 
Al Gore called it Wednesday night at a gala dinner filled with 
presidential hopefuls. 
</P>
<P>
	The crop of contenders saluted the role New Hampshire -- and its  
voters -- have played in presidential elections in years past, 
keeping in mind that the state's role will be equally important 
this time around. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Dole, taking a cue from David Letterman, compiled her  
top 10 ways to woo New Hampshire voters. Among them: ``Claim to 
have invented the New Hampshire primary,'' ``Wear a plaid shirt and 
leave the state'' and ``Change my middle name to 'dubya.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Others described how they have already mastered the art of  
getting up close and personal with the people of New Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	When Lamar Alexander walked across the state while campaigning  
in 1995, he met a woman on a cigarette break from her job inside a 
shoe factory job. Alexander told her he wanted to be her next 
president. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's all we need, another president,'' the woman responded,  
blowing smoke onto Alexander's flannel shirt. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, New Hampshire's favorite son, drew laughs for poking fun  
at the possibility that the state's primary may be held in 
December. The New Hampshire governor signed a bill Tuesday which 
would allow the primary to be held this year, in order to stay a 
week ahead of the other states. 
</P>
<P>
	His rendition of ``Twas the Night Before the Primary'' touched  
nearly every candidate with rhymes like: ``Is it Libby or Liddy, 
Elizabeth or Ma'am. It's your last name dear lady that's got you in 
a jam,'' and ``George Junior's left Austin, with endorsements and 
dough, his views on the issue we still do not know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith did not exempt himself from his own humor, acknowledging  
that his poll numbers show he is ``no sure thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Single digits, no name ID, so say the polls. But there's many  
more Smiths than Bushes and Doles.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others engaged in self-mockery as well.  
</P>
<P>
	Gore used his turn at the stump to point out that the event was  
being held in the taxpayer-financed Ronald Reagan Building. 
</P>
<P>
	``So we can all say 'I paid for this microphone' ... but I'm the  
only one who can say I invented this microphone,'' Gore quipped. 
</P>
<P>
	Buchanan, who lost to George Bush in 1992 and Bob Dole in 1996,  
begged for mercy from their family members -- who have become his 
new nemeses in the upcoming race. 
</P>
<P>
	``Elizabeth, don't send me back to 'Crossfire' again,'' Buchanan  
said. ``Ted Turner is getting fed up with this act.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the no-show contenders at the event didn't go unscathed  
altogether. Gore opened his shtick by reporting on one of the 
absent, but just recently added, competitors to the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``Orrin Hatch called to say he'd be late, and we should start  
without him,'' Gore said. ``I think we already did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The event was held to raise money for the Library and Archives  
of New Hampshire's Political Tradition, which has a collection of 
election campaign papers and paraphernalia from five decades of New 
Hampshire primaries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
