<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 23:40:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Elton Brand's Journey to the NBA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEERFIELD, Ill. (AP) -- With the NBA draft just a few hours away,  
Elton Brand and Ron Artest couldn't sleep. They wandered the 
hallways of their hotel, passing each other countless times as they 
paced. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, the old AAU buddies sat down and started talking. They  
reminisced about the old days, when they practiced in the basement 
of the Riverside Church in a gym so small, guys ran into walls on a 
regular basis. They recalled that summer of their junior year in 
high school, when their AAU team went an incredible 64-1. 
</P>
<P>
	And they talked about how far they've come, Artest from a rough  
neighborhood in New York City, Brand from Peekskill, N.Y. Making it 
to the NBA was amazing enough. The thought of playing on the same 
team was just too incredible to even consider. 
</P>
<P>
	Well, well, well, look who's together again.  
</P>
<P>
	``That brought tears to my eyes. When they said Chicago Bulls, I  
thought, `I'm back with Elton again,''' Artest said Thursday, the 
day after he was drafted 16th by the Bulls in the first round. ``I 
just feel right at home. If I've got a problem, I can just talk to 
E.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not only is being together good for them, Brand said it will be  
good for the Chicago Bulls. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know each other's games,'' said Brand, the No. 1 pick.  
``Ron's a great player and he's going to work very hard. He's going 
to push me, and I'm going to push him. We also have Michael Ruffin 
and I know he can play, also. So I think we've got a great start so 
far.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When it comes to rebuilding Chicago's shattered dynasty, though,  
everything begins with Brand. As a sophomore at Duke, he averaged 
16.2 points and 9.8 rebounds as the Blue Devils rolled through the 
ACC season to the NCAA championship game. He's 6-foot-8 and 275 
pounds, and his arm span is wider than some small planes. 
</P>
<P>
	He's also got the biggest, softest hands general manager Jerry  
Krause has ever seen. 
</P>
<P>
	But that's not all. Brand said there's plenty else he can do  
that he just never got to show at Duke. Like his short-range jumper 
and his perimeter game. His body, too. Though he's already as solid 
as an oak tree, he's never really been on a serious weight lifting 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm definitely going to improve, athletically and  
physically,'' he said. ``I'm very eager to get in here and just get 
started. I'm looking forward to the great experience that's going 
to come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So are the Bulls. When Michael Jordan retired, Scottie Pippen  
went to Houston and Dennis Rodman left on yet another wild 
adventure, Chicago went from six-time champions to the cellar on an 
express elevator. The Bulls' 13-37 record was third-worst in the 
NBA and the worst in franchise history. 
</P>
<P>
	Krause was looking for building blocks in this draft, and he got  
a big one in Brand. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's going to be a leader in this league,'' Krause said. ``We  
think he has the special qualities we need, especially at the 
position he's going to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brand is well aware of how big the expectations are for him. All  
he has to do is look around the Bulls' practice facility and see 
those six gold trophies gleaming in the case. Or look up to the 
ceiling and see the championship banners. 
</P>
<P>
	It's kind of like when he first arrived at Duke -- though he said  
he thinks the Bulls have a few more banners than the Blue Devils. 
</P>
<P>
	``Down the road there's going to be a lot of pressures with  
fulfilling everyone's expectations of the No. 1 pick. Especially 
coming to a team like the Bulls with the great tradition and 
heritage and championships,'' Brand said. ``It's going to be a lot 
of pressure, but I think I can face that pressure and perform very 
well. 
</P>
<P>
	``At every level, I've had to face pressure and criticism and  
such, but I always prevailed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It hasn't been an easy road for Brand, either. His mother,  
Daisy, can't remember a summer her son took off. While his friends 
were hanging out at home, Brand was always traveling somewhere for 
a tournament or a game. 
</P>
<P>
	He once played on an AAU team in Albany, N.Y., a two-hour trip  
from his home in Peekskill. That was too far a trip to make for 
practice, so Brand just showed up for the games. 
</P>
<P>
	When he joined the Riverside AAU team, it meant a 45-minute  
train ride each way, and he made the trip at least three or four 
times a week for practices and games. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I got the express train, maybe four stops. If not, maybe 20  
stops,'' he said, smiling. ``But it was worth it. Definitely worth 
it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
