<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clapton Concert Raises Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The concert was billed as Eric Clapton and  
Friends, and for 3 1/2 hours, Clapton, David Sanborn, Sheryl Crow, 
Mary J. Blige and Bob Dylan gave the crowd what they wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no warm-up band, no fancy set, no special effects  
inside Madison Square Garden on Wednesday night, just a half-dozen 
or so musicians on a flat white stage, playing what amounted to a 
pleasing string of greatest hits. 
</P>
<P>
	Clapton played a mix of old and new. At times his music was  
sweet with pure and shimmering notes that dripped from his fingers. 
Other songs washed the audience with waves of anguished riffs. 
</P>
<P>
	He started with songs like ``Hoochie Coochie Man,'' ``Change the  
World,'' ``River of Tears,'' ``Wonderful Tonight,'' ``Tears in 
Heaven,'' and ``Old Love.'' Then 2 1/2 hours into the show, just as 
the crowd was starting to wonder if he might not play it, he let 
rip with his signature ``Layla.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The surprise of the evening was the appearance of Sanborn, who  
hadn't been named as a guest. He was brought on early and played 
through most of the concert, showing that he can do for the sax 
what Clapton can do for the guitar. His masterful skill during a 
rendition of ``Little Wing'' clearly delighted Clapton and Crow. 
</P>
<P>
	And so it was, friends on stage. At times Clapton took center  
stage. Just as often, he stepped back, away from the microphone and 
played his guitar. As Crow quipped, ``It isn't bad having Eric on 
back-up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This was not an evening for egos. At various points, Clapton  
shared the microphone with Crow and Dylan. He and Dylan sang 
``Crossroads,'' but not ``All Along the Watchtower. And the entire 
entourage, minus Blige who didn't reappear for the encore, ended 
the show by singing ``Bright Lights, Big City.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The sold-out concert, with tickets priced from $35 to $250, was  
to raise money for the Crossroads Centre, a residential drug and 
alcohol treatment facility founded in 1997 on the island of Antigua 
by Clapton, who has himself fought drug and alcohol addiction. 
</P>
<P>
	The concert will be shown on cable station VH1 on July 27.  
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Clapton raised more than $5 million for the center by  
auctioning 100 guitars. A spokeswoman for Clapton said she didn't 
have an immediate tally of how much the concert raised. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
