<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 15:06:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Construction Spending Down 0.9 Pct. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The nation's manufacturing sector expanded for  
the fifth straight month in June, and at a stronger pace than 
expected, according to a survey of corporate purchasing managers 
released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Growth in new orders at the nation's factories indicated the  
upward trend will continue. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both production and new orders exhibited significant growth  
when compared to May,'' said Norbert J. Ore, head of the National 
Association of Purchasing Management's survey committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The report is watched closely because it gives economists --  
including Federal Reserve officials -- the first reading on how the 
manufacturing sector and, in turn, the overall economy, fared in 
the previous month. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, meanwhile, the Commerce Department reported  
construction spending fell in May for a second straight month. That 
indicated that one of the economy's strongest sectors is starting 
to slow, in part because mortgage rates have been rising. 
</P>
<P>
	The report said spending dropped 0.9 percent in May after  
falling 2 percent in April. Decreases were reported in 
single-family homes, apartment buildings, hotels and motels as well 
as in big government construction projects, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a second report, the Labor Department said the number of  
Americans filing new claims for unemployment benefits dropped last 
week. It said 299,000 people filed claims, some 5,000 fewer than in 
the previous week and an indication that the labor market remains 
exceptionally tight. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchasing managers report sent the bond market falling and  
pushed the yield on the Treasury's 30-year bond up to 6.00 percent 
from late Wednesday's 5.96 as investors feared that the Fed, which 
raised interest rates modestly on Wednesday, might use further 
increases to slow the economy's growth and inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	But the stock market shrugged off the report and the bond  
market's response, and the Dow Jones industrial average was up 81 
points at the 11,052 level in late afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	The purchasing managers' survey indicated that 16 of 20  
industries reported a pickup in business last month. 
</P>
<P>
	The trade group's monthly index of business activity rose to 57  
percent in June from 55.2 percent in May, a much stronger showing 
than the 54.4 percent analysts expected. 
</P>
<P>
	A reading above 50 percent in the index indicates the  
manufacturing economy is expanding. The index has been climbing 
since a prolonged downturn ended in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Bryan Jordan, an economic analyst at Banc One Investment  
Advisors in Columbus, Ohio, said the latest report showed 
``manufacturing recovering quite nicely so far'' after a weak 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that the trend should continue ``as long as the global  
economy continues to come back'' from the crisis sparked by the 
collapse of Asian currencies in summer of 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Thayer, chief economist at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St.  
Louis, said the report signaled ``there's still a very healthy 
economy ... without any real problems in the pipeline.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A majority of the purchasing managers surveyed said new orders  
were stronger or remained at May levels, and just 13 percent said 
they were lower. The index for new orders rose to 61.7 percent in 
June -- its highest level in two years -- from 58.9 percent in May. 
</P>
<P>
	The backlog of orders increased for the fourth consecutive  
month, but not as strongly as in May, the report showed. The index 
was 54.5 percent in June versus 55.5 in May. 
</P>
<P>
	The NAPM said its price index reached 53.5 percent in June,  
rising above the 50 percent mark for the second consecutive month 
and indicating that the cost of raw materials continues to rise. 
</P>
<P>
	The price index had risen to 52.2 percent in May, marking the  
first time since December 1997 that manufacturers indicated they 
were paying higher prices for raw materials. 
</P>
<P>
	The NAPM represents executives who buy raw materials and  
supplies for manufacturers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
