<HEADLINE> Kennedy Center Gets Grant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Performances past and future will benefit from  
$4 million in grants to the Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts 
and the Library of Congress, made by the Doris Duke Charitable 
Foundation in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Of $3 million for the Kennedy Center, $2 million will go to its  
Millennium Endowment Fund to help organize international festivals. 
The grant is to be matched by other contributors over three years. 
The other $1 million will support festivals dealing this year with 
Africa, next year with Ireland and in 2001 with Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	An additional $1 million, it was announced Tuesday, will go to  
the Library of Congress over two years so it can create an archive 
on the work of Martha Graham. She was a leading creator and 
performer of American dance who died in 1991 at age 96. The library 
will buy a collection of her papers concerning her career of more 
than 65 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The money also will commission the Martha Graham Company to  
reconstruct five of her works for presentation and video 
productions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
