<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Sports Getting TV Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Who needs Tim Duncan or Brett Hull? This is the weekend of women  
in sports. 
</P>
<P>
	With the NBA and NHL seasons finished, the Wimbledon women, the  
Women's World Cup and the WNBA are taking over. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the All London Club still refuses to pay women equal  
prize money, viewers have been watching them more than the men in 
eight of the last nine tennis majors. 
</P>
<P>
	Don't expect that trend to change this year, even with Andre  
Agassi and Pete Sampras advancing deep into the tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Not with American Alexandra Stevenson and 16-year-old Australian  
Jelena Dokic getting most of the attention so far and American 
Lindsay Davenport breezing into the semifinals. There's also a pair 
of World Cup matches on ESPN on Sunday and a WNBA game Saturday 
afternoon on NBC. 
</P>
<P>
	They don't have to worry much about the competition -- the X  
Games and some lesser-known golf tournaments. 
</P>
<P>
	The Women's World Cup hasn't enjoyed the same level of success  
on television as it has with attendance, but its TV ratings still 
have been better than for regular-season NHL games. 
</P>
<P>
	Then again, that's nothing to brag about.  
</P>
<P>
	``Women's sports are still difficult to succeed on weekend  
afternoons because it's so crowded and traditionally it's been the 
man controlling the remote,'' said Rob Correa, vice president of 
programming at CBS. ``You need to grow a core audience with weekday 
cable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, women's sports must be doing something right: They are  
forcing television networks to change their programming. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC sports chairman Dick Ebersol has said he will show women's  
basketball, softball and soccer in its entirety at the Sydney 
Olympics. CBS will switch the women's final to the premier time 
slot for the U.S. Open tennis tournament, instead of sandwiching it 
between a pair of men's semifinals as it has done in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	And HBO, in its final year of broadcasting Wimbledon, devoted an  
unprecedented 70 percent of its coverage to women. 
</P>
<P>
	With the sudden exposure and engaging role models such as Anna  
Kournikova, Mia Hamm and Chamique Holdsclaw, girls growing up have 
a different outlook on female athletes nowadays. 
</P>
<P>
	``These girls now want to grow up and be athletes,'' said NBC  
analyst and three-time Wimbledon champion Chris Evert. ``There are 
attractive, appealing girls out there and now they realize that's 
it is OK to run around and sweat and be tough. Twenty years ago it 
was frowned upon and wasn't feminine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But just because women's sports has made it on network  
television doesn't mean it will stay. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's still too early to tell, but women's sports could be the  
next big thing,'' said media buyer Ron Frederick of the J. Walter 
Thompson agency. ``I've been a big skeptic of soccer, but I'm not 
as skeptical about this event.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *OVERDUE:* It may be a year late, but CBS will finally air the  
first live network prime-time motorsports race. 
</P>
<P>
	Wildfires in Florida spoiled the network's plan to televise  
NASCAR's Pepsi 400 last summer and the race was moved to TNN last 
October. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS intends to give it another try on Saturday at 8 p.m. EDT.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is uncharted territory and we are confident that a  
prime-time race on CBS is going to draw viewers to their 
television,'' said Rob Correa, CBS vice president of programming. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you'll see a few more prime-time races on national TV,  
but I don't think you'll see a mad rush to Saturday night racing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DOUBLE DUTY:* Tim McCarver will work a doubleheader on Saturday  
-- from different stadiums -- and it won't be an easy task. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fox analyst will broadcast the national game between the New  
York Mets and Atlanta Braves at Shea Stadium, which begins at 1 
p.m. EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	Hopefully it will be a low-scoring affair, because he'll need to  
get across the city to the Bronx in time for the Yankees-Orioles 
4:30 p.m. game on Fox's local cable telecast. 
</P>
<P>
	And there won't be any private jet or police escort, either.  
He'll have to battle the traffic like the rest of us. 
</P>
<P>
	McCarver will work four games this weekend in a 48-hour span,  
beginning with the Yankees game Friday night and ending with the 
Yanks game Sunday afternoon 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TUBE BITS:* Fox Sports Net will add a one-hour NFL pregame  
show, called ``NFL This Morning,'' with hosts Chris Myers and 
Jackie Slater. It debuts Sept. 12. ... ... ABC televises the Tour 
de France for the 11th year beginning Saturday at 3 p.m. EDT. ... 
UPN's new hockey comedy series ``Power Play'' lasted just two weeks 
in the United States after a successful run in Canada. ... TNN has 
reached a three-year agreement with Extreme Championship Wrestling 
to televise a weekly, hour-long wrestling series beginning in 
August. ... Former Cleveland Cavs coach Mike Fratello has been 
mentioned as a possible candidate to return to NBC or fill Doc 
Rivers' spot at Turner. NBC is looking for a broadcast partner for 
Marv Albert, who was rehired Tuesday, and the pair worked together 
at NBC. 
  	   	
</P>
