<DOCNO> APW19990701.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 12:40:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Retailers Look to Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Angelica Legaspi Lofgren's gut feeling told her  
importing Iranian caviar at the depths of Hong Kong's recession 
would be a tricky venture. 
</P>
<P>
	But she quit her cushy job at Deutsche Bank anyway and bought an  
importing company, Tenderloin Fine Food. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, she and her husband are selling the finest oscietra caviar  
-- at $1.20 a gram -- along with Scottish salmon, Australian 
lobsters, corn-fed American beef and gourmet chocolates to Hong 
Kong's well-heeled. 
</P>
<P>
	``People want to make sure their families are fed well and will  
pay a lot for that,'' Lofgren said, displaying the gung-ho 
swashbuckle that marked her 17 years as a foreign currency trader. 
</P>
<P>
	But with Hong Kong stuck in recession two years after Asia's  
economic crisis hit, sales of fancy food and other luxuries just 
aren't what they were back in the boom times, when people wined and 
dined in a carefree whirl of affluence. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many people still don't want to be seen eating caviar while  
their friends are having a hard time,'' Lofgren said, picking out 
morsels of imported chocolate in her small shop at a local gourmet 
supermarket. 
</P>
<P>
	Back when Hong Kong's stock and property markets were surging  
toward what seemed like an endless series of new heights, one 
upscale auto dealer recalls selling six cars -- all Rolls-Royce and 
Bentleys -- to just one customer. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past three months, Spenser Lam, general sales manager at  
MD Motors, the territory's sole distributor of the handmade English 
luxury models, said he has sold only ``a few.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No doubt, Hong Kong has had to cut back on its self-indulgence.  
Unemployment is at a record 6.3 percent. The economy has fallen for 
15 months in a row. And consumer prices have slid the past seven 
months in the spooky phenomenon known as deflation. 
</P>
<P>
	While property values have stabilized, they are down as much as  
50 percent since the crisis swept Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	But recently, pools of cash have been flowing into Hong Kong's  
financial markets from investors betting the economy is ready for a 
rebound. The blue-chip Hang Seng stock index recently hit 14,000, a 
level unseen since October 1997, when Asia's currency crisis was 
unfolding. 
</P>
<P>
	The surge has retailers of high-price, high-status merchandise  
hopeful that Hong Kong residents will soon step up their buying. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will take time before people start spending in the high  
luxury sector,'' said Lam. ``But soon we'll be flying again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not so fast, some economists caution. Whether the rise in blue  
chip stocks is just a brief spurt of optimism or a wider resurgence 
throughout the broader economy is not yet possible to judge, they 
say. 
</P>
<P>
	``That we have bottomed out is a fair point for one reason: We  
are full of capital in Asia,'' said Guonan Ma, an economist with 
Merrill Lynch. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock market's rally has shored up what Ma sees as the  
critical intangible that has eluded Hong Kong for many months: 
confidence. 
</P>
<P>
	But retailers are being hurt by other factors. Cheap goods over  
the border in Shenzhen, China, are tempting more and more Hong Kong 
residents to shop there -- a habit that may cost the territory's 
retailers as much as 20 percent of their earnings this year, Ma 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the signs of a fledgling recovery underpin the hopes of  
bullish entrepreneurs like wine importer Paolo Durazzo. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once you're down, the only way to go is up,'' said Durazzo,  
whose 2-year-old company, Casamia, has been breaking even at best. 
</P>
<P>
	At his booth during a recent food fair, Durazzo offered a  
Gramole Barrique 1995 red wine from Tuscany. Many visitors sipped a 
free glass, then looked at the $31 price tag, smiled politely and 
left. 
</P>
<P>
	``People will start buying again ... you'll see,'' Durazzo said.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
