<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Holbrooke Nomination Faces Hurdles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Richard Holbrooke's marathon nomination to be  
U.N. ambassador is facing new hurdles, even after a unanimous 
endorsement by a Senate committee. But the U.S. diplomat who's been 
standing in for Holbrooke in New York today called the committee 
action ``very good news.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the United Nations, Deputy Ambassador Peter Burleigh told  
reporters he remained optimistic that the Senate would confirm the 
nomination by week's end. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll just have to wait and see,'' he told a news conference.  
</P>
<P>
	Holbrooke's supporters in Washington were a little less  
optimistic after new objections to the career's diplomat's 
nomination surfaced. 
</P>
<P>
	Burleigh has served as acting U.N. ambassador since Bill  
Richardson left the post last fall to take over as energy 
secretary. Burleigh has been nominated to be U.S. ambassador to the 
Philippines and the Palau Islands in the western Pacific. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Senate approves Holbrooke's nomination, Burleigh said, he  
will remain at the United Nations until the end of August. If the 
Senate doesn't vote immediately, he said, ``I will stay here until 
Dick Holbrooke arrives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Czwartacki, a spokesman for Senate Majority Leader Trent  
Lott, R-Miss., said late Wednesday that more senators had signaled 
their intent to block the nomination from coming to a floor vote in 
the coming days. 
</P>
<P>
	That is in addition to a ``hold'' put on the nomination by Sen.  
Charles Grassley over an unrelated civil service dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	Grassley is protesting a State Department decision to transfer a  
senior staff member from a U.N. office in New York to a lesser post 
in Washington after she informed members of Congress about alleged 
waste and mismanagement within the United Nations. He contends the 
transfer and demotion violated a law that he sponsored protecting 
whistle-blowers. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview, Grassley said the civil servant, Linda  
Shenwick, should be restored to her former job as a budget and 
administrative officer at the U.S. mission to the U.N. in New York. 
But he said he would settle for a ``mutually acceptable'' agreement 
between Ms. Shenwick and the State Department. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we can work this out by the end of the week if the  
State Department wants to,'' Grassley said. 
</P>
<P>
	The State Department denies that it singled out Ms. Shenwick for  
punishment, but says the matter is under investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, other senators have come forth and put holds on the  
nomination, Czwartacki said. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike Grassley, who made his intentions known publicly, these  
senators did so anonymously, which is allowed under Senate 
tradition. 
</P>
<P>
	Czwartacki said he did not know who the senators were or whether  
their concerns were identical to Grassley's. 
</P>
<P>
	But their objections to moving ahead this week with the  
nomination appeared ``irreconcilable.'' Czwartacki did say the 
situation could change quickly. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
