<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> HBO Studies Art and Mentally Ill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``The Living Museum,'' a documentary about  
art and the mentally ill, challenges our perceptions about both. 
</P>
<P>
	Director Jessica Yu, an Academy Award winner for her short film,  
``Breathing Lessons,'' takes an admiring but unromanticized look at 
six artist-patients who do their work in a secluded corner of a 
monolithic New York state mental hospital. 
</P>
<P>
	The result, on HBO at 7:30 p.m. EDT Tuesday, July 6, is a film  
infused with the hope and pain of its subjects and the vitality, 
wit and sadness of their creations. 
</P>
<P>
	Their art stands on its own, bold and perceptive and, certainly,  
individualistic. This is not basket-weaving therapy we're talking 
here. The artists, some of whom discovered their talent after 
becoming ill, also evade stereotype. 
</P>
<P>
	There's Issa Ibrahim, articulate and handsome and sentenced to  
an indeterminate stay at Creedmoor Psychiatric Center in Queens, 
N.Y., for crimes he refers to only obliquely. He draws on history, 
including his own, to create statements on race, freedom and 
deliverance. 
</P>
<P>
	David Waldorf is a skilled painter who crafts delicately  
abstract images with inspiration from Beethoven's music created in 
his later, deaf years. Waldorf finds his own severe episodes of 
illness profoundly inspiring as well. 
</P>
<P>
	On the street, he says, he sees ``these great movements of  
people. Somehow, I feel the very flight of life itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Art is a bridge between the mentally ill and the world, Waldorf  
says. His own pieces provide a kind of Rorschach test for the 
viewer, forced to consider what they are willing to see, or admit 
to seeing, in drawings born of brilliance and instability. 
</P>
<P>
	Helen Sadowski, who studied at the Philadelphia College of Art,  
tells a wrenching story of depression, attempted suicide and 
estrangement from family members she says blame her for her 
illness. 
</P>
<P>
	Sadowski's paintings, in counterpoint to her chaotic life, rely  
on carefully controlled lines and blocks of pastel color. 
</P>
<P>
	``Her work represents beauty and nothing but beauty ... and that  
works for her,'' Dr. Janos Marton, who helped establish the Living 
Museum at Creedmoor and is its director, says in the film. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Marton, The program is open to any patient at  
Creedmoor and ``is not art therapy, it's just art,'' although it 
can have a therapeutic effect. 
</P>
<P>
	Marton is our guide through the museum and a key part of the  
documentary. His appreciation for his patients' unrestrained 
talents, his gentle regard for their well-being, and his joy in his 
own work are a pleasure to behold. 
</P>
<P>
	So is the film, which takes an unhackneyed approach to its  
subject. There's none of the atonal music often clumsily used to 
``evoke'' mental illness, and the artwork is shot with the same 
care and respect accorded those who created it. 
</P>
<P>
	It took a single visit to the Living Museum for Yu to decide it  
was a place and people worth spending time around. 
</P>
<P>
	``As soon as I walked in there, I was so overwhelmed by the  
art,'' she said in an interview. ``From the outside, it looks like 
the other buildings at Creedmoor ... but there's a really relaxed 
feeling in the place having to do with the people. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a feeling it is their place, and in any institution  
that's a really rare feeling,'' she said. She was also intrigued by 
the artists, especially Waldorf, who tried to explain why he would 
not trade his life for one of normality. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have to know how this person came to this point,'' Yu  
recalls thinking. 
</P>
<P>
	The filmmaker spent a year filming at the museum, choosing to  
string her visits out gradually over 1997 so that the artists (who 
include both in- and outpatients) could become comfortable with her 
and her crew. 
</P>
<P>
	``The main thing is that people get a sense of them as people as  
well as residents of Creedmoor,'' Yu said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other profiled artists are John Tursi, John C. Mapp and a woman  
identified as Eileen, the most severely disturbed patient. Although 
Eileen can be disruptive, the other patients generously agreed she 
should be allowed to work with them in the museum. 
</P>
<P>
	That spirit of cooperation infuses the art program.  
</P>
<P>
	``Creedmoor is really supportive of the Living Museum and that's  
unusual,'' said Yu. ``Dr. Marton is unusual, the whole existence of 
this place is unusual. You hope other hospitals are inspired to do 
this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Art shows the ``trial and error'' of life, and therefore belongs  
as much with those inside the hospital as those outside, Marton 
contends. ``I have this true belief that anyone can be an artist.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ....  
</P>
<P>
	DEFIANT DOCUMENT: The story of the Declaration of Independence  
and the fate of the original and its copies are detailed in ``Save 
Our History: The Declaration of Independence,'' showing 9 p.m. EDT 
Saturday (July 3) on the History Channel. Experts discuss the 
debate over the statement, its language and influence and what the 
faded version in the National Archives represents (it's neither the 
original or the oldest copy, according to the program). 
</P>
<P>
	Lynn Elber can be reached at lelber''at''ap.org  
  	   	
</P>
