<HEADLINE> Coroner Rules on Missing Sailors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Briton Glyn Charles and Australian John  
Dean were declared dead by a coroner Friday, six months after they 
were swept away by mountainous seas in the Sydney to Hobart yacht 
race. 
</P>
<P>
	The bodies of the two men were never found, unlike four other  
Australians who died in the race. 
</P>
<P>
	New South Wales state deputy coroner John Abernethy said he was  
satisfied all the sailors had died in the Tasman Sea even though 
the two bodies had not been recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	Abernethy adjourned the inquest for a month-long hearing in  
November. In the meantime he said, tests would be conducted at the 
Australian Maritime College in Launceston to investigate the 
stability of vessels and life rafts. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 115 yachts in the race, 70 boats withdrew because of the  
hurricane-strength winds. Seven boats were abandoned or sank. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
