<DOCNO> APW19990701.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 11:10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Time To Name That Olympic Mascot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Organizers of the 2002 Winter Games will  
use the Internet and a toll-free phone line in a national naming 
contest for the three Olympic mascots, a rabbit, coyote and bear. 
</P>
<P>
	The Salt Lake Organizing Committee launched its national ``Three  
Names for the Games'' contest Wednesday. The animals, which figure 
into western Indian myth and were chosen to reflect the Olympic 
motto of swifter, higher and stronger, debuted in May. 
</P>
<P>
	There are two methods of voting: via the Internet at  
www.slc2002.org or by calling a toll-free number, (877) 3MASCOTS. 
Participants, who will be asked for a name, address and phone 
number, will be eligible for prizes from Olympic sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	The contest runs through July. Voters will cast ballots for one  
set of three names. The winning names will be announced in 
September. 
</P>
<P>
	After taking suggestions from 42,000 school children in 1,400  
classrooms, the committee winnowed the list of possible names to 
nine and grouped those into three sets of names. Of the nine, five 
names came from students -- Copper, Cliff, Shadow, Arrow and Bolt. 
</P>
<P>
	At a press conference announcing the contest on Wednesday, three  
youngsters became the first to vote for mascot names via the Web. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell Aivazian, a student at Alta View Elementary in Sandy,  
and Todd Lehman, a student at Evergreen Junior High in Holladay, 
both voted for the names under Option 2: Sky, Cliff and Shadow. 
They said the names conjure up images of Utah. 
</P>
<P>
	Cindi Arko, who attends Columbia Elementary School in West  
Jordan, picked Option 3: Arrow, Bolt and Rocky. 
</P>
<P>
	``They just sounded cool to me,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Option 1 names include Powder, Copper and Coal.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
