<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise in Midday Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks touched a 21-month high early  
Friday after a gain on Wall Street. The dollar edged higher against 
the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 91.68 points,  
or 0.51 percent, to 17,952.43 points at the end of the morning 
session. On Thursday, the average closed up 331.01 points, or 1.89 
percent -- the market's highest close since Sept. 30, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point Friday morning, the Nikkei briefly passed the  
18,000-point mark for the first time since September 1997, rising 
as high as 18,066 before falling back on profit taking, traders 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.86 yen, up 0.10 yen from late Thursday in  
Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 120.78 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, the rise on Wall Street as well as hope for  
an economic recovery in Japan boosted prices, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The rise in share prices is likely to accelerate,'' said  
Sachio Ishikawa, general manager of the stock division at Chuo 
Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average posted its fourth  
consecutive gain, rising 95.62 points to 11,066.42 at Thursday's 
close. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said some investors are exercising caution while  
awaiting the results of the Bank of Japan's quarterly ``tankan'' 
survey of business sentiment, due out Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	But major private sector think tanks and research institutes are  
forecasting a significant improvement in the survey results, the 
Nihon Keizai newspaper reported Friday. There is increasing 
sentiment ``that the tankan won't be bad,'' Ishikawa said. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's government spokesman welcomed the rise in share prices.  
</P>
<P>
	``Confidence in our country's economy is being reflected in  
stocks, and I am happy about it,'' Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu 
Nonaka said at a regular news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
exchange's first section rose 16.43 points, or 1.14 percent, to 
1,463.84. The TOPIX posted a 31.21-point gain, or 2.20 percent, the 
day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar moved in a narrow range amid  
worries that Japanese monetary authorities may intervene in some 
form Friday, to support the euro against the yen, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	To underscore such fears, Japan's Vice Finance Minister for  
International Affairs Eisuke Sakakibara said early Friday that 
euro-yen trading was moving rapidly. 
</P>
<P>
	Sakakibara, who is leaving his post, added that authorities were  
``monitoring'' the situation. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro dropped to a new low against the dollar in New York on  
Thursday. It was quoted at $1.0229, down from $1.0338 Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, it was traded at 123.82 yen, down from 125.04 yen late  
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell to 1.700  
percent from Thursday's finish of 1.7400 percent, driving its price 
up to 100.86 yen from 100.51 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
