<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U S West To Discuss Qwest Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- U S West Inc., the Denver-based Baby Bell phone  
company at the heart of a three-week takeover battle, said it will 
explore a $34.7 billion offer from Qwest Communications 
International Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	U S West's decision Thursday follows a similar move Monday by  
Frontier Corp., the fifth-largest long-distance company, which is 
weighing a $11.8 billion takeover bid from Denver-based Qwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, however, both U S West and Frontier have merger  
agreements with Global Crossing Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
	But on Thursday Global Crossing gave U S West permission to  
provide information to Qwest so that they can discuss the rival 
offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Sol Trujillo, U S West chairman, president and CEO said in a  
statement, ``The Board remains committed to acting in the best 
interests of U S West shareholders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Global Crossing and Qwest are building worldwide networks to  
carry high-speed Internet traffic. They are fighting for U S West 
and Frontier in order to secure the customers and sales to drive 
their business plans. 
</P>
<P>
	This is just the latest in a series of recent bidding wars in  
the communications industry. In May, AT&AMP;T Corp., the nation's 
largest long-distance company, won a bidding war against Comcast 
Corp. for MediaOne, a large cable company. And in Europe, upstart 
Olivetti SpA won a fight with Deutsche Telekom for control of 
Telecom Italia SpA. 
</P>
<P>
	Behind the aggressive offers is a sea change in technology,  
which is forcing telephone, cable TV and computer companies to 
offer many of the same services. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest chairman and CEO Joseph P. Nacchio said the company hopes  
to begin discussions with U S West as soon as possible. 
</P>
<P>
	``We firmly believe a combination of U S West and Qwest will  
significantly benefit the shareholders, customers and employees of 
each of our companies,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Global Crossing, based in Bermuda, offered $10.9 billion in cash  
and stock for Rochester, N.Y.-based Frontier and about $31 billion 
in stock for U S West. The deal with U S West, however, hangs on 
the success of the Frontier acquisition. If Frontier backs out, it 
could scuttle Global Crossing's plans to buy U S West. 
</P>
<P>
	If Qwest is the victor, Frontier and U S West would have to pay  
about $1 billion in breakup fees to Global Crossing. 
</P>
<P>
	U S West's announcement came after the markets closed. The  
company's stock ended the day unchanged at $58.75 on the New York 
Stock Exchange, where Frontier's shares rose 31 1/4 cents to $58.93 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Qwest's stock rose 31 1/4 cents to $33.37 1/2 on the Nasdaq Stock  
Market, where Global Crossing's shares fell $2.65 1/4 to $40. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
