<HEADLINE> Texas Killer Executed for '95 Murder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- A former construction worker who  
clubbed a woman to death and stuffed her body in a closet while 
robbing her home was executed on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Daniel Tuttle, who turned 35 last Saturday, refused to  
allow his attorneys to file appeals on his behalf. He was the 15th 
prisoner to be executed in Texas this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuttle turned his head toward members of the victim's family,  
who watched through a window, and apologized for the killing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope my dropping my appeals has in some way began your  
healing process. This is all I can do to help you out in any way 
for the nightmare and pain that I have caused you,'' Tuttle said 
before being given a lethal injection. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am truly sorry and I wish I could take back what I did, but  
I can't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cathy Harris, 42, was beaten with a claw hammer in February  
1995. Her body was wrapped in blankets and squeezed into a closet 
in her trailer home. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuttle, a friend of her nephew's, had been staying with her but  
had been asked to leave because he was not paying his share of the 
bills. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuttle told police when he was arrested four days after the  
killing that he had been high on drugs and only wanted to knock her 
out ``like you see on TV'' to steal from her. 
</P>
<P>
	``She started screaming and I lost it,'' he told police.  
</P>
<P>
	Tuttle took Harris' pickup truck, her credit cards and her  
.357-caliber Magnum revolver. 
</P>
<P>
	In a conversation early on the day of the murder, Tuttle told  
Harris' nephew he had watched the movie ``Natural Born Killers'' 
three times the previous day. The 1994 film is about the media's 
glorification of a pair of serial killers. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
