<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unfunny `Taming of the Shrew' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ``Clobber Me, Kate.''  
</P>
<P>
	That could be the new title for the frantic, physical and mostly  
unfunny revival of ``The Taming of the Shrew'' that the Public 
Theater is presenting as its inaugural attraction in Central Park 
this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite all the furious fisticuffs, not much seems to work in  
this hodgepodge production, starting with the crucial casting of 
Kate and Petruchio, the battling would-be lovers of Shakespeare's 
venerable comedy. 
</P>
<P>
	Jay O. Sanders' Petruchio is all hale and hearty, beefy and  
blustery but without much magnetism. One wonders what Kate finally 
sees in this dull Verona jock, who at one point in the proceedings 
dons wrestling tights. 
</P>
<P>
	Allison Janney's Kate looks a bit like a young, schoolmarmish  
Katharine Hepburn, maybe because she wears spectacles and pins her 
hair in a bun. 
</P>
<P>
	Janney is a fine actress able to handle comedy and drama, as  
anybody knows who saw her in the movie ``The Object of My 
Affection'' or on stage in the Broadway revival of ``A View from 
the Bridge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the woman has been given minimal guidance from director Mel  
Shapiro who has her bellowing and barging all over the Delacorte 
stage as if she were a banshee. Janney is much too intelligent a 
performer for all that yelling. Her screeching companionship surely 
would test not only Petruchio but just about everyone else within 
earshot. 
</P>
<P>
	Shapiro has opted to do a more complete ``Shrew'' than usual,  
leaving in the extensive opening scenes involving drunken tinker 
Christopher Sly, played by the reliable comic, Max Wright. Often 
these moments are cut, and you can see why. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright's fussing and fuming produce scattered laughs as he sets  
up the story as a play-within-a-play. The meeting, turbulent wooing 
and eventual winning of Kate is watched from the sidelines by Sly, 
who at one point is recruited to portray a minor character in the 
action. 
</P>
<P>
	If the leads make scant impressions, so do most of the  
supporting players. A romantic subplot involving Kate's sister, 
Bianca, and a young gentleman, Lucentio, fritters away much of the 
evening. The comedy is as labored as it is long, wasting several 
veteran performers including MacIntyre Dixon and Tom Mardirosian. 
</P>
<P>
	One bright spot is Mario Cantone, who plays Grumio, grumbling  
servant to Petruchio. Cantone creates a larger-than-life character, 
cartoonish to be sure, but as vivid and colorful as Marina 
Draghici's eye-catching costumes. 
</P>
<P>
	Karl Eigsti's setting is vaguely Italian, white or  
pastel-colored Mediterranean buildings that are nicely set off by 
the backdrop of lush park greenery, 
</P>
<P>
	One measure of the production's misplaced boisterousness is the  
periodic appearance of four singing and dancing monks. Their 
musical outbursts -- in Italian -- get English subtitles on screens 
placed on each side of the wide stage. The men even get a big 11 
o'clock number -- well, more like 10:30 p.m. song -- in which they 
seem to be imitating one of the Public Theater's better-known shows 
-- '' A Chorus Line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If anything, the silly moment makes one anticipate the November  
arrival on Broadway of ``Kiss Me, Kate,'' the Cole Porter musical 
based on ``Shrew.'' Porter's terrific songs should at least provide 
the buoyancy that this earthbound production sorely lacks. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
