<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Abortion Foes Targeting Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Abortion opponents will look to the Senate to  
do this year what it could not accomplish last year: send the White 
House a bill that would make it more difficult for a minor to 
terminate a pregnancy by going to another state. 
</P>
<P>
	House lawmakers voted 270-159 Wednesday in favor of new  
restrictions on abortions by teens. The bill would penalize anyone 
who helps a minor avoid parental involvement laws by going to 
another state for an abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	But the tally fell short of the two-thirds majority, or 286  
votes, that would be needed to overturn a threatened veto by 
President Clinton. Voting in favor were 206 Republicans and 64 
Democrats; voting against were 14 Republicans, 144 Democrats and 
one independent. 
</P>
<P>
	The House passed a similar bill last year, but it failed to  
reach the Senate floor after getting caught up in the end-of-year 
crush of legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Abortion opponents are hoping the Senate will act earlier this  
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Right to Life Committee, which lists the bill as a  
top legislative priority, said a majority of the 100 senators 
support the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	It is pending in the Senate Judiciary Committee, which has yet  
to act. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., who  
supported the bill last year, did not return a telephone call 
Wednesday for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Abortion rights advocates predicted the Senate will pass the  
bill, given next year's elections. But they also are assured of 
Clinton's veto. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am hopeful that at least enough senators will understand the  
danger of this kind of legislation to young women who are in 
crisis, to family members who may need to help these women and to 
the Constitution,'' said Kate Michelman, president of the National 
Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action League. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill makes it a crime for anyone other than a parent,  
guardian or legal custodian to evade parental involvement laws by 
taking a minor to another state for an abortion. It would not apply 
if the abortion was needed to save the girl's life. 
</P>
<P>
	Violators face penalties of up to a year in jail and $100,000 in  
fines, and parents whose daughters had abortions could pursue civil 
remedies. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 30 states have laws that require the notification or  
consent of at least one parent for a minor's abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of the bill said it was more about upholding the  
rights of parents to be involved when a daughter chooses to end a 
pregnancy, and about protecting the health and well-being of 
minors, than about abortion itself. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents argued that it would do more harm than good because  
girls without supportive parents would be left to resolve the 
situation on their own. They also said nonparents who could help 
them, such as grandmothers or adult siblings, would be scared away 
under the threat of federal prosecution. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 1218.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
