<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets soared ahead Thursday,  
boosted by news that the U.S. Federal Reserve sees no pressing need 
to raise interest rates again. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, Asia's largest market, stocks closed sharply higher on  
the news that had lifted Wall Street prices on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average soared 331.01  
points, or 1.9 percent, to 17,860.75, its highest close since Sept. 
30, 1997, when it ended at 17,887.71. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Federal Reserve raised interest rates by a quarter  
point on Wednesday but hinted it didn't see the need for more 
increases, thrilling U.S. traders who had worried about further 
tightening. 
</P>
<P>
	The news slightly weakened the U.S. dollar in Tokyo.  
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.82 yen by late afternoon, down 0.04 yen  
from late Wednesday and below its late New York level of 120.93 yen 
overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices skyrocketed on the Korea Stock Exchange, with the key  
index jumping 4.2 percent, or 36.98 points, to close at 919.98. 
</P>
<P>
	The market got a lift from the U.S. interest rate news as well  
as the Samsung Group's filing for court receivership for its 
debt-ridden unit Samsung Motors Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the Kospi's highest close since 920.43 on May 27, 1996.  
</P>
<P>
	In Singapore, the U.S. rate announcement drove the benchmark  
index to its third record close in the past two weeks. The 
benchmark Straits Times Index finished at 2214.75 points, up 47.05 
points, or 2.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong, Taipei and Bangkok financial markets were closed  
Thursday for holidays. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Indonesian blue chips ended higher, despite domestic  
political concerns. The JSX Composite Index gained 1.7 percent, or 
11.017 points, to end at 673.042. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian shares jumped 3 percent, fueled by local  
fund buying and the rally on Wall Street. The Kuala Lumpur Stock 
Exchange Composite Index rose 24.21 points to end at 835.31. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Philippine shares ended sharply higher on the U.S.  
monetary policy announcement. The PSE Index closed up 56.34 points, 
or 2.3 percent, at 2,543.30. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian shares rose on the back of Wall Street's  
gains and higher New York commodity futures prices. The All 
Ordinaries Index gained 1.1 percent, or 33.2 points, to close at 
3,002.1. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand shares bucked the trend, falling a sharp  
drop by market heavyweight Telecom Corp. of New Zealand. The 
NZSE-40 Capital Index closed 9.30 points, or 0.4 percent, lower at 
2,127.10. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
