<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bad News Continues for Coca-Cola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Coca-Cola has been battered by a spate of bad  
news this past year. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday brought word of more woes.  
</P>
<P>
	The company extended a glass bottle recall in Poland, in the  
aftermath of a major health scare in Europe over Coke products. 
</P>
<P>
	And, the Atlanta-based company reported that its second-quarter  
finances will be hurt by the health crisis and by continued 
economic downturns in other key overseas markets that have been 
reeling for more than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Also in the past year, regulatory obstacles delayed Coke's  
efforts to take over the French brand Orangina and most Cadbury 
Schweppes brands overseas, and four current or past employees, all 
black, filed a lawsuit charging the company with racial 
discrimination. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no question that the last 18 months or so has been  
challenging,'' company spokesman Rob Baskin said. ``I don't know 
that it's been more challenging than other times in the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After all, he said, Coke in its 113-year history has been  
through the Great Depression, recessions in the United States and 
abroad, and world wars. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important to keep these things in perspective,'' Baskin  
said. ``It's a matter of taking the long view and weathering the 
storms.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coke has long been as popular on Wall Street as it is with loyal  
consumers, and its stature and reputation have helped keep the 
recent events from adding up to disaster. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have had a rough patch here,'' said Martin Romm, a Credit  
Suisse First Boston analyst who's followed Coke for more than two 
decades. ``I think Coke has really acted as an extremely focused 
company intent on doing the things that in the long term are in the 
best interests of their business. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've been remarkably stable in an otherwise unstable  
environment,'' said Romm, among many analysts who still give Coke a 
good long-term outlook. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, M. Douglas Ivester, chairman and chief executive  
officer, said the company believes ``that the worst is behind us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We remain extremely confident in the fundamental strengths of  
our business systems throughout the world,'' Ivester said. ``Our 
company continues to be well-positioned to emerge from the current 
economic environment with an enhanced system that can refresh more 
consumers, every day, all over the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The series of setbacks has brought increased scrutiny on  
Ivester, who succeeded Roberto C. Goizueta, Coke's CEO for 16 
highly successful years, in October 1997 following Goizueta's death 
from lung cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	``While nobody is blaming Ivester for any of these  
circumstances, CEO's have been eased into premature retirement for 
less,'' an Atlanta Journal-Constitution story commented Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Coke has been criticized for a slow response to the health  
crisis that saw authorities link 249 cases of illness to Coke 
products and three European countries temporarily ban some Coke 
beverages. Ivester took personal charge of the crisis last week, 
apologizing in Belgium and pledging that Coke would regain trust. 
</P>
<P>
	Since overseas problems began hurting Coke's sales last year,  
Ivester has insisted that Coke remains focused on long-term 
opportunities and is committed to global growth. 
</P>
<P>
	A key director said Ivester retains the board's full support.  
</P>
<P>
	``We think Doug is the right man at the right time in the right  
place,'' said James B. Williams, retired chairman and CEO of 
SunTrust Banks. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the company's strong civic reputation, most in the  
Atlanta area have had a wait-and-see response to the discrimination 
suit filed in April alleging the company gives less pay and 
opportunity to black employees. However, subsequent disclosures 
that black executives at Coke gave Ivester, at his request, 
recommendations for increasing diversity in December 1995 and that 
the plaintiffs had made formal complaints before the suit raised 
some eyebrows. 
</P>
<P>
	``What surprises me is that they didn't nip it (complaints of  
discrimination) in the bud any earlier,'' said state Rep. Tyrone 
Brooks, D-Atlanta, who heads the Georgia Association of Black 
Elected Officials. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
