<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Franc At 8-Yr. Low Vs. Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The euro dropped to a new low against the dollar  
Thursday after the European Central Bank chose not to follow the 
U.S. Federal Reserve's decision of a day earlier to raise its key 
interest rate. 
</P>
<P>
	The Swiss franc fell to an eight-year low.  
</P>
<P>
	The European currencies struggled as new evidence emerged of  
continued strength in the U.S. economy and as higher interest rates 
in the United States made returns more attractive on 
dollar-denominated holdings. U.S. stocks rose Thursday, adding to 
Wednesday's sharp gains, with broad indexes reaching new highs. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to interest rates, the euro was hurt by the European  
Central Bank's insistence that the weakening euro wasn't a problem. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0229, down  
from $1.0338 Wednesday. Earlier in Europe, it fell to a new low of 
$1.0200, down more than 12 percent from where the euro debuted in 
January, when it replaced the currencies of 11 nations in the 
European Union. 
</P>
<P>
	While the euro tumbled, the currency did come off its early low  
amid reports that the ECB intervened in foreign-exchange markets to 
boost the struggling currency. The ECB refused to comment on the 
report. 
</P>
<P>
	The ECB left interest rates unchanged Thursday. In April, when  
it lowered its key lending rate by half a percentage point to 2.5 
percent, the central bank had said that would be the last cut for 
the foreseeable future. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the Federal Reserve nudged short-term U.S.  
interest rates up by a quarter point in an attempt to cool down the 
fast-paced U.S. economy and avoid inflationary pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists said that diverging growth prospects in the United  
States and the European Union justify U.S. short-term rates twice 
as high as those for euro nations. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Fed raised rates and the ECB did not follow. Now the cycle  
favors the United States,'' said Ricardo Gomes, head of foreign 
exchange at Republic National Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	He added that its not just the euro that was struggling against  
the dollar. Other currencies -- including the Swiss franc -- have 
been selling off on expectations that European economic growth will 
lag that of the United States in coming months. 
</P>
<P>
	``There seems to be a capital movement out of all of Europe,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar rose to 1.5692 Swiss francs from 1.5479 Wednesday,  
reaching the highest level since the summer of 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	While the euro and Swiss franc struggled, the dollar got a lift  
from bullish U.S. economic data. The National Association of 
Purchasing Management reported that the nation's manufacturing 
sector expanded for the fifth straight month in June, and at a 
stronger pace than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Federal Reserve said Wednesday that it didn't plan on  
raising rates again in the near future, investors believe that a 
string of stronger-than-expected data like that seen in Thursday's 
report may force the central bank to change its stance. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.4729 Canadian dollars, up from  
1.4667. The British pound rose to $1.5728 from $1.5785. Against the 
Japanese yen, the dollar was trading at 120.78 yen, down from 
120.93 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Thursday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.9120 German 
marks, up from 1.8914; 6.4144 French francs, up from 6.3452; and 
1,893.94 Italian lire, up from 1,872.66. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
