<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arco: Plaintiffs Weren't Employees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Nine people who filed a lawsuit accusing  
Atlantic Richfield Co. of denying them benefits when they worked in 
Alaskan oil fields were never employed by the company, an Arco 
spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Plaintiffs in the class-action lawsuit were employees of other  
companies that Arco hired to perform a variety of services in North 
Slope oil fields, spokeswoman Marylou Flynn said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The response was Arco's first to the lawsuit filed last week in  
U.S. District Court. 
</P>
<P>
	The plaintiffs contend that Arco hired them as temporary workers  
and then misclassified them to avoid playing benefits. They are 
seeking the same health and pension benefits given to Arco's 
regular 18,000-member work force. At least 100 and as many as 1,500 
workers may have been misclassified by Arco, Brian Ward, attorney 
for the plaintiffs, has said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ward's law firm won a similar case against Microsoft Corp.,  
which was accused of hiring temporary workers to avoid paying 
benefits. The Arco case differs from Microsoft's because the 
employees in question were hired by third-party contractors, said 
Ms. Flynn. 
</P>
<P>
	``None of these plaintiffs ever worked for Arco or work for Arco  
now,'' she said. ``All of them became employees of independent oil 
field service companies that hired them and provided their 
benefits. We hired these companies to do jobs for Arco.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
