<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Pick South Philly Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- After months of indecision, GOP officials on  
Thursday settled on a South Philadelphia sports arena to host the 
party's 2000 presidential convention. 
</P>
<P>
	``The next president of the United States, that woman or man who  
will lead us to the next millennium, will be nominated right here 
in this building, the First Union Center,'' Republican National 
Chairman Jim Nicholson announced at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	The convention, scheduled for the week of July 29 to Aug. 4,  
2000, is expected to draw about 40,000 people, including 15,000 
members of the press. 
</P>
<P>
	Party officials had for six months been contemplating the  
downtown Pennsylvania Convention Center, impressed by its modern 
meeting facilities and central location. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson said he was ultimately swayed by the First Union  
Center's superior television production capabilities, 
accessibility, ample parking and sound equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	A team of engineering and architectural consultants has already  
boosted First Union's capacity from 18,000 to between 23,00 to 
24,000. Mayor Edward G. Rendell has promised that one lane of Broad 
Street, which connects Center City to the sports complex, would be 
reserved for convention traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	Philadelphia has hosted eight presidential nominating  
conventions, including the Republicans' first national convention 
in 1856. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
