<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	World Economy Growing Slowly  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Despite the recovery of most financial  
markets, the world economy is still growing slowly and the poorest 
countries continue to suffer the most, according to a U.N. report. 
Economic growth this year in developing nations is on track to be 
lower than any year this decade, according to ``The World Economy 
in 1999,'' which is to be released today. 

</P>
<P>
	Computer Export Restrictions Eased  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is easing export  
restrictions on computers today, making it easier for the high-tech 
industry to sell more powerful systems to foreign countries 
including China which has a vast market. The industry had sought 
the change because current restrictions, designed to keep advanced 
technology out of the hands of hostile militaries, have failed to 
keep up with the advances in commercially available computers. 

</P>
<P>
	Cable Car Crash Kills 20 in France  
</P>
<P>
	SAINT-ETIENNE-EN-DEVOLUY, France (AP) -- A cable car gondola  
crashed hundreds of feet to the ground today on the slopes of a ski 
resort in the French Alps, killing all 20 people aboard. Officials 
said no tourists were riding the private cable car that was 
carrying workers to the Pic de Bure space observatory. The gondola 
fell 262 feet onto a rock-studded grass slope above 
Saint-Etienne-en-Devoluy, 400 miles southeast of Paris. It was the 
worst cable car disaster in the country's history. 

</P>
<P>
	15 Injured in Indonesian Protest  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Riot police fired warning shots and  
tear gas today into a crowd of 1,500 protesters, injuring at least 
15 people in the worst outbreak of street violence since landmark 
elections last month. Police also arrested 12 people after 
demonstrators tried to force their way into the Indonesian Election 
Commission building to protest alleged vote-rigging by the ruling 
Golkar party and to demand the military cease meddling in politics. 

</P>
<P>
	EU OKs $5.2M for Romanian Orphanages  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) - The European Commission approved nearly  
$5.2 million in aid today for children growing up in Romania's 
orphanages, where appalling living conditions have worsened due to 
government budget cuts. These children live in ``dreadful 
conditions,'' which have become worse since the Romanian government 
decided to reduce funds for orphanages as part of belt-tightening 
efforts to reform the economy, said a statement by the Commission, 
the European Union's executive arm. Close to 150,000 children are 
in Romania's orphanages. 

</P>
<P>
	French Court Gives Noriega 10 Years  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- A French court today sentenced former Panamanian  
dictator Manuel Noriega and his wife to 10 years in jail for 
laundering millions of dollars through accounts in several leading 
French banks. The couple, which was also fined a total of $29.1 
million, was tried and sentenced in absentia. Noriega is currently 
in jail near Miami, serving a 30-year term for money laundering and 
drug trafficking. Felicidad Noriega's whereabouts are unknown to 
authorities. 

</P>
<P>
	AOL, Prodigy Offer Free Computers  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- America Online Inc. and Prodigy Communications  
Corp., two major providers of Internet access, have joined an 
industry push to offer consumers free personal computers if they 
agree to sign up for online service for three years. AOL said it 
would give a $400 rebate on selected eMachines Inc. computers to 
people who agree to subscribe to its $21.95-a-month CompuServe 
Internet access for three years. The lowest-price eMachines 
computer is $399, in effect making it free, but the monitor isn't 
included. Prodigy announced a similar three-year deal for computers 
bought at Best Buy consumer electronics stores. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 19.32; Nasdaq Up 7.35  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 1 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 19.32 points at 10,990.12. Advancing issues on the New York 
Stock Exchange led decliners 1,506-1,416. The Nasdaq was up 7.35 at 
2,693.47. 

</P>
<P>
	Davenport Beats Novotna  
</P>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- Lindsay Davenport advances to the  
Wimbledon semifinals for the first time in her career after beating 
defending champion Jana Novotna today 6-3, 6-4. As rain disrupted 
play for the third day this week, the third-seeded American 
dominated the error-prone Czech to extend her career record against 
Novotna to 6-0. Davenport will face the winner of the first ever 
quarterfinal match between two qualifiers: 18-year-old American 
Alexandra Stevenson and 16-year-old Australian Jelena Dokic. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief By LINDA KIM  

  	   	
</P>
