<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Headmaster After Fox Sitcom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KENT, Conn. (AP) -- Seth MacFarlane has been out of prep school  
for eight years now and the headmaster is still on his case. 
</P>
<P>
	The top administrator of the Kent School is leading a one-man  
campaign to get advertisers to drop ``The Family Guy,'' an animated 
TV comedy created by MacFarlane, a 1991 Kent alumnus. 
</P>
<P>
	The show, which airs Thursdays at 9 p.m. EST on Fox, is about a  
doofus husband, his wife, their slacker teen-agers, homicidal 
toddler and trilingual pooch. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rev. Richardson Schell, headmaster at the Kent School for 18  
years, has asked such major companies as Pepsico, Philip Morris, 
Chrysler and Sprint to drop ``The Family Guy.'' At least two of 
them, Philip Morris and Sprint, have withdrawn their ads from the 
show. 
</P>
<P>
	Schell, who was in London on Thursday and could not immediately  
be reached by telephone, told The New York Times that he finds the 
show ``obnoxious.'' He said he also objects to the fact that the 
name of the cartoon family, Griffin, is the same as that of his 
assistant at the Kent School. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no problem with Seth, and it is not a personal  
vendetta,'' Schell told the Times. 
</P>
<P>
	Jokes on the show have touched on subjects such as racism,  
urination and flatulence. One gag involved a toy called ``G.I. 
Jew.'' In one episode, a boy shoots the head off a John F. Kennedy 
Pez dispenser, then says: ``At least I have my Bobby Kennedy Pez 
dispenser to back him up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Fox network spokeswoman in Los Angeles did not immediately  
return a call for comment. McFarlane declined to comment, the Times 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Schell wrote the advertisers on behalf of ``Proud Sponsors  
USA,'' which he acknowledges has a total membership of one. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Shafer, a spokesman for Overland Park, Kan.-based Sprint,  
said letters from Schell and others prompted the long-distance 
phone company to undertake its own review of the show. 
</P>
<P>
	``The show is out there on the edge, in terms of subject matter  
and the way that it deals with controversial subjects,'' Shafer 
said. ``The show was risky enough that we felt it didn't match the 
advertising goals of our brand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris was airing youth smoking prevention ads on the  
show. Spokeswoman Mary Carnavale said the show was inconsistent 
with the company's emphasis on diversity, in part because the main 
characters are all white and in part because of the potentially 
offensive racial and ethnic subject matter. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
