<HEADLINE> Powerful Fireworks Ring Broken Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Five people are accused of running a fireworks  
ring that allegedly sold thousands of powerful illegal explosives 
in several states. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not talking about firecrackers. These are mini-bombs,''  
said Ann Brown, chairwoman of the U.S. Consumer Product Safety 
Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	Indictments against three of the defendants were unsealed  
Thursday, charging them with selling and transporting illegal 
fireworks. The maximum sentence is 21 years in prison and fines of 
up to $3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation was sparked by the death of Eric Pluger, 17,  
who was killed July 14 when he and his friends blew up a mailbox 
with a quarter-stick of dynamite. The Shiocton, Wis., teen-ager 
died after he was hit by metal flying from the mailbox. 
</P>
<P>
	It is not known if the fireworks the defendants sold were  
involved in the death. 
</P>
<P>
	Indicted were Donald R. Peters and his daughter Peggy S. Malueg  
of Green Bay and Charles J. Childers of Appleton. Rodney L. Harris 
of Appleton and Albert Castellano Jr. of Rochester, Ind., pleaded 
guilty in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the indictments did not say exactly what the defendants  
are accused of selling, authorities have seized more than 8,000 
pounds of illegal fireworks in Wisconsin over the past year, 
Assistant U.S. Attorney Mario F. Gonzales said. 
</P>
<P>
	The fireworks included more than 65,000 quarter-sticks,  
half-sticks, M-80s and other explosives banned under federal law. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're talking about an operation that sold, conservatively,  
hundreds of thousands of devices, and it may be in the millions,'' 
said Eric Stone, director of the legal division of the Consumer 
Product Safety Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	About 8,500 Americans received medical attention last year after  
being injured by fireworks. More than half of those injuries occur 
around Independence Day. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
