<HEADLINE> Jim Brown Charged With Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Prosecutors filed charges Thursday against  
Hall of Fame football player and actor Jim Brown for allegedly 
threatening to kill his wife and breaking her car windows with a 
shovel. 
</P>
<P>
	City Attorney Jim Hahn filed one count of making a terrorist  
threat and one count of vandalism, both misdemeanors, against 
Brown, 63, for an alleged incident June 15 at the couple's 
Hollywood Hills home, said Lara Bloomquist, supervising attorney. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown was arrested that night after his wife of two years,  
Monique, 25, called 911 at 6:50 p.m. He was booked at the Hollywood 
station and posted $50,000 bail. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Brown later held an impromptu news conference outside their  
home and said she had ``overreacted'' and denied that threats were 
made against her. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown, through his lawyer William Grayson, denied the charges.  
</P>
<P>
	``His wife did not feel threatened and continues to live  
peacefully with her husband,'' Grayson said Thursday. ``They did 
have an argument but there was no violence, no injury.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brown is scheduled to appear Tuesday in Municipal Court to enter  
a plea, Bloomquist said. He faces up to 18 months in jail and a 
$2,000 fine if convicted on both counts. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown retired from pro football in 1966. Playing for the  
Cleveland Browns, he set many National Football League rushing and 
scoring records. He has appeared in several Hollywood films, 
including ``The Dirty Dozen.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
