<HEADLINE> Smuggling Ringleader Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- The leader of an illegal-immigrant smuggling ring  
that made about $150 million and slipped thousands of people into 
the United States was sentenced Thursday to 10 years in prison for 
money laundering. 
</P>
<P>
	Nitin Shettie, also known as Nick Diaz, ran an operation that  
smuggled about 7,200 illegal immigrants over 20 months from India 
into the United States, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shettie pleaded guilty in April to a charge of conspiring to  
launder smuggling proceeds. He was arrested in November following a 
yearlong investigation led by the Immigration and Naturalization 
Service. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, federal authorities called it the largest illegal  
alien operation ever uncovered in the United States. Immigrants 
paid $20,000 each, and were hidden in small ``stash houses'' before 
being delivered to U.S. employers seeking inexpensive labor. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department estimates the organization made about  
$150 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
