<DOCNO> APW19990701.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 08:19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Sosa Hits 30th As Clinton Watches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- For Sammy Sosa, it was quite an unusual good-luck  
charm: President Clinton, standing in the owner's box with a 
half-eaten hot dog and a Chicago Cubs cap in his hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa hit his 30th home run of the season Wednesday shortly after  
the president arrived at Wrigley Field in Chicago to watch Sosa, 
one of his favorite athletes. 
</P>
<P>
	``He brings good luck,'' Sosa said of Clinton. ``A big guy like  
that comes to town to see the game -- it doesn't look too good if we 
lost.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs beat the Milwaukee Brewers 5-4 on Sosa's solo homer.  
Clinton -- dropping his usual impartiality during sporting events -- 
cheered, waved to fans, gave a thumbs-up and mouthed hellos. 
</P>
<P>
	``He did what everybody else in the entire stadium did,'' said  
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart. ``The Brewers played well, the 
Cubs played well. But the player the president takes a special 
interest in made the difference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lockhart said the timing of Clinton's arrival and Sosa's home  
run was the president's ``latest example of a long-standing 
streak'' of luck. 
</P>
<P>
	After the game, Cubs general manager Ed Lynch took Clinton to  
the clubhouse to congratulate Sosa. Lockhart said Clinton and Sosa 
hadn't seen each other since Sosa came to the White House in 
January; Clinton had invited Sosa to attend the State of the Union 
address as his guest. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton and Sosa chatted for 10 minutes in the locker room and  
for another 10 minutes alone in a nearby room. Sosa gave Clinton a 
blue Cubs jacket and a red Beanie Baby bear with a Cubs emblem on 
the package. The two exchanged autographs. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was asked whether his wife, Hillary, would allow him to  
keep the Cubs jacket, given her newfound loyalty to the New York 
Yankees. Clinton nodded yes -- after a slow pause. He teasingly 
chastised a reporter who asked whether the first lady was still a 
Cubs fan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't play press games here,'' he said, smiling. ``This is  
about sports, not politics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president went to Wrigley Field following a speech to pitch  
his new Medicare proposal to senior citizens. He was so excited 
about attending the game that he announced it at the start of his 
speech -- to the annoyance of the Secret Service, which didn't 
exactly want the world to know his plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton paused at a local hotel to change out of his business  
suit and keep tabs on the Northern Ireland peace talks. He spoke 
for about 10 minutes with British Prime Minister Tony Blair to get 
an update, then zipped over to the game, where the score was 4-3 
Brewers in the fifth inning. 
</P>
<P>
	The president settled in the Cubs' owner's box, looking relaxed  
in a yellow, open-necked shirt and brown blazer. He waved to the 
fans. Some booed, others craned to catch a view of him. 
</P>
<P>
	In the middle of the seventh inning, Clinton joined in singing  
the traditional baseball anthem, ``Take Me Out to the Ball Game.'' 
Moments later, Sosa knocked the ball over the left field wall and 
Clinton neglected his hot dog long enough to stand and applaud. 
</P>
<P>
	Sosa now has reached 30 homers in a season for the sixth time.  
He has homered in four consecutive games, his longest streak since 
last June 3-8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
