<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Gov't Investigation Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A day after the independent counsel law  
expired, Attorney General Janet Reno took authority Thursday to 
appoint special prosecutors to investigate alleged wrongdoing by 
presidents and top government officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The new rules announced by the Justice Department replace the  
21-year-old independent counsel law. That statute died after years 
of controversy over investigations such as Lawrence Walsh's of the 
Reagan-era Iran-Contra affair and Kenneth Starr's of President 
Clinton's involvement in Whitewater and other matters. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Reno and Starr urged Congress in the spring to let the  
independent counsel law lapse. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder said at a news conference  
the new rules were intended to ``strike the proper balance between 
accountability and independence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe these regulations will ensure integrity,  
independence and accountability in high-profile investigations,'' 
Holder said. ``It is time to move on from our experience with the 
independent counsel act and to return this nation back to the 
principles that have guided law enforcement for nearly 200 years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rules give Reno the sole authority to appoint a prosecutor,  
to be called a special counsel, if she determines the Justice 
Department would have a conflict of interest in investigating 
allegations of wrongdoing, and if she decides that naming an 
outside prosecutor would be in the public interest. 
</P>
<P>
	Reno would outline the boundaries of the investigation, although  
a special prosecutor could ask her to expand those boundaries to 
cover new matters that surface. 
</P>
<P>
	A special counsel would not be subject to day-to-day supervision  
by the Justice Department but would be required to comply with its 
practices and seek guidance from department officials on those 
policies. 
</P>
<P>
	A Justice Department commentary on the rules said that provision  
would ``help to guard against a special counsel becoming too 
insulated and narrow in his or her view of the matter under 
investigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A prosecutor would have to notify the attorney general before  
seeking an indictment in a sensitive case, and she could veto a 
planned indictment. Reno also would have veto power over appeals 
and in some instances over investigative steps she considered 
unwarranted or inappropriate. 
</P>
<P>
	If she vetoed a proposed action by a prosecutor, she would be  
required to notify Congress at the end of the investigation and 
explain why the action was not approved. 
</P>
<P>
	Special counsels could be fired for good cause by the attorney  
general. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department would set a special counsel's budget. An  
outside prosecutor's final report would be submitted to the 
attorney general and generally would be kept confidential unless 
the attorney general determined it should be publicly released. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the independent counsel law, prosecutors were named by a  
three-judge panel. Although they generally were supposed to follow 
Justice Department policies, prosecutors in effect had free rein to 
decide how to handle an investigation, how much money to spend and 
what court appeals to pursue. 
</P>
<P>
	The independent counsel law was enacted as a response to the  
1973 Saturday Night Massacre, in which two attorneys general 
resigned rather than carry out President Nixon's demand that they 
fire Watergate special prosecutor Archibald Cox. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
