<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Download Delays Bug Online Shoppers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) -- As much as $4.35 billion in  
electronic commerce may be lost annually in the United States 
because online shoppers frustrated with slow download times simply 
give up making a purchase, a study says. 
</P>
<P>
	A study released Wednesday by Zona Research says one-third of  
online shoppers may not buy an item over the Internet due to the 
slowness of the experience, whether caused by their own modems or a 
failure at a Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	A crash at the eBay auction Web site in early June indicated how  
costly any failure can be for an e-commerce Web site. The Web site 
was down for about 24 hours on June 10 and 11, resulting in a 
revenue loss of between $3 million and $5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Zona study found that 44.1 million people are currently  
shopping online, with some 37.5 million new online shoppers 
expected within the next 12 months. 
</P>
<P>
	A recent University of Texas study revealed that online shoppers  
generated nearly $102 billion in sales, or 1 percent of the 
nation's gross domestic product, last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Zona study said the biggest losses would be at Web sites  
with pages that take longer than eight seconds to load for users 
with a 14.4 kilobyte modem. Those sites stand to lose $876 million 
a year, the study said. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
