<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	House Passes Consumer Privacy Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House voted Thursday to give consumers the  
right to block banks and other financial companies from sharing 
their personal data with outside firms. The vote on privacy 
measure, proposed by House Republican leaders, was 427-1. It was 
attached to sweeping legislation which would allow banks, 
securities firms and insurance companies to merge. The bill was 
passed, 343-86. 

</P>
<P>
	Milosevic Wins Opposition Support  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- More evidence of mass killings  
emerged Thursday in Kosovo as President Slobodan Milosevic won 
conditional support from a key opposition group, furthering his 
campaign to retain power and avoid war crimes prosecution. The 
commander of U.S. peacekeepers in Kosovo, meanwhile, warned that 
his soldiers face a continuing threat from Serb paramilitaries who 
remain in the province in violation of a peace agreement that 
required all Yugoslav forces leave. 

</P>
<P>
	Mediators Try To Save Congo Talks  
</P>
<P>
	LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) -- As fighting intensified in southeastern  
Congo, Zambian officials tried Thursday to salvage stalled talks on 
a cease-fire to end the country's civil war. African foreign and 
defense ministers failed to agree on several key issues and a 
dispute among rival Congolese rebels also delayed talks, a Zambian 
official said on condition of anonymity. Mediators, headed by 
Zambian President Frederick Chiluba, were shuttling among 
representatives of warring parties in an effort to resolve 
differences and end the 11-month conflict that has enveloped most 
of Central Africa, he said. 

</P>
<P>
	No Agreement Yet on N. Ireland  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Rival negotiators failed for a  
second straight day early Friday to form the Protestant-Catholic 
government at the heart of the Northern Ireland peace accord. But 
they agreed to meet for one final session later in the day. British 
Prime Minister Tony Blair presided over more than 12 hours of 
talks, warning during the session that the world would be baffled 
if peace slipped away. Adding to the tensions, scores of marches 
took place Thursday night across Northern Ireland to commemorate 
the slaughter of Ulster Protestants at the Battle of the Somme in 
World War I. 

</P>
<P>
	Y2K Lawsuit Bill Passed by Congress  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Exactly six months before the year 2000,  
Congress endorsed legislation Thursday to shield businesses from a 
potential flood of Y2K computer-related lawsuits. The White House 
says President Clinton will sign it. A House vote of 404-24 was 
followed by an 81-18 vote in the Senate. The Senate's main sponsor, 
Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., called passage ``a victory for the 
nation and for the continued prosperity of our economy as we enter 
the new millennium.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Cable Car Crash Kills 20 in France  
</P>
<P>
	SAINT-ETIENNE-EN-DEVOLUY, France (AP) -- In the worst cable car  
disaster in French history, a gondola plunged to the ground 
Thursday, killing all 20 people aboard a private lift that was 
carrying workers to a space observatory high in the Alps. The cable 
car was about one-quarter the way up the mountain when it suddenly 
fell 262 feet onto a rock-studded slope above 
Saint-Etienne-en-Devoluy, a ski resort south of Grenoble. 

</P>
<P>
	U S West To Discuss Qwest Offer  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- U S West Inc., the Denver-based Baby Bell phone  
company at the heart of a three-week takeover battle, said Thursday 
it would explore a $34.7 billion offer from Qwest Communication 
International Inc. U S West's decision follows a similar move 
Monday by Frontier Corp., the fifth-largest long-distance company, 
which is weighing a $11.8 billion takeover bid from Qwest. 
Currently, however, both U S West and Frontier have merger 
agreements with Global Crossing Ltd. But on Thursday Global 
Crossing gave U S West permission to provide information to Qwest 
so that they can discuss the rival offer. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rise in Midday Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks reached a 21-month high in midday  
trading Friday. The Nikkei rose 91.68 points to 17,952.43 points at 
the end of the morning session. In New York, the Dow Jones 
industrial average posted its fourth consecutive gain, rising 95.62 
points to 11,066.42 at Thursday's close. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Defeats Germany 3-2  
</P>
<P>
	LANDOVER, Md. (AP) -- The United States turned to its defenders  
Thursday night, getting second-half goals from Brandi Chastain and 
Joy Fawcett to edge Germany 3-2 in their toughest game thus far in 
the Women's World Cup. The Americans advanced to a Fourth of July 
semifinal at Stanford, Calif., against the winner of Thursday's 
late game between Brazil and Nigeria. Before a festive crowd that 
included a late-arriving President Clinton and family, the 
Americans stormed back with a sensational second half and wore down 
the Germans. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief By ANDREW DAMPF  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
