<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Belfast Talks Remain Deadlocked  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- The two parties crucial to  
forging a Protestant-Catholic government for Northern Ireland 
accused each other of spurning compromise today, threatening 
negotiations aimed at salvaging last year's peace accord. The 
talks, adjourned early today after going 18 hours straight, were 
set to reconvene at midday. Progress depends on whether the Ulster 
Unionists, Northern Ireland's major British Protestant party, would 
accept a pledge from the IRA-linked Sinn Fein party to do its best 
to deliver the Irish Republican Army's disarmament by May. 

</P>
<P>
	21 Killed in French Alps Cable Car Crash  
</P>
<P>
	GRENOBLE, France (AP) -- A cable car crashed to the ground early  
today at a resort town in the French Alps, killing all 21 people 
aboard, officials said. The cable car fell about 260 feet in 
Saint-Etienne-en-Devoluy, a ski resort south of Grenoble in the 
Hautes-Alpes region of the French Alps. None of the 21 people 
riding the cable car survived the crash, officials at the regional 
prefect's office confirmed. Most of the victims were reported to be 
employees of a nearby observatory. 

</P>
<P>
	Two Amtrak Trains Graze Each Other  
</P>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Two Amtrak trains grazed each other  
early today, injuring at least five people. ``We're still not sure 
what happened,'' said Fire Chief Ray Alfred. The accident caused 
the engine car and a baggage car to tip over. The injured were 
taken to St. Vincent's Medical Center in Jacksonville, said 
hospital spokeswoman Kim Welch. The trains were heading in opposite 
directions on the Miami-to-New York City route and were carrying a 
total of about 300 people, said Amtrak spokesman John Wolf. 

</P>
<P>
	Winning Ticket Bought in Minn.  
</P>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- People standing in long lines around the  
country helped push the Powerball jackpot to $150 million, the 
third highest ever, before a player who bought a ticket in 
Minnesota came up with the winning numbers. ``The sales are 
extremely out of control. It's just packed,'' Deana Warner, a store 
manager in Fond du Lac, Wis., said before last night's drawing. The 
winner with the ticket purchased in Minnesota was not immediately 
determined. 

</P>
<P>
	Center Party Joins Barak Coalition  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak widened his  
coalition today as a moderate party agreed to join, ensuring his 
government broad support for reactivating the peace process. After 
more than five weeks of coalition negotiations, Barak announced 
yesterday that he had the numbers to form a government. The leader 
of the Center party, former Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai, 
said after a meeting overnight with other party members that it 
would be part of the new government. 

</P>
<P>
	Russia Denies Violating Air Space  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Moscow denied today that two Russian strategic  
bombers violated the airspace of Iceland -- a NATO member -- during 
military exercises last week. The two long-range Tu-95 Bear bombers 
``did not cross Iceland's air border'' during a 15-hour training 
flight last Friday, a Russian Air Force spokesman said, the 
Interfax news agency reported. Russian officials said four bombers 
flew over the North Pole and test-fired strategic missiles as part 
of military exercises code named ``West 99.'' 

</P>
<P>
	North, South Korea Resume Talks  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- North Korea and South Korea resumed talks today  
on reuniting families separated by their 54-year rivalry. South 
Korean Vice Unification Minister Yang Young-shik told North Korean 
negotiators that all Koreans -- whether from the communist North or 
capitalist South -- want the divided families reunited. Yang's plea 
and optimistic tone met chilly replies from lead North Korean 
negotiator Pak Yong Su. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stock Prices Close Higher  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks ended higher today with the Nikkei  
gaining 331.01 points to close at 17,860.75. 

</P>
<P>
	Athletics 14, Mariners 5  
</P>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Ramon Hernandez went 3-for-4 with four  
RBIs, including his first major league homer, as the Oakland 
Athletics routed the Seattle Mariners 14-5 last night to snap a 
six-game losing streak. Rookie Tim Hudson threw seven shutout 
innings for the Athletics, who stopped the Mariners' three-game 
winning streak. Miguel Tejada and Ryan Christenson each drove in 
three runs for Oakland. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief By DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
