<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Immigrants Find Success in Silicon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP)-- Chinese and Indian immigrants, coming to  
this country with top notch technical skills and a desire to take 
big chances, are finding great success in the Silicon Valley. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were immigrants because we were risk takers. We left our  
safe land behind and came to this place looking for something 
bigger and better,'' said Vinita Gupta, board chairman of 
Sunnyvale, Calif.-based Digital Link Corp., one of the top 
companies linking businesses on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	A new study from the San Francisco-based Public Policy Institute  
of California shows that highly skilled Asian immigrants are now 
senior executives at one-quarter of Silicon Valley's new technology 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	These immigrant-run companies collectively accounted for more  
than $16.8 billion in sales and 58,282 jobs in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the entrepreneurs -- including Ms. Gupta -- arrived in the  
United States after 1970 to pursue graduate studies, according to 
the study. 
</P>
<P>
	``People from India are highly analytical and technical, but as  
immigrants we have a hard time getting integrated into society,'' 
said Ms. Gupta. ``We have found a great niche in the Silicon Valley 
because we can use our skills and start our own businesses, rather 
than try to fit into the existing system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The study backs Silicon Valley leaders who persuaded Congress  
this year to provide 142,500 more visas over three years for 
computer savvy foreigners with skills that high tech employers 
contend are tough to find but vital for the industry's continued 
growth. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics argue that American workers are being overlooked in  
favor of cheaper labor. 
</P>
<P>
	The study said the economic contributions of immigrants are not  
limited to their direct role as engineers and entrepreneurs. 
</P>
<P>
	They also create professional and social networks that  
facilitate immigrant job search, information exchange, access to 
capital and managerial know-how, and the creation of shared ethnic 
identities. 
</P>
<P>
	``The region's most successful Chinese and Indian entrepreneurs  
rely heavily on such ethnic resources while simultaneously 
integrating into the mainstream technology economy,'' said AnnaLee 
Saxenian, the author of the study. 
</P>
<P>
	K.B. Chandrasekhar, who came from India to the U.S. in 1990 and  
co-founded Santa Clara, Calif.-based Exodus Communications Inc. a 
few years later, said he mentors as many young Indian entrepreneurs 
as he can find time to help. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a matter of pride for us,'' said Chandrasekhar, whose  
company has become a leading provider of network management systems 
for companies doing business online. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990701.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 12:40:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Bankers Want Licenses Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian financiers on Thursday threatened to sue  
the Central Bank for pulling the licenses of four insolvent 
commercial banks this week, calling the move detrimental to the 
country's welfare. 
</P>
<P>
	The Central Bank insisted that its decision to revoke the  
licenses of Uneximbank, Mosbiznesbank, Promstroibank and 
Mezhkombank was taken under pressure from international lending 
organizations and that it was necessary so that Russia could 
qualify for badly needed foreign loans. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Monetary Fund has urged Russia to stop wasting  
scarce resources on subsidies to shaky banks and to accelerate the 
liquidation of insolvent organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	But the president of the Association of Russian Banks, Sergei  
Yegorov, called the decision ``impulsive'' and ``anti-state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The (association) and the Russian banks will seek protection  
in the courts,'' Yegorov added. 
</P>
<P>
	Central Bank chairman Viktor Gerashchenko again argued Thursday  
that the four commercial banks had long deserved to lose their 
licenses and that ``naturally there was pressure from the 
international financial community,'' the Interfax news agency 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	But he conceded that closing the insolvent banks won't be easy.  
Russia's 18 largest banks -- many of which are considered bankrupt 
and subject to liquidation -- hold some $850 million in deposits, 
Gerashchenko said. Government officials have long warned that 
shutting down the banks could provoke mass protests and public 
unrest. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerashchenko said the Cabinet is drafting a bill on partial  
compensation of deposits in the banks that are to be liquidated, 
Interfax reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Russians have already lost their money since the onset of  
an economic crisis in August, when several large commercial banks 
froze individual deposits or offered to repay hard-currency 
deposits in rubles at an extremely low exchange rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Some people have tried to sue, but usually with little success.  
</P>
<P>
	In a separate development Thursday, the deputy chief of the  
Interior Ministry's organized crime department, Anatoly Petukhov, 
said that Russian banks are unwittingly holding up to several 
million of counterfeit U.S. dollars on deposit, the ITAR-Tass news 
agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Most savings in Russia are kept in stable foreign currencies,  
especially U.S. dollars and German marks, and the demand for them 
has also given rise to a large counterfeiting industry. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
