<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 162-Year-Old Dam Being Removed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) -- As church bells pealed Thursday, a torrent  
of water was unleashed through a manmade gap in the 162-year-old 
Edwards Dam in the nation's first government-ordered demolition of 
a dam in the name of conservation. 
</P>
<P>
	The removal of the hydroelectric dam opens an upstream stretch  
of the Kennebec River to Atlantic salmon, striped bass, endangered 
shortnosed sturgeon and other fish for the first time since the 
1830s. 
</P>
<P>
	It is seen as a precedent for other projects, particularly in  
the West, where some dams have been targeted for similar fates. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has fixated the attention of river communities across the  
nation,'' said Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt, who watched from 
the river's edge with hundreds of others as silt-laden water rushed 
downstream. 
</P>
<P>
	Babbitt said he was told years ago that the project ``was not  
going to happen in my lifetime. And, of course, here we are here 
today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Angus King started the process by ringing a bell. More  
bells ringing from a church signaled a big backhoe to rip into a 
temporary dam. 
</P>
<P>
	Within seconds, a trickle, then a rush, of water flowed through  
a 60-foot gap that had already been cut in the 917-foot-wide 
Edwards Dam, which was made of timber, rock and concrete. It will 
take until November before the demolition is complete. 
</P>
<P>
	Dams have been demolished in other states, including North  
Carolina, California and Oregon, but the Edwards Dam, which 
produced only a small amount of electricity, is the first to be 
forcibly removed under a policy that weighs power needs against 
environmental protection. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just watched a river being reborn. You don't get to see that  
every day,'' said Margaret Bowman of American Rivers, part of a 
coalition that pressed for the dam's removal. 
</P>
<P>
	Energy groups were not so moved.  
</P>
<P>
	``Our concern is the level of celebration and whether we're  
going to get caught up in a sort of dam hysteria that would lead to 
the removal of other projects without doing the thorough analysis 
that's necessary,'' said Linda Church Ciocci, executive director of 
the National Hydropower Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Ciocci's group, which represents 140 licensees, also questioned  
whether federal energy regulators had the authority to order the 
demolition. The group is trying to get the order rescinded even 
though the demolition has begun. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ordered the Edwards  
Dam's owners to pay for the removal and restoration of land around 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a deal that bothered some environmentalists, Bath Iron  
Works and upstream dam owners agreed to shoulder the cost, putting 
up more than $7 million. In exchange, BIW received the right to 
fill in wetlands downstream and dam owners got to delay 
construction of fish ladders that enable fish to get upstream. 
</P>
<P>
	``Environmental gains minus environmental gains equals zero  
environmental gains,'' said Jonathan Carter of the Forest Ecology 
Network, who still was glad to see the dam go. 
</P>
<P>
	The dam, about 40 miles from the ocean, has blocked sea-run fish  
for 162 years. Conservationists have labored for years to restore a 
river that was once so choked by pollution that the state Capitol 
windows had to stay closed in the summer to keep out the stench. 
</P>
<P>
	The dam rose amid some opposition in 1837 along a river that had  
been known for its thriving fishery. It supplied mechanical power 
to sawmills and a cotton mill, and later was fitted to generate 
hydroelectric power. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents argued the dam generated only 3.5 megawatts, or  
one-tenth of 1 percent of the state's power. The owner, Edwards 
Manufacturing Co., wanted to increase output to 11 megawatts. But 
FERC denied the application in 1997 and ordered the demolition, 
citing compelling environmental concerns. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990701.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 12:20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Auto Analyst Joins Priceline.com </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Maryann Keller, a respected Wall Street analyst  
and author of two books on General Motors Corp. and the auto 
industry, has joined the Internet buying service Priceline.com Inc. 
to oversee expansion of its new-car buying program. 
</P>
<P>
	Keller, the lead auto analyst at ING Baring Furman Selz LLC for  
the past 13 years, was named president of Priceline.com's 
automotive services unit Thursday. The new-car buying service is 
being tested in the New York City area and will be expanded 
nationwide by year's end, Keller said. 
</P>
<P>
	Priceline.com is an Internet service that allows consumers to  
name a price for airline tickets, hotel rooms and loans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maryann Keller is in the unique position to leverage her  
extensive experience and contacts to build a world-class team and 
strategy for Priceline.com's automotive services unit,'' said 
Richard S. Braddock, chairman and chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Priceline.com is entering an Internet car-buying arena already  
crowded with independent companies, automakers and dealer groups. 
Industry analysts expect the number of consumers using the Internet 
to buy new and used cars and trucks to grow rapidly in the coming 
decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Consumers using Priceline.com will submit a bid for the make and  
model they want and indicate how far they are willing to travel to 
buy it. Priceline.com will then submit the bid to franchised 
dealers within that area to see if any area willing to sell at that 
price. 
</P>
<P>
	Most other Internet car-buying services promise a low, no-haggle  
price from a participating dealer, who pays a fee for the sales 
leads. 
</P>
<P>
	Keller said that while the Internet will not eliminate the need  
for dealerships, it will fundamentally change the way dealers do 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm absolutely convinced it will change the way people buy  
cars,'' she said. ``The car dealership is now, in effect, open 24 
hours a day. Those that do it and do it effectively can gain share 
in their market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Keller said that after 28 years as an auto analyst, she was  
ready to try something different. 
</P>
<P>
	Priceline.com's car-buying service will be rolled out to other  
markets gradually over the next several months, including such 
large markets as California and Michigan, Keller said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
