<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doomed Amtrak Train Ran Red Light </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- An engineer's error was responsible  
for two Amtrak trains sideswiping each other and injuring eight 
people, investigators said. 
</P>
<P>
	A southbound train rolled through a red signal light requiring  
the engineer to stop, striking the northbound train that was moving 
onto a siding early Thursday, said Russ Gober, lead investigator 
for the National Transportation Safety Board. 
</P>
<P>
	Gober said the engineer radioed: ``I made a bad mistake. I made  
a bad judgment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The trains, both called the Silver Palm, were carrying a  
combined 300 passengers when they collided in downtown 
Jacksonville. The trains were en route between Miami and New York 
City. 
</P>
<P>
	Four locomotives and seven cars derailed, said Jane Covington, a  
spokeswoman for CSX Transportation, which owns the track. 
</P>
<P>
	Passengers said the accident jolted them out of their seats.  
Eight people were released after being treated at hospitals for 
minor injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	The southbound train was traveling at 55 mph, while the  
northbound train was moving at 14 mph, Gober said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was asleep and then I heard my wife. I jumped up and held up  
the top bunk where my kids were sleeping,'' said Modesto Romero of 
Newark, N.J. ``They were a little scared.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Railroad crews were righting the cars and placing them back on  
the rails Thursday afternoon. The railroad's main line was expected 
to be open today. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
