<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Both Wimbledon Finals on Sunday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- Rain-plagued Wimbledon appears headed  
for overtime again. 
</P>
<P>
	Only two matches were completed Thursday and, with tournament  
organizers facing a huge backlog of unfinished matches, both 
singles finals now are set for Sunday, with doubles play likely to 
spill into Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Usually, the women's singles and men's and mixed doubles finals  
are Saturday, with Sunday reserved for the men's singles and 
women's doubles finals. 
</P>
<P>
	Weather forecasters say Wimbledon is so popular this year that  
every rain cloud in the southeast seems to he headed for the All 
England Club. 
</P>
<P>
	The result has been scheduling chaos for referee Alan Mills and  
his crew. 
</P>
<P>
	After a virtually uninterrupted first week, the rain washed out  
Tuesday's program entirely and allowed only a handful of matches 
Monday and Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	On what should have been women's semifinals day, organizers had  
to schedule four men's and women's quarterfinals Thursday. 
Persistent showers made it a stop-start day and only two of the 
eight matches -- Steffi Graf beating Venus Williams 6-2, 3-6, 6-4 
and Lindsay Davenport beating defending women's champion Jana 
Novotna 6-3, 6-4 -- were completed. 
</P>
<P>
	With the forecast of a rain-free day Friday, the Wimbledon  
committee hopes to complete two men's quarterfinals which had 
barely started and start two more from the beginning. They also 
have to finish two more women's quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
	If that goes according to plan, there should be two groups of  
semifinals Saturday and both singles finals Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wimbledon seems be in the firing line of any rain that  
develops,'' said Marco Petagna, forecaster at the London Weather 
Center. ``Any rain that's around seems to be in that part of the 
world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The forecast for the weekend is not promising.  
</P>
<P>
	``On Saturday, the rain should clear around 7-8 a.m. and it will  
be a case of bright weather with the risk of scattered showers with 
still the potential of a heavier shower,'' Petagna said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will be similar Sunday with a mixture of bright spells and  
a few showers. There could well be some general rain setting in 
during the afternoon around 3-4 p.m.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mills, the tournament referee, said the club tried to be ``fair  
and evenhanded'' with the players. 
</P>
<P>
	``The men still have one day per round,'' he said. ``We are  
looking at a Friday, Saturday, Sunday scenario for the women.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last time both singles finals were played Sunday was 1989  
when Boris Becker and Steffi Graf both won to make it a first ever 
German double. 
</P>
<P>
	The last time Wimbledon had to play on a third Monday was in  
1996 when Martina Hingis became the youngest ever Wimbledon 
champion at 16, teaming with Helena Sukova in the women's doubles. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990701.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 14:30:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Record Co. Charged in Payola Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Fonovisa, the nation's largest independent  
Latin music record label, was charged along with two of its 
executives with offenses involving payola, or paying radio stations 
to play certain records. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal prosecutors Wednesday charged Fonovisa promotion chief  
Jesus Gilberto Moreno with making improper payments for radio 
airplay. 
</P>
<P>
	Fonovisa president Guillermo Santiso was charged with a  
payola-related tax violation, and the record label was charged with 
a tax offense for allegedly falsely reporting promotional expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal law prohibits radio stations from taking money to play  
specific songs without disclosing the payment to listeners. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman and attorneys for the record company had no comment.  
</P>
<P>
	In May 1997, Moreno paid $2,000 to a program director to have  
Fonovisa records added to the station's play list, court records 
alleged. 
</P>
<P>
	The charges come after a two-year investigation of Fonovisa,  
which is owned by Mexican media giant Grupo Televisa and ruled 
Spanish-language airwaves in 1997 with hits from such artists as 
Enrique Iglesias and Marco Antonio Solis. 
</P>
<P>
	The label was accused of making illegal payments to radio  
stations around the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Grupo Televisa said last year that it reported the alleged  
illegal activities to the U.S. government and cooperated with the 
investigation. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990701.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 15:40:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Automakers Make Gains in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- European automakers again posted some of the  
biggest percentage gains in the U.S. market last month, while the 
Chrysler unit of DaimlerChrysler AG saw sales fall 5 percent 
compared with record sales a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Most European automakers who reported Thursday had double-digit  
gains compared with June 1998, which also was a robust month for 
U.S. sales of cars and light trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	Volkswagen AG reported its strongest June in 26 years and its  
best month overall since May 1979. Its sales were up 23 percent 
over a year ago, due in large part to the success of its redesigned 
Jetta compact sedan -- the nation's best-selling European car. VW 
sold 13,101 Jettas in June for its best month since the nameplate 
was introduced 19 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Audi AG had its most successful June since 1987 with a 44  
percent sales increase from a year ago. Its new TT sports car was 
off to a strong start in its second month. Saab AB, meanwhile, had 
a 34 percent sales increase last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the drop in June sales for DaimlerChrysler -- which has  
brands such as Chrysler, Plymouth and Dodge and Jeep -- the 
German-American automaker said the unit posted a record first half 
with just over 1.39 million sales, and had its best quarter ever in 
April through June. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think the market continues to show strength, and we have a  
robust production schedule planned to match that demand,'' said 
James P. Holden, vice president of sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The comparison to June 1998 was tough for DaimlerChrysler. Big  
``loyalty coupon'' discounts that the three Detroit automakers 
offered to consumers that month generated unusually strong sales; 
the former Chrysler Corp. set what was at the time a record for any 
month that June. 
</P>
<P>
	Car sales took the hardest hit at DaimlerChrysler last month,  
down 14 percent, while truck sales were off about 1.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	One bright spot was the Jeep division, which set a June record  
with Grand Cherokee sales up 9 percent and Cherokee sales up 20 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota Motor Corp. posted a 5 percent gain for its strongest  
June and best-ever second quarter. Though Toyota's U.S. car sales 
were off 10 percent, its truck sales soared 35 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Most ominous for Detroit's automakers was the news that Toyota's  
new Tundra full-size pickup had the best first-month U.S. sales of 
any Toyota model ever. Toyota sold 8,011 Tundras last month, 
breaking the previous first-model record of 3,339 set by the Tercel 
subcompact in October 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford, GM and Dodge have dominated the full-size pickup market  
for decades. The V8-powered Tundra, assembled in Princeton, Ind., 
is the first serious challenge by a foreign automaker in the 
full-size pickup market. 
</P>
<P>
	New models also helped boost Nissan Motor Co.'s sales up 5  
percent. The new Xterra sport utility vehicle had one of the best 
first month's sales figures in the company's history, with 5,470 
sold. The Nissan Crew cab pickup and Quest minivan also sold well, 
offsetting an 11 percent decline in car sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Honda Motor Co. set June and half-year records; its June sales  
increased just over 1.5 percent. The biggest percentage gains were 
for Honda's minivan and sport utility vehicles, led by a 277 
percent increase for the redesigned Odyssey minivan. 
</P>
<P>
	General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co. planned to report their  
June sales Friday. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
