<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Down on Weather / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices collapsed  
Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade after forecasters predicted 
hot, dry weather will not linger in the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors removed a weather premium that had buoyed the market  
earlier this week on fears that temperatures in the upper 90s 
across the Midwest and parts of the Plains would damage young 
crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Agronomists earlier had suggested corn crops in Illinois and  
Iowa, the two largest growing states, were particularly vulnerable 
since they are entering the crucial pollination period that sees 
ears beginning to fill out. 
</P>
<P>
	But while temperatures are expected to soar, beneficial rainfall  
has been and is expected to continue to fall across growing regions 
through the weekend. And the hot weather is expected to abate by 
midweek. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybean farmers this spring and early summer have  
enjoyed relatively few weather problems, putting them on track to 
harvest a record soybean crop and the fourth-largest corn crop on 
record, according to the U.S. Agriculture Department. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for September delivery fell 5 1/2 cents to $2.58 3/4 a bushel;  
September corn fell 8 cents to $2.08 1/4 a bushel; September oats fell 
3 3/4 cents to $1.11 1/2 a bushel; November soybeans fell 8 cents to 
$4.52 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures were mostly higher on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while pork futures were mostly lower. 
</P>
<P>
	August live cattle fell .25 cent to 62.37 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose 1.42 cents to 75.97 cents a pound; August lean 
hogs rose .03 cent to 44.60 cents a pound; August pork bellies fell 
.30 cent to 36.55 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
