<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Worried About Future Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Members of the Federal Reserve expressed  
concerns about future inflation at their May meeting, leading them 
to vote unanimously for a policy directive leaning toward an 
increase in interest rates, according to minutes of the meeting 
released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The minutes of the May 18 discussions showed that the members of  
the Federal Open Market Committee, composed of board members in 
Washington and regional bank presidents, were worried about a 
number of developments that seemed to suggest inflation could start 
to be a problem. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed, after its latest FOMC meeting, announced on Wednesday  
that it was raising the federal funds rate, the interest that banks 
charge each other on overnight loans, by a quarter-point to 5 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The FOMC set the stage for that rate increase by changing its  
policy directive at the May meeting from neutral to one that leaned 
in favor of a rate increase. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Fed officially announced the change in its directive  
immediately following the May discussions, the first time it has 
done so, the minutes released Thursday revealed the internal 
discussions that led to the change. 
</P>
<P>
	``Members commented that they saw few signs of any moderation in  
the expansion of economic activity from the rapid pace that had 
prevailed in recent quarters,'' the minutes said. 
</P>
<P>
	While the FOMC members agreed that recent improvement in the  
nation's productivity allowed more room for noninflationary 
economic growth, they worried that growth, which came in at a 4.3 
percent annual rate in the first quarter, was still too rapid to 
keep inflation under control. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel's May discussions occurred only days after the  
government reported that consumer prices, because of a surge in 
energy costs, shot up 0.7 percent in April, the worst showing in 
nine years. 
</P>
<P>
	``The firming of oil and other commodity prices, the more  
frequent anecdotal reports of increases in some costs and prices 
and the most recent CPI statistics could be read as suggesting at 
least that the trend toward lower inflation was coming to an end 
and perhaps also as harbingers of a less favorable inflation 
performance going forward,'' the minutes said in summarizing the 
closed-door deliberations. 
</P>
<P>
	FOMC members said that a key question about future inflation  
prospects was whether productivity, the output per hour of work, 
would continue posting the favorable gains of recent quarters. 
Those gains had allowed companies to pay for wage increases through 
increased output rather than being forced to raise prices to 
customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``While an upward trend in underlying inflation had not  
materialized thus far, the members were concerned that if recent 
developments continued, especially if demand did not slow to a more 
sustainable pace, inflation was more likely to rise over time,'' 
the minutes said. 
</P>
<P>
	The minutes showed the vote in May to change the policy stance  
from neutral to one leaning toward a rate increase was 11-0. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed announced along with Wednesday's rate increase that it  
had now returned the policy directive to a neutral stance, cheering 
investors who had feared that the Fed's first rate increase in two 
years could be followed by a series of increases. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed will reveal the vote for the increase in the funds rate  
and the change in the policy stance when it releases the minutes of 
the June 29-30 meeting on Aug. 26. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
