<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Archaeologists Find Child in S.C. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- Archaeologists looking for the remains  
of a Confederate submarine crew under the football stadium at The 
Citadel have discovered the body of a child from the same era in a 
glass-top coffin. 
</P>
<P>
	The discovery came yesterday during a search for the crew of the  
H.L. Hunley. 
</P>
<P>
	Some archaeologists think the child may have been buried next to  
its father in the former mariners' graveyard. Its body is encased 
in an expensive coffin with a full-length glass pane for a lid. 
</P>
<P>
	``One could see the sentiment of the time, allowing the child to  
be buried there,'' said Jonathan Leader of the state Institute of 
Archaeology and Anthropology. 
</P>
<P>
	The child could have died from any number of diseases that were  
rampant in Charleston at the time of the Civil War, Leader said. 
</P>
<P>
	The gender of the child has not been determined. Archaeologists  
first thought the child was as old as 11, which, if it were a boy, 
would have made him eligible to be a cabin boy or powder carrier in 
the Confederate Navy. But a forensic dentist determined the child 
was 3 to 5 years old. 
</P>
<P>
	Archaeologists hope to find the remains of four Hunley crewmen  
whose bodies were recovered after the submarine sank during a test 
run in 1863. Two sets of possible crewman's remains have been found 
so far in two stacked coffins in a single grave. 
</P>
<P>
	Confederate sailors were buried at the site when it was the  
city's cemetery for seamen. The site was covered over in 1948 when 
a 21,000-seat stadium was built at the state military college. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
