<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 07:50:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Exchanges, Online Brokers Wrangle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- It was a lot simpler when stock prices went  
out over the ticker, an invention that revolutionized the 
securities market in 1867 when it came to the New York Stock 
Exchange. Electronic transmission of market data arrived in the 
1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the Internet gives investors access to instantaneous  
stock quotations, but technology brings complications. Who owns the 
real-time stock quotes? The millions of online investors who 
``create'' them by trading or the stock exchanges? 
</P>
<P>
	Some lawmakers are proposing to protect market databases from  
hackers and pirates without giving the stock exchanges ownership 
rights, and the issue has pitted the exchanges against online 
brokers such as Schwab and Ameritrade. 
</P>
<P>
	The brokerage firms pay fees to the nation's stock exchanges for  
the market data, charges which totaled an estimated $414 million 
last year. The New York Stock Exchange, for example, charges the 
firms a penny every time they tap into a real-time stock quote. The 
NYSE has proposed reducing the fee to 0.75 cent, but the brokerages 
maintain that a one-time fee would make more sense than charging 
for each use. 
</P>
<P>
	With the explosion in online investing, real-time stock quotes  
are ``like oxygen to investors,'' Rep. Michael Oxley, R-Ohio, said 
at a hearing Wednesday of the House Commerce subcommittee on 
finance, which he heads. ``Stock prices are facts, just like any 
facts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Oxley noted that some observers, comparing stock quotes in this  
context to sports statistics, have maintained that giving the New 
York Stock Exchange an ownership right would be akin to Major 
League Baseball asserting a property right to Ted Williams's 
batting average in a given season. 
</P>
<P>
	Oxley, Rep. Thomas Bliley, R-Va., chairman of the full Commerce  
Committee, and some Democratic lawmakers have proposed legislation 
that seeks to protect market databases against hackers without 
bestowing new property rights. That way, Oxley said, the measure 
would preserve investors' access to stock price information. 
</P>
<P>
	Annette Nazareth, director of market regulation at the  
Securities and Exchange Commission, which oversees the financial 
markets, testified that the agency supports the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	She called it ``a balanced and reasonable legislative approach  
to continue the widespread availability of real-time market 
information.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A competing version, authored by Rep. Howard Coble, R-N.C.,  
would give the NYSE, the Nasdaq Stock Market and other exchanges 
more control over the databases. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Bernard, executive vice president and general counsel of  
the NYSE, said the nation's largest stock exchange needs the money 
it gets from selling data to run its operations and detect and 
prevent fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that consumers should have ready access to all  
types of financial information, including real-time market data,'' 
Bernard testified. ``The NYSE wants to disseminate as much 
real-time market data to the public (as possible). It is extremely 
easy to obtain free real-time market data on the Internet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Carrie Dwyer, executive vice president for corporate  
oversight at Charles Schwab and Co., which calls itself the biggest 
online brokerage in the world, said the public is the true owner of 
market data and it should be fairly priced. 
</P>
<P>
	The fees charged by the exchanges for the data unfairly  
discriminate against online brokerage firms as opposed to 
full-service traditional brokers, and are a ``hidden cost'' passed 
on to investors, Ms. Dwyer maintained. 
</P>
<P>
	``The cost of market data ... is the single greatest hurdle in  
providing investors with access to market data,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	And J. Joe Ricketts, chairman and Co-CEO of online brokerage  
Ameritrade, suggested it should be the other way around: the 
exchanges ought to pay the brokerage firms that provide the data to 
investors. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
