<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sens. Want To Expand Family Leave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Democratic senators want to expand the Family  
and Medical Leave Act to give parents up to 24 hours a year to 
participate in academic activities at their children's schools. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to give parents something they don't have enough of --  
time,'' said Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., who has introduced 
legislation to expand the six-year-old law. 
</P>
<P>
	Murray's bill has 11 Democratic cosponsors. It has drawn no  
support so far from majority Republicans. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters say the expansion should not add any cost to  
businesses because the 24 hours would come out of the 12 weeks of 
unpaid leave already available to care for a new child, a seriously 
ill family member or a personal illness. 
</P>
<P>
	The law only applies to companies with 50 or more workers, as  
would Murray's proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	The 24 hours would be available only for academic activities  
such as parent-teacher conferences, researching new schools or 
educational events; sports or other extracurricular activities 
would not be included. 
</P>
<P>
	Randel Johnson, a vice president for the U.S. Chamber of  
Commerce, the world's largest business federation, said the law 
already is troublesome. 
</P>
<P>
	Businesses have difficulty replacing workers because the unpaid  
leave can taken in fragmented segments, he said. Also, serious 
illness is defined loosely, creating confusion for administrators, 
he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Such problems ``ought to be looked at, reviewed and corrected  
before people talk about expanding it,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Murray's proposal is the latest to expand the 1993 law. Earlier  
this year, President Clinton and Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., 
the law's chief author, called for companies with more than 25 
workers to participate. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
