<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Babbitt Casino Probe Said Ending </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An investigation into whether Interior  
Secretary Bruce Babbitt lied to Congress about the rejection of a 
proposed Indian casino -- and whether campaign contributions were 
involved -- is nearing its conclusion, according to the special 
prosecutor. 
</P>
<P>
	Babbitt testified before a grand jury investigating the matter  
Wednesday, but neither his spokesman nor officials of the 
prosecutor's office would provide any details or even confirm the 
appearance. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Independent Counsel Carol Elder Bruce provided a  
glimpse of the progress being made in her investigation in a letter 
to the U.S. attorney's office in Wisconsin, a copy of which was 
made available Wednesday to The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	She said in the letter that she was ``nearing the end of our  
factual investigation and are in the process of reviewing the facts 
and the law in order to reach a final conclusion'' on whether to 
seek any indictments. 
</P>
<P>
	She estimated that she would complete the investigation by  
mid-August. She wrote the letter to request an additional 60-day 
postponement of consideration of a civil suit involving the casino 
decision. She previously had been granted three such postponements 
and wrote, ``I fully expect this to be the last request.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bruce has been concerned the civil suit would adversely affect  
the integrity of her 14-month investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The special prosecutor is trying to determine, among other  
things, whether Babbitt lied under oath before a Senate committee 
about the circumstances surrounding the decision in 1995 to reject 
a casino application from three Chippewa tribes. 
</P>
<P>
	Bruce is also looking into whether promises of Democratic  
campaign contributions by opponents of the casino influenced the 
decision. Tribes opposing the casino later gave the Democratic 
National Committee nearly $300,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Babbitt has vigorously denied any connection between campaign  
contributions and the decision to reject the casino planned in 
Hudson, Wis. He also has denied intending to mislead senators 
during a sometimes contentious hearing on the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	But a longtime friend, Paul Eckstein, who was a lobbyist for the  
tribes seeking the casino, testified to the same Senate 
Governmental Affairs Committee that Babbitt -- during a meeting the 
day the casino decision was made -- alluded to Democratic campaign 
contributions and pressure from the White House. 
</P>
<P>
	Babbitt has said Eckstein misunderstood the conversation and has  
denied misleading lawmakers about the events leading up to the 
casino decision. He also said he made one remark, referring to 
White House pressure, simply to get Eckstein out of the office, and 
that, in fact, there was no such pressure. 
</P>
<P>
	Babbitt's appearance Wednesday before the grand jury was his  
first. It could not be learned how long he testified, or whether he 
was scheduled to return. 
</P>
<P>
	Interior Department spokesman Mike Gauldin referred questions to  
Babbitt's personal lawyer, Lloyd Cutler, who did not return a phone 
call to his office. 
</P>
<P>
	The contents of the Bruce letter was first reported Wednesday by  
the Minneapolis Star Tribune. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
