<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Stocks Rise; Dow Closes at 11,066.42  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average extended its  
stunning gains today, flirting with a record high as investors 
reveled in the new interest rate environment. At the close on Wall 
Street, the Dow was up 95.62 at 11,066.42. The blue-chip index held 
steadily above 11,000 for the first time in weeks, and inched 
within 28 points of its May 13 record high close of 11,107.19. 
Broader stock indicators also rose. The Nasdaq Composite index was 
up 20.09 at 2,706.21, its second record close in as many days. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        11,066.42  + 95.62
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1,701  Declines 1,374  Unchgd  484
NYSE Volume:         803,758,760
Most Active NYSE issue:        America Online112 3/4   + 2 3/4
S&AMP;P 500:         1380.96  + 8.25
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          794.95  -  2.98
Nasdaq Composite Index        2,706.21  + 20.09
Gold(final) -    $263.90    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.

</P>
<P>
	Manufacturing Up; Construction Down  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The nation's manufacturing sector expanded for  
the fifth straight month in June, and at a stronger pace than 
expected, according to a survey of corporate purchasing managers 
released today. Growth in new orders at the nation's factories 
indicated the upward trend will continue. The National Association 
of Purchasing Agents' monthly index of business activity rose to 57 
percent in June from 55.2 percent in May, In Washington, meanwhile, 
the Commerce Department reported construction spending fell in May 
for a second straight month. That indicated that one of the 
economy's strongest sectors is starting to slow, in part because 
mortgage rates have been rising. The May decline was 0.9 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler's U.S. Sales Fall  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- European automakers again posted some of the  
biggest percentage gains in the U.S. market last month, while the 
Chrysler unit of DaimlerChrysler AG saw sales fall 5 percent 
compared with record sales a year ago. Most European automakers who 
reported today had double-digit gains compared with June 1998, 
which also was a robust month for U.S. sales of cars and light 
trucks. Volkswagen AG reported its strongest June in 26 years and 
its best month overall since May 1979. Its sales were up 23 percent 
over a year ago. Audi AG had its most successful June since 1987 
with a 44 percent sales increase. Despite the drop in June sales 
for DaimlerChrysler's Chrysler, Plymouth, Dodge and Jeep brands, 
the German-American automaker said the unit posted a record first 
half with just over 1.39 million sales, and had its best quarter 
ever in April through June. 

</P>
<P>
	Summers Confirmed for Treasury Post  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate confirmed Lawrence Summers today to  
become Treasury Secretary, elevating him from his No. 2 slot in the 
department to succeed the outgoing Robert Rubin. Senators approved 
Summers' nomination by 97-2, underlining the lack of controversy 
that had accompanied his selection by President Clinton. Summers, 
44, joined Treasury in 1993 as undersecretary for international 
affairs, and has served as Rubin's deputy since 1995. 

</P>
<P>
	Computer Export Restrictions Eased  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton eased export restrictions on  
computers today, making it easier for the high-technology industry 
to sell more powerful systems to foreign countries. ``These 
policies will strengthen America's high-tech competitiveness, while 
maintaining controls that are needed to maintain our national 
security,'' Clinton said in a written statement. The industry had 
sought the change because current restrictions, designed to keep 
advanced technology out of the hands of hostile militaries, have 
failed to keep up with the advances in commercially available 
computers. 

</P>
<P>
	Dell Chairman Sees Overseas Growth  
</P>
<P>
	AUSTIN (AP) -- Dell Computer Corp., the nation's largest direct  
seller of computers, can grow considerably overseas over the next 
few years, Chairman Michael Dell says. ``In Europe, we have a 
business that's roughly $6 billion in size,'' Dell said last night. 
``Essentially, in the United Kingdom, we're pretty much tied for 
No. 1.... Our models work better there than in the U.S.'' The 
company, which sells a majority of its computers to businesses, 
governments and other public institutions, reported revenues 
exceeding $5.5 billion in the fiscal quarter that ended in April, 
up 41 percent from a year ago. 

</P>
<P>
	AOL, Prodigy Offer Free Computers  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- America Online Inc. and Prodigy Communications  
Corp., two major providers of Internet access, have joined an 
industry push to offer consumers free personal computers if they 
agree to sign up for online service. While smaller companies 
started giving away PCs last year, AOL and Prodigy are the biggest 
examples yet of how the plunging price of computers is fast making 
them into just a delivery mechanism for services and software. 

</P>
<P>
	Auto Analyst Joins Priceline.com  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Maryann Keller, a respected Wall Street analyst  
and author of two books on General Motors and the auto industry, 
has joined the Internet buying service Priceline.com Inc. to 
oversee expansion of its new-car buying program. Keller was lead 
auto analyst at ING Baring Furman Selz LLC for the past 13 years. 

</P>
<P>
	Starbucks Expects Lower Profits  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Starbucks Corp. shares tumbled today after the  
coffee retailer warned that shortfalls in its non-core businesses 
and the cost of launching a new Internet portal will result in 
lower than expected earnings for the next two quarters and for the 
year. Analysts had estimated the gourmet coffee retailer would earn 
60 cents per share for fiscal 1999. But Starbucks late yesterday 
predicted earnings of 54 cents per share, with earnings over the 
next two quarters coming up 3 cents short of expectations. Company 
executives had expected that strong retail sales in Starbucks core 
coffee business would make up the difference, but that didn't 
happen, CEO Howard Schultz said. Starbuck shares were down 10 5/8 at 
26 15/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Singapore Firm On Trader's Trail  
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- A Singapore law firm said today that it plans  
to keep investigating whether the securities trader blamed for the 
collapse of Britain's oldest bank has any money hidden away. The 
rogue trader, Nick Leeson, is scheduled to be released from a 
Singapore prison as early as Saturday. Working from his base in 
Singapore, Leeson, a Briton, made unauthorized futures trades that 
eventually lost $1.4 billion and led to the collapse of Barings 
Bank in 1995. 

</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong, Disney Discuss Theme Park  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Hong Kong and Walt Disney Co. officials said  
they will need four more months of discussions to resolve economic 
issues before reaching a deal on a Disney theme park. ``We're not 
talking about dating any more -- we're talking about money,'' 
Stephen Ip, Hong Kong's secretary of economic services, told a news 
conference. Hong Kong officials declined to go into details of 
their negotiations, citing a confidentiality clause. Disney had no 
comment. 

</P>
