<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T Drops Rates, Hikes Monthly Fees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- AT&AMP;T lowered long-distance rates for basic  
residential customers, passing on savings from a government-ordered 
reduction in the fees long-distance companies pay to local carriers 
to connect calls. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, the company also announced that certain  
monthly charges would go up, prompting consumer groups to contend 
that these increases would offset the decline in rates for most 
residential phone users. 
</P>
<P>
	Customers not enrolled in one of the company's calling plans  
will see a drop of 2 cents, from 28 cents to 26 cents, per minute 
for Monday through Friday daytime calls. Basic rate weekend calling 
will decline to 11 cents per minute from 11.5 cents. 
</P>
<P>
	``The trend in the industry is that long distance rates are  
going down because of the decline in the access fee,'' said Jim 
McGann, a spokesman for AT&AMP;T. 
</P>
<P>
	Long-distance companies also have sought to restructure the way  
such charges are passed on to consumers, by moving them out of 
per-minute rates and into flat-rate fees. AT&AMP;T announced an 
increase in the ``carrier line charge,'' which the company collects 
from residential customers to reimburse local phone companies. 
Starting July 1, this charge will rise from 85 cents to $1.51. 
</P>
<P>
	Another line-item charge, the ``universal connectivity charge,''  
which goes to a fund that supports affordable phone service in high 
cost areas and telephone service for schools and libraries, will 
increase by 6 cents to 99 cents. 
</P>
<P>
	But consumer groups say many residential phone users do not use  
enough long-distance time to balance out the increases in the 
monthly charges. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the vast majority of consumers, AT&AMP;T's rate reduction  
comes nowhere near offsetting these new monthly fees, leaving 
consumers with higher bills even though costs to long distance 
companies are coming down dramatically,'' said Gene Kimmelman of 
Consumers Union. 
</P>
<P>
	Only high-volume users, such as businesses, are likely to  
benefit from the changes, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Communications Commission Chairman Bill Kennard said  
earlier this week the half-billion-dollar reduction in access fees 
makes available to long distance companies should be used to lower 
long-distance rates for consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	``If consumers see higher flat fees without reduced per-minute  
rates, they may want to shop around for another long-distance 
company,'' Kennard advised. 
</P>
<P>
	MCI said Thursday that it has not yet determined how the  
reductions in access charges will be passed on to their customers. 
Previous reductions were used to offer customers 5-cents-per-minute 
calling on Sundays, instead of a decrease in basic rates, said MCI 
spokesman Brad Burns. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we do know is our customers will continue to fully  
benefit from access reductions as they have in the past,'' Burn 
said. MCI will be increasing its universal service charge -- which 
goes into the fund for schools and libraries -- from 6 percent to 
7.2 percent of the customer's monthly usage bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Sprint was expected to announce changes associated with the  
restructuring in access charges on Friday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
