<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Germans Find Kosovo Massacre Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- German peacekeepers today uncovered  
new evidence of mass killings by Serb paramilitary forces, some of 
whom might still be operating in Kosovo in violation of the NATO 
peace deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The commander of U.S. peacekeepers warned that his soldiers face  
a continuing threat from the Serb paramilitaries who remained in 
the province despite a peace agreement stipulating that all 
Yugoslav forces should be gone by now. 
</P>
<P>
	In southwestern Kosovo, German troops found the graves of 119  
people whom villagers said were murdered by Serbs on March 25 -- a 
day after NATO began bombing Yugoslavia. The bodies were found near 
Celine and Nagafc, and local villagers said they believed more 
victims remain undiscovered. 
</P>
<P>
	German troops took reporters today to Celine but were unable to  
continue to nearby Nagafc, a half-mile away, because of land mines. 
German officers said both villages appeared to have been targeted 
by Serbs who burned and buried some of the victims. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are dead bodies still lying inside houses in that  
village,'' said Lt. Col. Dietmar Jeserich, referring to Nagafc. 
</P>
<P>
	In Celine, villagers said Myftar Zeqiri, 60, and 22 other  
members of his family were later buried by survivors in a common 
grave, about 100 yards from their house. Clothes, mattresses and 
shoes were still strewn over a path leading from the burned-up 
house to the grave. 
</P>
<P>
	``They'd been hiding there when the Serbs found them and killed  
them all,'' said Hamid Rexhepi, a relative. 
</P>
<P>
	In Pristina, U.S. Brig. Gen. John Craddock said his troops still  
face threats from both remnants of the Serb forces and from ethnic 
Albanian rebels who don't want to disarm. He declined to say which 
was a greater threat. 
</P>
<P>
	He added, however, that U.S. forces were investigating reports  
that Serb paramilitaries are still operating in Kosovo. American 
troops came under sniper fire twice last week but suffered no 
casualties. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a dangerous environment out there,'' he said. ``There are  
elements ... who wish KFOR forces ill,'' referring to the 
peacekeepers by their acronym. ``This is not going to be a quick 
fix. There are still too many acts of violence. There are still too 
many homes burning at night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some 860,000 ethnic Albanians fled Serb forces and Kosovo  
beginning in March; more than half have returned since the war 
ended last month. 
</P>
<P>
	In Belgrade, meanwhile, the government appeared to be pursuing a  
two-track strategy: overtures to certain opposition groups while 
cracking down on others demanding President Slobodan Milosevic's 
resignation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Belgrade military court has launched a criminal  
investigation against opposition leader Zoran Djindjic for failing 
to respond to a draft notice during the 78-day NATO bombing 
campaign, his lawyer Sinisa Nikolic said. Such an investigation is 
often the first step toward a formal indictment. 
</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav Prime Minister Momir Bulatovic summoned other parties  
to a meeting today to discuss how to rebuild the country. The 
invitation appeared aimed at exploiting divisions in opposition 
ranks. 
</P>
<P>
	The invitation came on Wednesday, one day after some 10,000  
people rallied in a central Serbian city calling for Milosevic's 
resignation in the first such protest since the NATO bombing 
campaign ended on June 12. 
</P>
<P>
	Parties in the Alliance for Change, which organized the rally,  
were not invited to the meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	The ultranationalist Serbian Radical Party, the moderate Serbian  
Renewal Movement, and reformists in Yugoslavia's smaller republic 
Montenegro were invited. The Montenegro reformists -- the Democratic 
Party of Socialists -- immediately rejected the offer. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
