<DOCNO> APW19990701.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 16:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Both Parties Excel at Fundraising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With control of both houses of Congress at  
stake in the 2000 election, two party committees that help 
congressional candidates are taking in record amounts of campaign 
cash this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Republican Congressional Committee raised $26  
million between Jan. 1 and June 30. The Democratic Senatorial 
Campaign Committee took in $12 million during the same period. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic National Committee, meanwhile, reported that it  
had finally raised enough to retire its debt from the 1996 
elections, when the DNC refunded around $3 million amid allegations 
that the contributions illegally came from foreign sources. 
</P>
<P>
	The DNC reported taking in more than $21 million during the  
first six months of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	The figures include money raised under federal contribution  
limits that can be used to directly aid congressional candidates, 
and the unregulated contributions from corporations, labor unions 
and individuals known as soft money. 
</P>
<P>
	The party committees reported their hauls a day after Texas Gov.  
George W. Bush smashed fund-raising records for presidential 
campaigns, taking in more than $36 million so far. 
</P>
<P>
	The three other main party committees -- the Republican National  
Committee, the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee and the 
National Republican Senatorial Committee -- declined to release 
their midyear fund-raising totals Thursday. They do not have to 
file with the Federal Election Commission until later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican congressional committee's fund-raising is up 63  
percent from the first six months of 1997, when it raised $16 
million. The NRCC also paid off its $3.6 million debt from last 
fall. 
</P>
<P>
	``Set a pro-famliy, pro-growth agenda and Americans will respond  
with their hearts and wallets,'' said NRCC Chairman Tom Davis, 
R-Va. ``The NRCC's record-setting budget numbers and recent 
congressional generic ballot figures prove it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One way the NRCC raises money is by inviting industry  
representatives who donate $10,000 apiece to discuss issues with 
key GOP lawmakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Representatives of the technology industry breakfasted Thursday  
with Davis; Rep. Thomas Bliley, R-Va., chairman of the House 
Commerce Committee; and Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., chairman of 
Commerce's telecommunications subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic Senate committee, which raised more than $8  
million during the first six months of 1997, surpassed that total 
by almost 50 percent this year, taking in $12 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our supporters recognize that this is perhaps the most  
important election cycle in a generation,'' said the DSCC's 
chairman, Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J. ``They have been energized 
by the successes of the 1998 cycle and are committed to building 
the strength -- both financial and organizational -- to restore a 
Democratic majority.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic National Committee reported raising more than $21  
million between Jan. 1 and June 30, enough to finish paying off its 
debt from the 1996 elections. Two years ago, the debt stood at $16 
million. As of March 31, the debt was $9.3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The party took in slightly more than the amount of money it  
raised during the same period two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee,  
John Del Cecato, would say only that the committee expected to 
reach its goal of $14 million for the first six months of 1999. 
That would be double the $7 million the committee raised during the 
same period two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican senatorial committee, which reports monthly,  
raised almost $11 million through May 31. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican National Committee raised almost $32 million  
through May 31. Between Jan. 1 and June 30, 1997, the RNC took in 
$39 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
