<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study Reveals Campus Gun Possession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- About 3.5 percent of college students have guns at  
school, a statistic that doubles among students with serious 
alcohol problems, Harvard researchers said in a study to be 
published Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	With 14 million students in the nation's four-year and two-year  
colleges, that means there are as many as 450,000 students with 
guns, said Dr. Matthew Miller, a senior researcher at Harvard's 
Injury Research and Control Center. 
</P>
<P>
	The report is based on a sample of some 15,000 students at 130  
four-year colleges and did not account for hunting weapons. The 
results appear in the July issue of The Journal of American College 
Health. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun possession is significantly more likely among students who  
binge drink and drive or who damage property after drinking, the 
report said. Binge drinking was defined as having five or more 
drinks at a sitting. 
</P>
<P>
	The connection is worrisome, said Henry Wechsler, principal  
investigator at the Harvard School of Public Health College Alcohol 
Study. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same, however, ``I don't want to give the impression that  
there are thousands of drunk college students shooting people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The study was based on 1997 questionnaires filled out  
anonymously by students. The questionnaire primarily focused on 
alcohol use, but also asked students if they had a working firearm 
at school. 
</P>
<P>
	Results showed that 3.5 percent of students surveyed said they  
owned guns. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall number increased to 7 percent among those who said  
they were likely to binge drink and drive or damage property after 
drinking. 
</P>
<P>
	The study had a margin of error of 1 percentage point.  
</P>
<P>
	Although it's possible some students may have been lying or  
exaggerating on their questionnaires, Miller said he takes their 
answers seriously because the forms were anonymous. 
</P>
<P>
	The study also found gun possession at college was more common  
among whites than among minority groups, and more prevalent among 
students who belonged to fraternities or sororities. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun ownership differed according to the region of the country.  
</P>
<P>
	Six percent of students attending colleges in the South had  
guns, compared with 4 percent in the West and 1 percent in the 
Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey also found that two-thirds of the student gunowners  
live off-campus. Although most colleges prohibit guns on campus, 
researchers estimate students keep at least 100,000 guns in the 
nation's dormitories. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
