<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Victims Decry Okla. Bombing Ruling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Victims of the Oklahoma City bombing denounced a  
decision by a federal appeals court to toss out the 12-year prison 
sentence given to Michael Fortier, the man who failed to alert 
authorities to the plot. 
</P>
<P>
	``What makes me more upset than anything against Fortier is that  
this man was technically out of it and all he had to do was make 
one dang phone call to prevent it from happening,'' said Dan 
McKinney, whose wife, Secret Service Agent Linda McKinney, was 
killed in the 1995 blast. ``He's going to get slapped on the 
wrist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled Wednesday that  
Fortier's sentence should have been based on guidelines for 
involuntarily manslaughter rather than the significantly higher 
guidelines for first-degree murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortier, 30, pleaded guilty to having advance knowledge of the  
plot to bomb the building. He testified against Timothy McVeigh and 
Terry Nichols, admitting he helped McVeigh move and sell stolen 
weapons and lied to FBI agents. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court said even though Fortier's conduct ``bordered  
on recklessness,'' the district court went too far using 
first-degree murder guidelines to set his sentence and $200,000 
fine. 
</P>
<P>
	The lesser guidelines would have put Fortier's sentence at a  
maximum of 51 months, said his lawyer, Michael McGuire. Fortier 
began serving his sentence in August 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Myron Marlin, a Justice Department spokesman, wouldn't comment  
until prosecutors had a chance to review the opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	The bombing killed 168 people and injured hundreds more.  
</P>
<P>
	McVeigh was convicted of murder, conspiracy and weapons charges.  
He is appealing his death sentence. Nichols was convicted of 
involuntary manslaughter and conspiracy and sentenced to life in 
prison. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
