<HEADLINE> Stocks Mostly Higher; Dow Up 39.58 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher today, with blue chips  
inching back to record levels, as investors got their bearings in 
the new interest rate environment. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up  
39.58 at 11,010.38 after searching for a direction in morning 
trading. Since hitting a new closing high of 11,107.19 on May 13, 
the Dow has struggled to revisit the 11,000 level. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also reversed early losses. The  
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 2.77 to 1,375.43, and the Nasdaq 
composite index was up 17.79 to 2,703.91. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock prices briefly faltered in tandem with bond prices, which  
dropped after the National Association of Purchasing Management 
reported the manufacturing sector expanded at a 
stronger-than-expected pace in June. The report suggested the 
threats of inflation that first prompted the Federal Reserve to 
raise interest rates Wednesday may not have evaporated. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock and bond markets rallied after the Fed followed  
through on expectations and raised rates one-quarter percentage 
point. But bonds sank today, pushing the yield on the 30-year 
Treasury bond to 6.06 percent, up from 5.96 late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	By midday, stocks were shrugging off the bond market's concerns.  
``A little hiccup in bond land is not likely to end the mania on 
Wall Street,'' said William Meehan, chief market analyst for Cantor 
Fitzgerald. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock investors sent the Dow up 155.45 points and the S&AMP;P 500  
and the Nasdaq to new closing highs Wednesday after the Fed's 
announcement. More than the rate increase, which was widely 
expected and frequently telegraphed by Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan, 
investors applauded the Fed's policy shift to a ``neutral'' bias on 
the need for future rate increases. 
</P>
<P>
	Gourmet coffee company Starbucks tumbled after surprising Wall  
Street with a forecast of lower than expected earnings for the next 
two quarters and for the year. Starbucks shares fell 12 3/8 to 25 
3/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Drug stocks were mostly higher, led by Eli Lilly, which gained 2  
1/16 to 73 11/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues barely outnumbered decliners on the New York  
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 382.94 million shares, ahead 
of Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 0.89 at 649.02, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was down 3.92 at 794.01. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
