<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gun Cos. Sued in Accidental Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The families of two children who accidentally  
shot themselves in the head sued two gunmakers Thursday, claiming 
they are responsible for not making their weapons childproof. 
</P>
<P>
	The suits seek $6 million for the family of 3-year-old Jordan  
Garris, who died after accidentally shooting himself in the head on 
June 6, and $1.25 million for the family of 8-year-old Nino Jacobs, 
who accidentally shot himself in the head two years ago and 
survived. 
</P>
<P>
	Gunmakers Sturm, Ruger &AMP; Company of Southport, Conn. and Lorcin  
Engineering Co. of Mira Loma, Calif., as well as On Target, Inc., a 
Severn, Md. gun distributor are named as defendants in the suits. 
On Target is accused in the Garris suit of knowingly selling 
``defective'' guns and failing to warn customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no reason why it should be easier for a child to fire  
a gun than open an aspirin bottle,'' attorney Andrew Freeman said. 
</P>
<P>
	In each case, Freeman contends the gunmakers negligently  
produced defective and unreasonably dangerous weapons which did not 
include devices to prevent their use by young children. The 
gunmakers are also accused of failing to adequately warn buyers of 
the dangers the guns posed to young children. 
</P>
<P>
	Freeman said the industry developed a childproof safety grip as  
early as the 1880s, but sells guns without such safety devices or 
warnings. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Jacobs case, the suit describes Lorcin Engineering as  
``one of the leading makers of handguns used by criminals in 
America.'' The suit claims the company ``pandered to its market and 
excluded these child-resistant devices that criminals do not 
desire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Waldorf, co-owner and president of Lorcin Engineering, said  
he could not comment on the specifics of the suit, which he had not 
received. 
</P>
<P>
	Waldorf said all of the guns manufactured by his company have  
safety devices and some are manufactured with a handle grip safety 
device. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the owner of the gun operates and leaves it stored in the  
proper fashion, there certainly is no risk of a child getting 
shot,'' Waldorf said. ``We'll vigorously defend any type of 
frivolous litigation. I have not seen the suit, but on the surface 
it appears to be another piece of frivolous litigation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A telephone call by The Associated Press on Thursday to Ruger  
headquarters was not immediately returned. On Target declined to 
comment on the suit. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference Thursday, Freeman displayed a circa 1894  
Smith &AMP; Wesson handgun that incorporated a metal lever on the back 
of the handgrip which prevented the weapon from being fired unless 
it was depressed. Children are unable to fire the weapon because 
their hands are not strong enough to depress the lever and pull the 
trigger, Freeman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The suits are the latest in a series against gun manufacturers,  
including several filed by cities seeking reimbursement for costs 
incurred as a result of gun violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Lorcin emerged from Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection six months  
ago after being hit with two dozen product liability suits, company 
officials have previously said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
