<HEADLINE> AP Clarifies Cuban Economy Story </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- In a June 30 story on a panel discussion of the  
Cuban economy, The Associated Press quoted Arturo Villar, publisher 
of the newsletter Hispanic Market Weekly as saying Cuba's 
government would collapse amid anarchy within months if the United 
States were to lift its economic embargo. In the panel discussion, 
Villar said Cuba is now in a state of anarchy in the sense that, in 
his view, the government has no coherent economic policy beyond 
retaining power. He predicted a rapid collapse of the government if 
the embargo were lifted, an action he favors, but he is not 
predicting more anarchy. 
  	   	
