<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Penn St. Defensive Coach To Retire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STATE COLLEGE -- Jerry Sandusky, who turned Penn State into  
``Linebacker U'' in 31 seasons as defensive coordinator, will 
retire after the 1999 season. 
</P>
<P>
	As an assistant to Joe Paterno, Sandusky has coached teams  
through four unbeaten seasons and two national championships, and 
has also had nine first-team All-Americans. As one of four 
assistants who have been at Penn State for more than two decades, 
he was seen as a candidate to replace the 72-year-old Paterno one 
day. 
</P>
<P>
	In making the announcement Thursday, Sandusky said he wants to  
spend more time working with The Second Mile, a charity he founded 
for kids. 
</P>
<P>
	``As the organization has grown, the demands for my hands-on  
involvement have increased dramatically,'' he said in a written 
statement. ``The staff has done a marvelous job of building the 
organization, which now touches more than 150,000 children 
annually.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Friends and family said the charity would keep him plenty busy.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's not like he's retiring,'' said his wife, Dorothy. ``But  
we'll be pleased with it. We have one grandchild and another one on 
the way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Nittany Lions are ranked as high as No. 1 in preseason  
polls, an expectation based in no small part because of the 
defensive unit. Nine starters return on a defense that ranked in 
the top 15 last year, including defensive end Courtney Brown, 
linebackers Short and LaVar Arrington, and cornerback David 
Macklin. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
