<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel Blocks USDA Dairy Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House members eager to block an Agriculture  
Department plan to overhaul the government's milk pricing program 
have cleared a legislative hurdle. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Agriculture Committee voted 32-15 in favor of a bill  
that would prevent Secretary Dan Glickman from implementing the 
system he proposed in April. The measure now goes before the full 
House, but members from the Midwest have promised to fight it. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's vote came after a four-hour hearing that included  
calls by some lawmakers to scrap the milk program. 
</P>
<P>
	``This backward system robs too many of our nation's dairy  
farmers of the opportunity to compete and prosper,'' said Rep. John 
Boehner, R-Ohio, who tried unsuccessfully to pass an amendment to 
phase out the system. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue are the nation's milk pricing regions, which are  
divided into what are called milk marketing orders. The orders set 
the price that processors pay dairy farmers, much like a minimum 
wage. 
</P>
<P>
	The price is higher the farther a farm is from Eau Claire, Wis.,  
which was considered the center of dairy production when the 
pricing system was established more than 50 years ago as a way to 
ensure all regions had sufficient milk supplies. The higher prices 
in other areas encourage farmers in the South, for instance, to 
produce milk. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics said the current system pits region against region -- all  
to the detriment of farmers in the Upper Midwest, where prices are 
kept the lowest. 
</P>
<P>
	The USDA plan attempts to close the disparity. It would increase  
the minimum price by 11 cents in Minnesota and 15 cents in 
Wisconsin from 2000 to 2006, according to a University of Missouri 
study. The price would fall 5 cents nationwide and far more in 
other states, as much as 46 cents in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Farmers in all regions of the country ought to have the  
opportunity to make a living,'' said Rep. John Sweeney, R-N.Y. 
``This proposal ensures fair market prices for farmers and 
reasonably priced, locally produced milk for consumers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Herb Kohl, D-Wis., said supporters of the House action want  
to ``maintain our current antiquated dairy pricing system.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's time our dairy pricing system is brought up to date,''  
Kohl said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
