<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Moves To Block IMF Gold Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two Republican lawmakers took the first step  
Thursday to block the proposed sale of IMF gold reserves to help 
reduce poor countries' debt. 
</P>
<P>
	House Majority Leader Dick Armey of Texas and Rep. Jim Saxton of  
New Jersey, vice chairman of the Joint Economic Committee, 
introduced legislation that would prohibit the sales unless the 
profits are returned to IMF member states. 
</P>
<P>
	Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said Monday that Congress should  
approve the sales to help fund the debt relief initiative, which 
was approved by the world's seven wealthiest nations at their 
summit last month in Cologne, Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the plan, they agreed to sell up to 10 million ounces of  
gold, worth an estimated $2.6 billion, of the IMF's 104 million 
ounces of gold reserves. But IMF rules say congressional approval 
is needed for the sale. 
</P>
<P>
	With the gold prices at a 20-year low of less than $265 a troy  
ounce after several central banks announced plans to sell the 
precious metal, there are fears that the IMF sales will drive the 
price lower and hurt export earnings of poor, gold-producing 
nations, some of them in Africa. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF says it would sell the gold in a way that would have  
minimal impact on the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Saxton said the plan to sell IMF gold lacks accountability.  
</P>
<P>
	``Given the choice of channeling billions to the IMF bureaucracy  
or reserving it for the taxpayers, it is virtually impossible to 
think that the Congress will endorse'' the gold sale plan, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	To help finance its part of the $27.5 billion debt relief  
initiative, Saxton said the IMF should borrow money from 
international capital markets as its sister institution, the World 
Bank, has done for years. 
</P>
<P>
	``However if the IMF wishes to gradually dispose of the gold at  
some future point, this bill ensures that the large, hidden 
potential gold profits are returned to the member countries and 
their taxpayers and not retained by the IMF bureaucracy for its own 
purposes,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
