<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 11:10 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Construction Spending Down 0.9 Pct.  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Construction spending fell in May for a second  
straight month, the first time that has happened in two years, 
indicating one of the economy's strongest sectors is starting to 
slow down. The Commerce Department said today that spending dropped 
by 0.9 percent in May, after falling by 2 percent in April. The 
declines were fairly widespread, with decreases reported in 
single-family homes, apartment buildings, hotels and motels and big 
government construction projects. The decrease was not expected. 
Many analysts had expected construction spending to rise by 1 
percent in May. 

</P>
<P>
	Jobless Claims Fall by 5,000  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of Americans filing new claims for  
unemployment benefits fell unexpectedly last week. The Labor 
Department said today that 299,000 Americans filed new claims for 
jobless benefits for the week ending June 26 -- down by 5,000 from 
the previous week. Many analysts had expected a slight rise in 
jobless claims. The four-week moving average for claims, which 
helps smooth out week-to-week volatility, also was down to 307,000, 
the lowest level since May 29 when they were at 305,500. 

</P>
<P>
	Continued Manufacturing Growth Seen  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The manufacturing sector grew in June for the  
fifth straight month, and a rising backlog of orders at the 
nation's factories indicates growth should continue, according to a 
survey of corporate purchasing executives released today. The 
National Association of Purchasing Management said 16 of 20 
industries reported a pickup in business. ``Both production and new 
orders exhibited significant growth when compared to May,'' said 
Norbert J. Ore, head of the trade group's survey committee. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Move Lower; Dow Down 23.43  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved lower today as investors pondered  
their course in the new interest rate environment. Just before 11 
a.m. EDT, the Dow Jones industrial average was down 23.43 at 
10,947.37. Broader stock indicators were posting narrower losses. 
The Nasdaq composite index was down 3.86 at 2,682.26. Bond prices 
responded most dramatically today to the Federal Reserve's decision 
to raise interest rates one-quarter percentage point. After a rally 
yesterday afternoon, bond prices sank today, pushing the yield on 
the 30-year Treasury bond to 6.04 percent, up from 5.96 late 
yesterday. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before 11 a.m. EDT  
