</P>
<P>
	Download Delays Bug Online Shoppers  
</P>
<P>
	REDWOOD CITY, Calif. (AP) -- As much as $4.35 billion in  
electronic commerce may be lost annually in the United States 
because online shoppers frustrated with slow download times simply 
give up making a purchase, a study says. A study released yesterday 
by Zona Research says one-third of online shoppers may not buy an 
item over the Internet because of the slowness of the experience, 
whether caused by their own modems or a failure at a Web site. A 
crash at the eBay auction Web site in early June indicated how 
costly any failure can be for an e-commerce Web site. The Web site 
was down for about 24 hours on June 10 and 11, resulting in a 
revenue loss of between $3 million and $5 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton To Sign Y2K Lawsuit Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation aimed at avoiding legal  
aftershocks from Year 2000 computer problems headed for a final 
vote in Congress today. The White House said the president, after 
lengthy negotiations over consumer protections, would sign the 
bill. The bill aimed at stemming a flood of lawsuits from possible 
computer breakdowns was assured of a big victory in the House 
today, followed by another strong show of approval in the Senate. 

</P>
<P>
	Markets Discuss After-Hours Trading  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Leaders of the major U.S. stock markets appear  
ready to cooperate with one another, to appease regulators, as they 
move to extend stock trading into the late evening and early 
morning hours. At a summit in Wall Street's back yard yesterday, 
Securities and Exchange Commission chairman Arthur Levitt stressed 
that all U.S. markets should open and close at the same time, 
despite varying proposals from the Nasdaq Stock Market and the New 
York Stock Exchange. Levitt said it would be too confusing for 
investors to have different exchanges open different hours. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Phone Giant NTT Reorganizes  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese telecommunications company Nippon  
Telegraph and Telephone Corp. implemented its long-planned 
corporate reorganization today, creating a holding company with 
three phone company subsidiaries. The move marks part of a major 
overhaul in Japan's once highly regulated phone and communications 
industry. NTT is the world's second largest telecommunications 
company after AT&AMP;T Corp. of the United States. Under the 
restructuring, NTT split its business operations into two regional 
telephone companies and one long-distance and international unit, 
NTT spokesman Kazuhiko Nishizawa said. 

</P>
<P>
	Asian Stock Markets Rally  
</P>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets soared ahead today, boosted  
by news that the U.S. Federal Reserve sees no pressing need to 
raise interest rates again. In Tokyo, Asia's largest market, stocks 
closed sharply higher on the news that had lifted Wall Street 
prices yesterday. Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average 
soared 331.01 points, or 1.9 percent, to 17,860.75, its highest 
close since Sept. 30, 1997, when it ended at 17,887.71. In 
Singapore, the U.S. rate announcement drove the benchmark index to 
its third record close in the past two weeks. The benchmark Straits 
Times Index finished at 2214.75 points, up 47.05 points, or 2.2 
percent. Hong Kong, Taipei and Bangkok financial markets were 
closed today for holidays. 

</P>
