<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Mubarak Wants New Middle East Talks  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak today said he  
would meet with Israeli and Arab leaders to try to revive Mideast 
negotiations. ``We remain most willing and determined to do all we 
can,'' he said after talks with President Clinton. At a joint White 
House news conference, Clinton said he expected to be talk with 
Israeli prime minister-elect Ehud Barak soon now that Barak is 
close to forming a new government. ``We now have a real chance to 
move the peace process forward in the Middle East,'' Clinton said. 

</P>
<P>
	Woman Claims $150M Powerball Prize  
</P>
<P>
	ROSEVILLE, Minn. (AP) -- A 21-year-old woman claimed a $150  
million Powerball jackpot prize at lottery headquarters today. 
Farrah Slad, who lives in central Minnesota, held the only winning 
ticket for last night's drawing. She chose to collect all the money 
in a lump sum worth $78.8 million rather than the jackpot that 
would be worth $150 million if taken over 25 years. After state and 
federal taxes, she will take home about $50 million. Slad, who 
works for MorNorth Mortgage, said she doesn't have any immediate 
plans, except to possibly buy a new car. 

</P>
<P>
	House Approves Y2K Lawsuit Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House today overwhelmingly passed  
legislation aimed at avoiding legal aftershocks from Year 2000 
computer problems. The Senate is to follow suit shortly, and the 
White House said the president, after lengthy negotiations over 
consumer protections, would sign the bill. The legislation, aimed 
at stemming a flood of lawsuits from possible computer breakdowns, 
cleared the House by a 404-24 vote. The Year 2000 problem -- also 
called Y2K and the millennium bug -- occurs because some computer 
programs, which were written to recognize only the last two digits 
of a year, may read the digits ``00'' as 1900 instead of 2000. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Criticizes Bush Over Funds  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush, banking a record  
$36 million for his presidential race, would be lining up with 
Republicans ``unanimously hostile'' to campaign finance reform if 
he rejects federal spending limits, President Clinton said today. 
``The American people will have to make up their minds about 
whether this is an important issue or not,'' the president said. 
Bush broke ahead of the entire 2000 pack when he announced this 
week that he had raised over the last four months a stunning $36 
million for Campaign 2000. 

</P>
<P>
	Blair Seeks Belfast Compromises  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Rival negotiators have achieved  
``historic, seismic shifts in the political landscape'' in talks 
this week, but must make further compromises to salvage Northern 
Ireland's peace accord, British Prime Minister Tony Blair said 
today. As negotiations resumed on forming a Protestant-Catholic 
government for the province, Blair called success or failure in the 
coming hours ``the thread by which Northern Ireland hangs.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Cable Car Crash Kills 20 in France  
</P>
<P>
	SAINT-ETIENNE-EN-DEVOLUY, France (AP) -- A cable car gondola  
crashed hundreds of feet to the ground today on the slopes of a ski 
resort in the French Alps, killing all 20 people aboard. Officials 
said no tourists were riding the private cable car that was 
carrying workers to the Pic de Bure space observatory. The gondola 
fell 262 feet onto a rock-studded grass slope above 
Saint-Etienne-en-Devoluy, 400 miles southeast of Paris. It was the 
worst cable car disaster in the country's history. 

</P>
<P>
	89-Year-Old Woman Walking Across US  
</P>
<P>
	WEATHERFORD, Texas (AP) -- The soft-spoken, 5-foot Doris Haddock,  
also known as ``Granny D,'' is nearly halfway through her 
3,055-mile walk across the country to call attention to 
campaign-finance reform. The 89-year-old former shoe factory worker 
and secretary set out from Southern California on New Year's Day 
and expects to finish in Washington in January, walking six days a 
week, 10 miles a day. This week, she made her way down U.S. Highway 
180 in the Texas summer heat. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Gains 59; Nasdaq Is Up 20  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average is back above  
the 11,000 mark. Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow was up 62.69 to 
11,033.49. The Nasdaq Composite Index is up 20.48 to 2,706.60. 

</P>
<P>
	Davenport Beats Novotna  
</P>
<P>
	WIMBLEDON, England (AP) -- Lindsay Davenport advances to the  
Wimbledon semifinals for the first time in her career after beating 
defending champion Jana Novotna today 6-3, 6-4. As rain disrupted 
play for the third day this week, the third-seeded American 
dominated the error-prone Czech to extend her career record against 
Novotna to 6-0. Davenport will face the winner of the first ever 
quarterfinal match between two qualifiers: 18-year-old American 
Alexandra Stevenson and 16-year-old Australian Jelena Dokic. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief By LINDA KIM  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
