<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> German Island Has Duty-free Shops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HELGOLAND, Germany (AP) -- On the European mainland, travelers  
have lost their chance to shop duty-free. But visitors to this 
North Sea resort island on Thursday were still stocking up on 
untaxed perfume, cigarettes and liquor. 
</P>
<P>
	Helgoland is one of a handful of EU islands -- along with Spain's  
Canary Islands -- where tax-free shopping will continue despite the 
duty-free ban that went into effect Thursday within the 15 
countries of the European Union. 
</P>
<P>
	The change made sense for the EU, where border controls have  
largely disappeared, officials have said. And EU taxpayers will get 
a boost from their governments' added revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	But Helgoland's duty-free shop owners said they thought there  
would be those who would go out of their way for a bargain, and 
they were getting ready to greet them. 
</P>
<P>
	Shop owner Niels Pfoertner said he expected a 20-30 percent  
surge in customers, and in preparation started stocking his 
inventory months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our stores are packed because we know what we have to  
expect,'' Pfoertner said, standing in front of a display of liquor 
and fine tobacco. 
</P>
<P>
	In the case of the Aland Islands, a self-governing Finnish  
region, island leaders won omission from the ban partly by arguing 
that the sale of tax-free goods was necessary to their economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Just a three-hour trip by speed boat from the northern city of  
Hamburg, Helgoland has long drawn visitors seeking cheap drinks and 
smokes, in addition to peaceful weekends in the island's brightly 
painted condos and hotels. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the chief of the island's tourism bureau, Martin Linne,  
was reserved in his optimism that business would increase just 
because of the tax-free status -- partly because of the $60 cost of 
the boat ride to the island. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will have many more visitors this year coming for one  
day,'' he said. ``But not so much that you could call Helgoland a 
boomtown.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ban on the industry worth about $7 billion a year does not  
effect international ferry routes and airports with flights to 
non-EU countries. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
