<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Senior Event Fights For Place  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, Md. (AP) -- As the newest event on the Senior PGA Tour,  
the State Farm Classic must fight for a premium date and attract 
the top players. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven of the top 10 money winners on the Senior Tour this season  
will battle for a healthy purse of $1.3 million. However, many of 
the most recognizable names will be absent when the second-year 
event tees off Friday at Hobbit's Glen. 
</P>
<P>
	Fan favorites such as Hale Irwin, Jack Nicklaus and Raymond  
Floyd have skipped this year's State Farm Classic because it falls 
on a holiday weekend and between two major tournaments. 
</P>
<P>
	Irwin, Senior Tour Player of the Year in 1997 and 1998, is  
resting an ailing shoulder for next week's U.S. Senior Open. 
Winning last weekend's Senior Players Championship with a 
remarkable score of 21-under, Irwin gave the State Farm Classic 
immediate legitimacy by playing the inaugural event. 
</P>
<P>
	Nicklaus also took this week off after having to withdraw from  
the Senior Players Championship. Nicklaus, who hopes to return next 
weekend, probably would not have played the State Farm Classic 
anyway. 
</P>
<P>
	Legends Arnold Palmer and Chi Chi Rodriguez drew some of the  
largest galleries last year. Neither included the State Farm 
Classic on their limited schedules this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other Senior Tour stars, Raymond Floyd and Gary Player, have  
told tournament organizers they will never play on July 4 weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	That leaves Lee Trevino and defending champion Bruce Summerhays  
as the most recognizable participants. Trevino graces publicity 
posters while Summerhays is featured on the program. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no question being sandwiched between two majors is  
tough on this event,'' Trevino said. ``There's some key guys who 
aren't here this week because they needed a break.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senior Tour schedule will remain the same in 2000 as the  
State Farm Classic completes its three-year guaranteed contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's tough being the new kid on the block, but I'm sure this  
tournament will get a better date in the future,'' Trevino said. 
</P>
<P>
	The inaugural State Farm Classic drew 93,000 fans, even though  
turnout on Saturday, July 4, was well below expectations. Executive 
director John Mathews thinks attendance will soar next year since 
the holiday falls on Tuesday, which is when optional practice 
rounds are held. 
</P>
<P>
	``We get a break with the calendar next year, and hopefully in  
future years the majors will be moved away from us,'' Mathews said. 
</P>
<P>
	Senior Tour officials are planning to spread the majors further  
apart in 2001. Mathews, who has already initiated negotiations to 
extend the State Farm Classic contract, is hoping the event can be 
played in June every few years. 
</P>
<P>
	``All indications are positive that this event will continue. We  
have the sponsor support and the fan interest,'' Mathews said. 
``The date isn't ideal, but we've made the most of it. If life 
gives you lemons, you make lemonade. I think we've made some darn 
good lemonade.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Famous players bring in the crowds, but ultimately good course  
conditions and strong competition keep a tournament on the tour. 
Summerhays pointed out that 22 of this season's top 30 money 
winners are competing here this weekend. Heading the field are 
Bruce Fleisher and Allen Doyle, tour newcomers who have both 
already topped $1 million in earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a topnotch field. Almost all the guys who are playing  
good right now are here,'' Summerhays said. ``John Jacobs, Dana 
Quigley and Tom Jenkins may not be recognizable names to the 
average fan, but they've all been playing great golf.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trevino said the seniors love Hobbit's Glen, a 7,078-yard course  
designed by Ed Ault and opened in 1967. That's because it's not 
tricked up with railroad ties, huge mounds and the other man-made 
obstructions common on new TPC courses. 
</P>
<P>
	``This course is absolutely perfect for our tour,'' Trevino  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an old, vintage course that enables you to play golf the  
way it's supposed to be played. You can bump and run or different 
things. So many of the new courses force you to play an aerial 
game,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
