<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senator Chastises Women on Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Ted Stevens, chairman of the Senate  
Appropriations Committee, said Thursday that women, wanting to 
spend money on ``touchy feely'' things, are less supportive of 
increases in defense spending than men. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's all these touchy feely things out there that they want  
to spend money on,'' Stevens, R-Alaska, told a breakfast of defense 
writers. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens, who is also chairman of the panel's defense  
subcommittee, said he gets ``more questions from women who say, 
`Why? What do you spend all that money for? We have enough. We 
don't need any more military.''' 
</P>
<P>
	``There are not as many women who support the national defense  
budget now as men,'' Stevens said. ``I really think there is a 
gender gap in the support for the large expenditures that are 
necessary to modernize the force.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If the women of the world wake up to the fact that we don't  
have a national missile defense system, that our current military 
systems are aging very rapidly and that if they don't watch out 
their sons and daughters are going to be going to war in equipment 
that their grandfathers built, then maybe we might see it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``But today there is not a unified support for a defense  
increase in the United States,'' Stevens said. 
</P>
<P>
	A Stevens spokeswoman, Jenifer Sicilano, said Stevens was just  
``saying that there was a gender gap there, that women are not 
necessarily as supportive of defense issues as are men.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
