<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'South Park' Tests Ratings Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- It was going well for awhile for Elizabeth  
Chacon and Gregory Contreras. 
</P>
<P>
	Without a parent or guardian, the 16-year-olds bought tickets,  
no questions asked, for an afternoon showing of the new, R-rated 
``South Park'' movie. Then reality hit. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we tried to get in, they said we couldn't. So they gave  
us our money back,'' said Chacon, standing outside the Galaxy 
Theater in Hollywood. ``We didn't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Life imitated art as the new movie opened Wednesday: Theaters  
had to turn away children trying to sneak into a vulgar movie about 
children who sneak into a vulgar movie. 
</P>
<P>
	``South Park: Bigger, Longer and Uncut'' may prove the biggest  
test yet to theater owners' recent agreement with President Clinton 
to strictly enforce the R rating, which bars anyone under 17 
without an adult. The recent agreement was in reaction to the 
Littleton, Colo., school massacre. 
</P>
<P>
	Another 16-year-old turned away from the Galaxy vowed to try and  
see the film somewhere else. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what the big deal is,'' grumbled Jose Tamayo.  
</P>
<P>
	The movie -- which has received glowing reviews -- is more about  
dirty words than dirty deeds. It thereby thumbs its nose at a movie 
rating system that prohibits kids from seeing foul-mouthed, cartoon 
8-year-olds but lets them view scenes of death and destruction. 
</P>
<P>
	Filled with raunchy dialogue about sex, jokes about bodily  
functions and profanity that would make a sailor blush, ``South 
Park'' -- based on the controversial TV series on cable's Comedy 
Central -- had to go through several edits before it could get down 
from an NC-17 to an R rating. (An NC-17 rating means no one younger 
than 17 allowed, not even with an adult.) 
</P>
<P>
	``The ratings board only cared about the dirty words. They're so  
confused and arbitrary,'' Trey Parker, who with partner Matt Stone 
created ``South Park,'' told The New York Times. ``They don't blink 
twice because of violence.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Parker and Stone clashed with the ratings board last year when  
their pornography industry farce ``Orgazmo'' was rated NC-17, even 
though it had no explicit sex scenes and only fleeting nudity. 
</P>
<P>
	The duo contends the only reason they received an R rating for  
``South Park'' was because it was backed by a major studio -- 
Paramount -- which also is a member of the industry group that 
handles the ratings, the Motion Picture Association of America. 
(``Orgazmo'' was an independent production.) 
</P>
<P>
	It's a claim Paramount dismisses.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's no way that the MPAA treats a studio different from  
anybody else,'' said Robert Friedman, vice chairman of the 
Paramount Motion Picture Group. ``You go through the exact same 
process, with the exact same people, sitting in judgment of what 
they think is right or wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jack Valenti, president of the MPAA, didn't return messages  
seeking comment. In the past, he has strongly defended the 
integrity of the ratings process, while acknowledging that 
decisions are subjective. 
</P>
<P>
	Even the ``South Park'' filmmakers agreed parents should  
probably be with their kids at the movie. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Fox, a spokesman for Comedy Central, which has aired  
``South Park'' since 1997, said the program -- shown at 10 p.m. 
Wednesdays -- is positioned for adults, but draws about 20 percent 
of it's audience from the under-18 crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	And so it was, at the Wynnsong 10 theater in Little Rock, Ark.,  
that 46-year-old Gary Bradberry accompanied his 12-year-old son to 
``South Park.'' The elder Bradberry explained that he and his son 
both watch the TV show and discuss troubling scenes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like it,'' the father said. ``It's a change from all other  
shows on TV.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
