<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Mostly Up; Gold Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The dollar was up against most other major  
currencies in European trading Thursday, as the beleaguered euro 
fell to a record low. Gold prices rose. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0239, down from $1.0316 Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	``The euro's looking technically poor,'' said Stephen  
Woolfenden, senior dealer at the London bank Standard Chartered. 
``The market had begun to gather a bit of confidence in the euro 
but in the last two sessions, this has gone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While a Thursday selloff took the euro to a new low against the  
dollar, analysts surveyed in Tokyo and London expect it to be 
higher by the end of the month. 
</P>
<P>
	``We buy into the European recovery story,'' said Michael  
Metcalfe, currency economist with NatWest GFM in London. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates compared with late Wednesday: 121.09 Japanese  
yen, up from 120.80; 1.5669 Swiss francs, up from 1.5496 and 1.4662 
Canadian dollars, down from 1.4752 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.5774, up from $1.5747.  
</P>
<P>
	At midday in New York, the dollar was quoted at 120.69 yen. The  
euro was trading at $1.0255 and the pound at $1.5769. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth: 1.9102 German marks, up from 1.8959; 
6.4065 French francs, up from 6.3586; 2.1523 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.1362; and 1,891.07 Italian lire, up from 1,876.96. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $262.40 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$260.80 on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid price was $262.45, up from $260.75.  
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong financial institutions were closed Thursday for a  
holiday marking the second anniversary of the territory's return 
from British to Chinese rule. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $5.31 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$5.22. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
