<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 22:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minister Convicted on 'Black Tax' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A black minister has been convicted of getting  
three people to file tax returns in which they claimed a ``black 
tax'' exemption that he said was available to descendants of 
slaves. 
</P>
<P>
	Willie Foster, 35, of Fort Worth could get up to 27 months in  
prison at sentencing Sept. 14. He was convicted on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Three people testified that Foster told them the exemption was a  
government reparation for descendants of slaves freed after the 
Civil War. No such reparations were ever authorized. One man 
actually received a $2,300 refund two years ago by making the 
claim. 
</P>
<P>
	``Willie Foster is not an American hero. You don't rope other  
hard-working people into this scam,'' prosecutor Terri Moore told 
the federal jury of three blacks and nine whites. ``He spread 
lies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doug Greene, Foster's lawyer, argued that the IRS was holding  
Foster responsible for its own mistakes. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury took less than an hour to convict Foster on three  
counts of filing false claims. 
</P>
<P>
	Foster himself got $30,085.89 back from the IRS after filing for  
the ``black tax'' exemption. The IRS caught the mistake, but Foster 
never gave the money back. No charges were ever brought against 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	Talk of slave reparations has circulated since the end of the  
Civil War, when Congress voted to give freed slaves 40 acres and a 
mule. President Andrew Johnson vetoed the plan. 
</P>
<P>
	The debate landed in the lap of the IRS after L.G. Sherrod, a  
journalist and economics consultant, wrote an essay in Essence 
magazine in 1993 in which she urged readers to use their tax forms 
to claim the modern-day equivalent of 40 acres and a mule. 
</P>
<P>
	``Simply enter $43,209 in `black taxes' and compute  
accordingly,'' she wrote. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
