<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 08:15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Sign Y2K Lawsuit Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Legislation aimed at avoiding legal  
aftershocks from Year 2000 computer problems headed for a final 
vote in Congress today. The White House said the president, after 
lengthy negotiations over consumer protections, would sign the 
bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill aimed at stemming a flood of lawsuits from possible  
computer breakdowns was assured of a big victory in the House 
today, followed by another strong show of approval in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton's signature, which appeared solid after  
lawmakers said Tuesday they had reached a compromise agreement with 
the administration, appeared a little shakier Wednesday after the 
White House indicated it still had some problems with the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	But White House spokesman Jake Siewert said today the president  
will approve it. ``We think this bill is critical to meet a 
national priority and the president is prepared to sign it into law 
because it is narrowly tailored to deal with litigation dealing 
with the Y2K problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Year 2000 problem -- also called Y2K and the millennium bug --  
occurs because some computer programs, especially older ones, might 
fail when the date changes to 2000. Because the programs were 
written to recognize only the last two digits of a year, such 
programs could read the digits ``00'' as 1900 instead of 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Al Gore, who has strong ties with the high-tech  
industry, which badly wants the legislation and played an active 
role in crafting the final product, told The Associated Press 
Wednesday he understood there were some last-minute problems in 
putting the deal in writing. But he said there was a ``90 percent 
chance'' they would be worked out and the bill signed. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said he was generally satisfied with the legislation.  
``It's a compromise outcome that overall serves the interests of 
the nation,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans stressed they had an agreement and were done  
negotiating. Sponsors of the original House bill, said Rep. Bob 
Goodlatte, R-Va., ``had to make tremendous concessions'' to win 
White House support and in the end, ``the Congress writes the 
legislation and not the president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The White House rejected the original House-passed bill as being  
too pro-business and to the disadvantage of consumers taking legal 
action to recover losses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate bill, written by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., with the  
help of Democratic Sens. Ron Wyden of Oregon and Christopher Dodd 
of Connecticut, was modified to address consumer concerns, but the 
White House said that it too was one-sided and would receive a 
veto. 
</P>
<P>
	Further changes agreed to over five days of negotiations ending  
Tuesday appeared to finally win White House approval. 
</P>
<P>
	Business groups and the high-tech industry, warning of billions  
of dollars in lawsuits from disruptions caused by computers that 
can't differentiate the year 2000 from 1900, lobbied hard for the 
legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore conceded he was caught between the interests of two strong  
Democratic constituents, the high-tech industry that wanted the 
bill and trial lawyers who opposed it. 
</P>
<P>
	But, he said the pressure was ``no more than is frequently the  
case when you have differing legitimate points of view that have to 
be reconciled.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would give companies 90 days to fix Y2K-related  
problems before lawsuits can be filed and by encouraging mediation. 
</P>
<P>
	It also would set punitive damage caps for small businesses,  
make it harder to file class action lawsuits and provide that, in 
most cases, a defendant can be held liable only for the proportion 
of damage actually caused by the individual or company. 
</P>
<P>
	In the final negotiations, some changes were made in the class  
action and proportionate liability sections to better protect 
consumer interests, and that won over such influential Democrats as 
Rep. John Conyers of Michigan, ranking Democrat on the Judiciary 
Committee, who opposed the original bills. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have now fully crafted a bill that we can all live with and  
enjoy,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	House Democratic leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri said he still  
thought the bill would undermine the civil justice system and would 
be used as a ``fund-raising tool'' for Republicans seeking 
high-tech donations. 
</P>
<P>
	But his Senate counterpart, Tom Daschle of South Dakota, said  
the bill was ``the best we can get under these circumstances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 775.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
