<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Pick Convention Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Republicans said today they will hold  
their 2000 national convention in the First Union Center, home to 
the city's basketball and hockey teams. 
</P>
<P>
	``That woman or man who will lead us into the next millennium  
will be nominated in this building,'' the party's national 
committee chairman, Jim Nicholson, told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision caps a selection process that began in November  
when Philadelphia was selected over Indianapolis, New Orleans, New 
York and San Antonio to be the site of the GOP convention -- the 
city's first since 1948, when it had both the Democratic and the 
Republican gatherings. 
</P>
<P>
	While the city was selected, the site wasn't, until today.  
</P>
<P>
	Party officials had been said to be leaning toward the downtown  
Pennsylvania Convention Center, which is close to fancy hotels and 
restaurants and to historical attractions such as Independence Hall 
and the Liberty Bell. 
</P>
<P>
	But officials were swayed by the First Union Center's  
technological amenities, easy accessibility and ample parking. The 
3-year-old building on the city's south side, about 3 1/2 miles from 
downtown, is close to the airport and has seating for 21,000 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	The convention will run from July 29 to Aug. 4, 2000, and will  
draw about 40,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision cheered several groups already booked into the  
convention center in the weeks leading up to the convention. They 
likely would have been displaced. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republicans will still use the convention center for  
meetings, receptions and the PoliticalFest, an extravaganza for 
political junkies, but those events do not require nearly as much 
lead time as the convention itself. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
