<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 13:20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Administration Changes Tax Crackdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration announced changes  
today in its broad proposal aimed at cracking down on corporate tax 
shelters. 
</P>
<P>
	``The proliferation of corporate tax shelters presents an  
unacceptable and growing level of tax avoidance behavior,'' the 
Treasury Department said in a report, underscoring its intent to 
curb such tax-avoidance schemes that are estimated to cost the 
federal government billions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	The department tweaked its original proposal, offered in  
February, after receiving input from concerned industry groups 
representing tax attorneys, accountants and corporate tax 
executives, among others. 
</P>
<P>
	The department, for instance, eliminated a provision in its  
original proposal that would have prevented a company from 
deducting from its taxable income the fees it paid a financial 
adviser if a transaction was deemed to be a tax shelter. 
</P>
<P>
	Generally speaking, a tax shelter is a financial arrangement  
aimed mainly at escaping taxes with no other economic or business 
purpose. 
</P>
<P>
	The department also decided to drop a provision contained in its  
original proposal that would have imposed a 25 percent excise tax 
on any transaction with a clause in which a tax-shelter promoter 
promises to refund a client's fees if the government kills the 
deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Overall, it (the revised proposal) represents a step in the  
right direction. The earlier proposal was an excellent example of 
overreaction or overkill,'' said Timothy McCormally, general 
counsel and director of tax affairs for the Tax Executives 
Institute, whose members work in corporate tax departments. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the department added a $100,000 penalty for failing to  
disclose to the federal government information about certain 
transactions, regardless of whether it is a tax shelter. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the changes, the department retained the core elements  
of its original proposal, said senior Treasury officials, who spoke 
on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The core elements generally call for:  
</P>
<P>
	--Increasing disclosure of corporate tax shelter activities.  
</P>
<P>
	--Increasing and modifying the penalties for the substantial  
understatement of income tax. 
</P>
<P>
	--Disallowing the use of tax benefits generated by a corporate  
shelter. 
</P>
<P>
	--Having all parties involved, such as promoters and advisers, be  
subject to liability if they facilitated a tax-avoidance 
transaction. 
</P>
<P>
	To be implemented, Congress must approve legislation containing  
Treasury's plan and President Clinton must sign it into law, the 
officials said. It's unclear how the proposal would fare on Capitol 
Hill. Republicans, who control Congress, agree there is a problem 
with the proliferation of tax shelters but so far haven't embraced 
the administration's proposal or offered their own. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990701.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 15:50:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lewis Widow To Push for Retrial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	One week after a jury could not decide whether a respected  
cardiologist was negligent in her husband's death, the widow of 
Boston Celtics captain Reggie Lewis said the inconclusive end to 
the lengthy trial was the result of a lack of courage by the panel. 
She also vowed to push for a retrial. 
</P>
<P>
	Speaking for the first time since a judge declared a mistrial in  
the malpractice trial, Donna Harris-Lewis recounted her feelings 
when the verdict was announced. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was numb. I was wordless,'' she said in a telephone  
interview Thursday. ``I couldn't believe the jurors did not see the 
medical evidence and did not have the courage to assign 
responsibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several of the 15 jurors have said they were split 9-6 in favor  
of Dr. Gilbert Mudge when they told the judge they were hopelessly 
deadlocked. Thirteen would have had to agree on a verdict. The jury 
did exonerate two of Mudge's consultants, Drs. Peter Friedman and 
Mark Creager. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis, 34, said she will appeal those verdicts and seek a  
retrial of Mudge, who publicly diagnosed Lewis with a benign 
fainting disorder two months before the NBA All-Star collapsed and 
died while practicing jump shots in July 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	She sought the money Lewis could have made had he lived past 27,  
as much as $75 million, according to one plaintiff's witness. But 
Harris-Lewis scoffed at the suggestion she was motivated by greed 
or wanted to silence questions about cocaine because drug use would 
have nullified Lewis' insurance policy and contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``If a defibrillator had been implanted, or (proper drugs) given  
to Reggie, and he died, I would say Dr. Mudge did his best,'' 
Harris-Lewis said. ``I never said Dr. Mudge was a bad doctor ... I 
don't hate him. But I know (he) made a mistake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The jury's exculpatory verdicts -- and inability to reach  
agreement on Mudge -- came after a nearly eight-week-long trial in 
which Harris-Lewis claimed the doctors misdiagnosed and mistreated 
her husband. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lewises had turned to Mudge for a second opinion after  
doctors at New England Baptist Hospital told the player he had a 
life-threatening, potentially career-ending cardiac condition after 
his collapse during a playoff game in April 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge, then head of clinical cardiology at Brigham and Women's  
Hospital, delivered the good news about Lewis' condition at a news 
conference: The athlete had a normal heart and could likely return 
to professional basketball. 
</P>
<P>
	Two months later, Lewis died of an abnormal heart rhythm while  
practicing jump shots at Brandeis University. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, one year after a Wall Street Journal article raised the  
issue of possible drug use by her husband, Harris-Lewis sued Mudge 
and his consultants. A third consultant settled before trial for an 
undisclosed amount. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge, now 54 and the head of the heart transplant unit at  
Brigham and Women's, has testified that two weeks before his death 
Lewis admitted he had used cocaine. The doctor said the belated 
confession made an accurate diagnosis impossible. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis maintains her husband never used drugs.  
</P>
<P>
	Mudge's attorney, William Dailey Jr., could not immediately be  
reached for comment Thursday, but he has said he hopes Harris-Lewis 
will reconsider a retrial. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
