<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Special Olympian Dies in His Sleep </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CARY, N.C. (AP) -- A 14-year-old Special Olympian from Egypt died  
in his sleep early Thursday, probably from an epileptic seizure, 
officials of the Special Olympics World Summer Games said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mohamed Abdul Baset Barin, a volleyball player, was pronounced  
dead in his room at North Carolina's Morrison Hall at Chapel Hill, 
N.C., after his coach called paramedics, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is tragic, it is saddening, but it was also, sadly,  
unavoidable,'' Tim Shriver, president and CEO of Special Olympics 
Inc., said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Tim Taft, chairman of the Special Olympics' medical advisory  
committee, said Barin was an epileptic. An autopsy performed 
Thursday by the state medical examiner's office suggested his death 
was related to epilepsy. But since Barin died in his sleep, 
examiners couldn't be absolutely sure, Taft said. Taft said Barin 
was taking medication for his disorder. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know he had an underlying seizure disorder,'' Taft said.  
``That is the most likely explanation for what happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Games organizers planned a moment of silence at each event venue  
Thursday night to observe Barin's death. 
</P>
<P>
	Special Olympians are all developmentally disabled, and many are  
afflicted with medical problems as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Joe Freddoso, CEO of the Games Organizing Committee, said Barin  
and his teammates watched volleyball competition Wednesday night at 
Carmichael Auditorium on the North Carolina campus, then returned 
to Morrison Hall, watched television and went to bed. 
</P>
<P>
	When Barin couldn't be awakened about 7 a.m. Thursday, his coach  
called paramedics, who pronounced him dead a short time later. 
</P>
<P>
	``On behalf of my parents and the entire Special Olympics  
movement, we extend our deepest sympathies to the family of Mohamed 
Abdul Baset Barin,'' Shriver said. ``He showed courage in 
everything he did and was a shining example, a hero of our 
movement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shriver said the rest of the 32-member Egyptian delegation will  
continue to participate in the Special Olympics. Barin's volleyball 
team played a match on Thursday, losing to a team from Delaware. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have asked to be allowed to continue but continue, if at  
all possible, without any outside interference,'' Shriver said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Special Olympics World Summer Games opened in the  
Raleigh-Durham area last Saturday and will end Sunday. About 7,000 
athletes from the United States and 150 other countries are 
participating. About 2,000 coaches, 15,000 friends and relatives 
and 45,000 volunteers also are involved in the Games. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
