<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cities Report Positive Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Many American cities and towns report a strong  
fiscal picture and expect continuing good economies as they 
increase spending on public safety and infrastructure repairs, the 
National League of Cities said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In responses to a questionnaire distributed to 317  
municipalities, 75 percent said they were better able to meet their 
financial needs than they were a year ago. And 64 percent said they 
expected to be in better financial shape next year than they are 
now. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most cities are upbeat about where they are and where they  
seem to be going,'' said Clarence E. Anthony, the mayor of South 
Bay, Fla., and National League of Cities president. 
</P>
<P>
	Most cities picked two factors -- the strength of their tax base  
and the health of the local economy -- as the most important factors 
affecting their ability to meet their overall needs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
