<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mortgage Rates Move Higher / National Mortgage Survey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The average interest rate on 30-year  
fixed-rate mortgages rose to 7.71 percent this week, the highest 
level in two years. 
</P>
<P>
	The average was up from 7.63 percent last week, according to a  
weekly survey released Thursday by Freddie Mac, the mortgage 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	Mortgages rates have been on an upward climb for the past two  
months and have fluctuated from their low for this year of 6.74 
percent set at the end of January to their current high of 7.71 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen-year mortgages, a popular option for refinancing,  
averaged 7.34 percent this week, up from the average of 7.28 
percent last week. 
</P>
<P>
	On one-year adjustable-rate mortgages, lenders were asking an  
average initial rate of 6.05 percent, up from 5.93 percent the 
previous week. 
</P>
<P>
	The rates do not include add-on fees known as points, which  
averaged at or just over 1 percent of the loan amount for all three 
types of mortgages. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
