<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Co-Pilot Sentenced in Fatal Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT STEWART, Ga. (AP) -- An Army pilot has been convicted of  
misappropriating a helicopter that was involved in a Bahamas crash 
that killed his wife and the wife of another pilot. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Warrant Officer Daniel Riddell was reprimanded Wednesday  
by a military judge and sentenced to $4,500 in fines and pay 
forfeiture. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am pleased with the judge's decision,'' said Riddell,  
accused along with another pilot of taking their wives on a joyride 
that turned tragic aboard the UH-60 Blackhawk last summer. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge, Col. Kenneth Pangburn, acquitted Riddell of  
conspiracy and dropped dereliction of duty charges. Riddell could 
have received two years in prison and been dismissed from the Army. 
</P>
<P>
	Riddell was charged along with Chief Warrant Officer David Guido  
-- the pilot -- and Sgt. William Westgate, who were in the Bahamas 
for a drug-interdiction mission. The July 6, 1998, crash on Grand 
Exuma Island killed Rebecca Riddell and Pam Guido. 
</P>
<P>
	Riddell testified that he took his wife on the flight as a  
reward for what she had put up with during his career. 
</P>
<P>
	Guido was convicted last month of conspiracy, wrongful  
appropriation of an aircraft and violation of a lawful general 
regulation. He was sentenced to a reprimand plus fines and 
forfeited pay totaling $10,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Westgate, an avionics technician, is scheduled to be court  
martialed July 8. He is charged with conspiracy and willful 
dereliction of duty. 
</P>
<P>
	Riddell testified that he believed mechanical problems -- not  
pilot error -- caused the crash. An Army board concluded the cause 
was pilot error. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Doug Andrews said Riddell punishes himself  
every day for the loss of his wife. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Riddell is ready to accept your sentence,'' Andrews said.  
``Your sentence, regardless of what it is, can't be harsher than 
what he's already been through.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
