<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alexander Loses Colleague's Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) -- Former Gov. Lamar Alexander, publicly  
upbeat even as his campaign for the Republican presidential 
nomination lags, has lost some support in his home state. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Zach Wamp, R-Tenn., announced Thursday that he no longer is  
backing Alexander and is throwing his support to Texas Gov. George 
W. Bush instead. The six other Republicans in the Tennessee 
congressional delegation continue to support Alexander. 
</P>
<P>
	``I strongly believe that as president, George W. Bush can lead  
the way in reversing the spiritual and moral decline that worries 
so many American families,'' Wamp said in a written statement. 
</P>
<P>
	``The delay in the announcement of my support for Governor Bush  
was simply caused by my genuine desire to not hurt my friend and 
fellow Tennessean Lamar Alexander.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Responding, Alexander's political director Brian Kennedy said,  
``We're proud to have the support of the rest of the Tennessee 
delegation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee Republican Party Chairman Chip Saltsman said he was  
``a little surprised'' by Wamp's move but that it would not sway 
others. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people in Tennessee are supporting Lamar for  
president,'' Saltsman said. ``The party has been neutral and we 
will continue to be neutral.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before Alexander officially announced his campaign March 9, each  
member of the Tennessee Republican delegation gave Alexander 
permission to use his name as an honorary campaign vice chairman, 
Alexander spokesman Bo Harmon said. 
</P>
<P>
	The next week, Bush's campaign claimed Wamp's endorsement,  
prompting a statement from the third-term Tennessee congressman 
that he supported Alexander but had attended an event for Bush, 
``whom I admire very much.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
