<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Rejects Easing Cuba Travel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration is threatening to  
veto a $12.7 billion foreign aid package that slashes many 
international programs, including the Peace Corps, while providing 
unrequested funds for a Kosovo security force. 
</P>
<P>
	Before passing the overall spending bill late Wednesday, the  
Senate rejected, 55-43, a proposal that would have eased 
restrictions on American citizens who want to travel to Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Sponsors said nearly 40 years of sanctions have failed to  
produce much impact on the policies of Cuba's Fidel Castro. But 
opponents argued that it would undermine long-standing U.S. policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not the time for lifting any of the sanctions on  
Cuba,'' said Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla. ``This is the time for us to 
hold the line on our policy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill for the first time slightly reduces overall aid for  
Israel and Egypt, by far the largest U.S. aid recipients. 
Assistance to Israel was reduced by $60 million and aid to Egypt by 
$40 million. Israel is to receive $1.08 billion in economic aid and 
$1.86 billion in military aid, and Egypt is to receive $775 million 
and $1.3 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure would provide $535 million to Kosovo and other  
Balkan and Eastern European states next year, mostly for 
reconstruction. Peacekeeping funds would be included in a separate 
bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House is threatening a veto of the overall bill,  
mainly on grounds that it cuts too much from what it views as 
critical programs, including the Peace Corps. The legislation makes 
a $50 million, or 19 percent, reduction to President Clinton's 
request for the organization. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would provide $1.9 billion less, overall, than Clinton  
wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	That would result in ``severe underfunding of a number of  
crucial programs,'' said a statement from White House Budget 
Director Jacob Lew. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall bill was approved 97-2.  
</P>
<P>
	One section opposed by the administration would add $20 million  
for a security force in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House statement on Wednesday said this provision  
``could be interpreted as aimed at training and equipping the 
Kosovo Liberation Army'' and that this was ``diametrically at 
odds'' with the recent agreement by the KLA to disarm under NATO 
supervision. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., chairman of the Senate  
Appropriations foreign operations subcommittee, told the Senate, 
``Members of the KLA may very well be included in a security force, 
but that is not a decision for us to make.'' He said the measure 
does not provide express support for arming or supporting the KLA. 
</P>
<P>
	The House has yet to act on similar legislation.  
</P>
<P>
	The Senate-passed bill also denies any foreign economic aid to  
Russia unless Moscow agrees to serve completely under NATO command 
in the Kosovo peacekeeping operations. 
</P>
<P>
	It also cuts $15 million from the administration's $55 million  
request under a 1996 program designed to provide North Korea with 
oil for conventional power plants to dissuade it from advancing its 
nuclear program. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also ignores the Clinton administration's request for  
$500 million to support the Wye River peace agreement between 
Israel and the Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
	Sponsors of easing the restrictions on flights to Cuba contended  
it made no sense to penalize Americans by not letting them visit 
Cuba and that the presence of more Americans on the island might 
have a beneficial effect. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's the purpose of a further isolation (of Cuba) if in 40  
years it hasn't produced a change?'' asked Sen. Christopher Dodd, 
D-Conn., the prime sponsor of the amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	His proposal would have given all U.S. citizens the same access  
to Cuba that journalists, humanitarian organizations and government 
officials have. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, there are no regular flights from U.S. airports to  
Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Direct charter flights to Cuba were legal until 1996 when Cuba  
shot down two Miami-based civilian planes flown by members of a 
Cuban exile group. Four men died in the incident off the Cuban 
coast. Clinton retaliated by banning such flights, but reinstated 
them in March 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the government imposes sharp restrictions on who can  
travel, mostly limiting travel rights to those who have families in 
Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., opposed the move to relax these  
restrictions. Even under the current setup, some 100,000 Americans 
a year have been visiting Cuba, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our argument with Fidel Castro is not over,'' Torricelli said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
