<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 02:40:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fla. Driver's License Laws Tougher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Mercedes Santana made it to Florida's driver's  
licensing office just in time. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dominican Republic native who had been using a driver's  
license from her home country got a state license hours before 
tighter requirements took effect. As of today, it is harder for 
teen-agers and undocumented aliens to get a Florida license. 
</P>
<P>
	Santana arrived at the licensing office before it opened early  
Wednesday to beat the long lines. Eight hours later, she had her 
license. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I (had not) gotten it today,'' Ms. Santana said, ``I would  
have driven without a license.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning today, applicants who don't have a valid U.S. or  
Canadian driver's license must show one of five official documents: 
a U.S. birth certificate, a valid U.S. passport, an Immigration and 
Naturalization Service green card, an employment authorization card 
or a Justice Department proof of non-immigrant classification. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, they must show a secondary piece of identification  
from a longer list of acceptable documents, including baptism 
certificates, marriage certificates, Social Security cards, family 
Bible records or birth announcements. 
</P>
<P>
	The new law brings Florida into compliance with other states.  
Since a license is usually enough identification for a credit card 
or bank account, it should make it harder to open false accounts, 
said Janet Dennis, spokeswoman for the Department of Highway Safety 
and Motor Vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the old law, applicants could present almost any form of  
identification bearing their name. 
</P>
<P>
	``Think about a family Bible record and a baptism certificate --  
those are easy to come by and they are also easy to (fake),'' said 
Ms. Dennis. ``This is really going to help us prevent fraud in 
Florida.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
