<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cisneros Tapes May Be Admissible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal judge who will preside over former  
Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros' trial showed little patience 
Thursday for the defense argument that none of the 88 tapes 
secretly recorded by Cisneros' ex-mistress should be allowed into 
evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	Just because all the tapes are copies, in some cases edited to  
delete certain passages, doesn't mean prosecutors shouldn't have 
the right to play snippets of conversations between Cisneros and 
one-time paramour Linda Jones, U.S. District Judge Stanley Sporkin 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't accept your position here that because some tampering  
has gone on, there cannot be the introduction of any tapes,'' 
Sporkin told Cisneros lawyer Barry Simon, offering the first hint 
of his thinking on the recordings' admissibility. 
</P>
<P>
	The tapes are crucial to Independent Counsel David Barrett's  
case that Cisneros, while being considered for a post in the 
Clinton Cabinet, conspired with Ms. Jones to understate how much 
money he gave her after their extramarital affair ended. 
</P>
<P>
	While Cisneros acknowledged during his Cabinet background check  
that he gave her financial support after publicity about their 
affair destroyed her marriage and career as a political 
fund-raiser, prosecutors contend he falsely told the FBI he never 
paid her more than $10,000 annually. 
</P>
<P>
	The 18-count indictment against Cisneros alleges he paid her  
more than $264,000 between 1990 and 1993. He has pleaded innocent. 
His trial is scheduled for September. 
</P>
<P>
	Sporkin, who has not heard any tapes but has read some written  
transcripts, said prosecutors should have the right to offer up 
recordings in which Cisneros discusses financial arrangements. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are some statements here that would indicate  
acknowledgment by the defendant that there have been payments,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge must rule on the tapes' admissibility at the  
conclusion of a pretrial hearing expected to continue through next 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	If the judge throws out the tapes, the prosecution would have to  
rely heavily on bank documents and the testimony of Ms. Jones, who 
acknowledged again and again from the witness stand last week that 
she lied repeatedly to federal agents investigating Cisneros. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros' lawyers contend all of the tapes are inadmissible  
because they are copies of since-destroyed originals and because 
Ms. Jones had an unlawful intent in making them. 
</P>
<P>
	Using the government's own tape expert, Simon sought to show  
that all 88 had potentially been edited. Prosecutors say Ms. Jones 
altered only five to remove sections where she threatened Cisneros. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're permitting phony, tampered evidence to come in,'' Simon  
said heatedly. 
</P>
<P>
	Snapped Sporkin: ``I'm not buying today, I'm not buying that  
argument.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones herself ran afoul of Barrett's investigation, in part  
because she misrepresented the tapes to the FBI and Internal 
Revenue Service as unaltered originals. She is serving 3 1/2 years in 
prison. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
