<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cable TV lures Viewers in Summer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Every television viewer knows that, come  
September, broadcasters deliver an orgy of new series and season 
premieres. But that's not the only time for networks to trot out 
big new projects. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable has its own ``shadow season,'' and we're smack in the  
middle of it. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable executives put forth their best material in the summer to  
steal viewers when the big networks are showing reruns. The 
strategy gets more popular every year, and it's paying off with 
some gaudy ratings. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the time for us to sort of move in for the kill,'' said  
Eileen Katz, executive vice president of programming at Comedy 
Central. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time this year, Comedy Central set aside one week  
to premiere several shows. The timing -- in mid-June, less than a 
month after the broadcast season ended -- was no coincidence. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Comedy Central's new programs, ``The Man Show,'' scored  
higher ratings than any other premiere in the network's nine-year 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	MTV is launching 10 series this summer, and existing shows like  
``Real World'' and ``Celebrity Death Match'' have started their 
seasons. The results? In June, MTV recorded some of its highest 
viewership levels ever. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though MTV is one of the most profitable networks in the  
business, executives see no sense in trying to compete with big 
network marketing budgets in September. 
</P>
<P>
	``This network was started as an alternative to what we called  
`real TV,''' said Judy McGrath, MTV president. ``We were always 
looking for an opportunity when broadcasters didn't see them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	TNT pulled in viewers with ``Pirates of Silicon Valley,'' its  
movie about the computer industry's pioneers, and will try again 
next week with ``The Hunley,'' a Civil War drama. ``The Count of 
Monte Cristo'' last week gave Bravo its best ratings ever for an 
original production. 
</P>
<P>
	The History Channel, frequent home to war documentaries, offers  
``The History of Sex'' next month. Discovery scares swimmers with 
its annual shark week, and the usually staid Bravo profiles '70s 
rock icons ABBA and David Cassidy. 
</P>
<P>
	HBO starts several series during the summer, such as ``Sex in  
the City'' and ``Oz.'' The Travel Channel, USA, The Food Network, 
TBS, The Learning Channel and Lifetime also bring forth new 
original material. 
</P>
<P>
	While cable watches its numbers soar, the audience for broadcast  
networks has plummeted. The average prime-time audience for CBS, 
NBC, ABC and Fox was 33 million last week, down from 47 million in 
mid-May, Nielsen Media Research said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cabletelevision Advertising Bureau predicts that this  
summer, for the first time, basic cable networks will overtake the 
top four broadcasters in viewers. Just five years ago, the four 
networks held a nearly 3-to-1 advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	Broadcasters are painfully aware that they bleed viewers in the  
summer, many of whom never return. But the economics of the 
business prevent them from presenting more than a handful of new 
shows. Programming is so expensive that networks generally lose 
money on shows unless they have a chance to rerun them. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, broadcasters seem to be rushing the seasons. They  
began advertising their new fall programs before summer even began. 
</P>
<P>
	Some in the industry predict the days of a uniform fall season  
opening are numbered, and all networks will sprinkle new shows 
throughout the year. 
</P>
<P>
	``During such a competitive time when there are so many  
choices,'' said MTV's McGrath, TV executives ``can't really afford 
to go fishing for that many months.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990701.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 14:40:23 </DATE_TIME>
