<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UN Chastises World Chiefs on Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United Nations sharply criticized NATO  
governments today for having spent billions to bomb Yugoslavia in 
the name of returning ethnic Albanians to Kosovo but refusing now 
to pay for their resettlement. The U.N. High Commissioner for 
Refugees has received only $140 million of the $400 million it says 
it needs to help repatriating refugees rebuild their homes and 
lives in Kosovo, said Soren Jessen-Petersen, the deputy high 
commissioner. ``I find it unacceptable that the international 
community is not in the position to give us the necessary funds,'' 
he told a news conference. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO, Russians Working Out Roles  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Russian military officials left  
Brussels today after ``productive'' but incomplete talks with NATO 
on the limits of their peacekeeping role in Kosovo, NATO officials 
said. The Russians, led by Adm. Valentin Kuznetsov, sought to 
extend their political powers within the wartorn province and 
establish a voice in the chain of command. They also want to expand 
their peacekeeping presence into two more sectors, NATO officials 
said. NATO officials, however, would prefer to keep the Russians in 
the decision-making background. 

</P>
<P>
	Y2K Lawsuit Bill Passed by Congress  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Exactly six months before the year 2000,  
Congress emphatically endorsed compromise legislation today to 
shield businesses from a potential flood of Y2K computer-related 
lawsuits. The White House says President Clinton will sign it. A 
House vote of 404-24 was followed several hours later by an 81-18 
vote in the Senate. The Senate's main sponsor, Sen. John McCain, 
R-Ariz., called passage ``a victory for the nation and for the 
continued prosperity of our economy as we enter the new 
millennium.'' One of the top legislative priorities of the business 
community this year, the bill would give them 90 days to fix Y2K 
problems before lawsuits could be filed. 

</P>
<P>
	Summers Confirmed for Treasury Post  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate confirmed Lawrence Summers today to  
become Treasury secretary, elevating him from his No. 2 slot in the 
department to succeed the outgoing Robert Rubin. Senators approved 
Summers' nomination 97-2. Rubin, who announced his resignation in 
May, steps down after a period of historic economic growth, debt 
reduction, job growth and low inflation. 

</P>
<P>
	Cable Car Crash Kills 20 in France  
</P>
<P>
	SAINT-ETIENNE-EN-DEVOLUY, France (AP) -- In the worst cable car  
disaster in French history, a gondola plunged to the ground today, 
killing all 20 people aboard a private lift that was carrying 
workers to a space observatory high in the Alps. The cable car was 
about one-quarter the way up the mountain when it suddenly fell 262 
feet onto a rock-studded slope above Saint-Etienne-en-Devoluy, a 
ski resort south of Grenoble. 

</P>
<P>
	Korea Talks Stall Again  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Talks between rivals North Korea and South Korea  
stalled again today, with the South pushing for discussions on 
reuniting separated families and the North again demanding an 
apology for a naval clash. The session lasted only 75 minutes. 
South Korean Vice Unification Minister Yang Young-shik afterward 
characterized the talks as ``parallel lines of different 
positions.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Blair Seeks Belfast Compromises  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Warning that the world would be  
baffled if peace slipped away, British Prime Minister Tony Blair 
presided over a last-gasp effort Thursday to form the 
Protestant-Catholic government at the heart of the Northern Ireland 
peace accord. Although talks continued past Blair's midnight 
Wednesday deadline for an agreement, the prime minister insisted 
the two parties central to the dispute blocking the government's 
formation already had delivered ``historic, seismic shifts'' in 
policy. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Up 95.62 at 11,066.42  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average extended its  
stunning gains today, flirting with a record high as investors 
reveled in the new interest rate environment. The Dow was ended up 
95.62 at 11,066.42. The blue-chip index held steadily above 11,000 
for the first time in weeks, and inched within 28 points of its May 
13 record close of 11,107.19. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 
1,697-1,385. The Nasdaq was at 2,706.21, up 20.09. 

</P>
<P>
	Cardinals Defeat Astros 10-4  
</P>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- Kent Bottenfield became the NL's first 12-game  
winner as the St. Louis Cardinals overcame a three-run deficit to 
beat Houston 10-4 today, the Astros' seventh loss in 10 games. J.D. 
Drew hit a two-run, inside-the-park homer for the Cardinals, who 
avoided a three-game sweep, and Bottenfield helped himself with a 
two-run double. Bottenfield (12-3) allowed four runs, seven hits 
and four walks in five-plus innings, and four relievers followed. 
Only Boston's Pedro Martinez (14-2) has more victories. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief By ANDREW DAMPF  
  	   	
</P>
