<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cubans' Arrival Generates Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Angry protests transformed into a celebration as  
six Cuban refugees were released from a detention center a day 
after they attempted to swim past circling Coast Guard boats. 
</P>
<P>
	The men clasped hands in victory Wednesday night as they emerged  
from the center. 
</P>
<P>
	``This shows that in this country there is democracy and that  
justice still prevails,'' said Raul Sosa, 36, a tow truck company 
owner who had waited hours in the rain outside the center. 
</P>
<P>
	The swim on Tuesday set off violent demonstrations and prompted  
the Coast Guard to investigate its own behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	Television reports showed the Coast Guard blasting the refugees  
with a hose as they stood in their 14-foot rowboat about 150 yards 
from shore. The agency then swarmed after the group jumped 
overboard and swam towards shore. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the swimmers was doused with pepper spray. Two reached  
the beach and four were plucked from the water and detained aboard 
a Coast Guard cutter. 
</P>
<P>
	Within hours, up to 3,000 people gathered at the Coast Guard's  
Miami Beach station, blocking the main access road between trendy 
South Beach and downtown Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Demonstrators held signs saying ``U.S. Coast Guard: Pigs like  
Castro'' and waved Cuban flags as they sang the Cuban national 
anthem. In Hialeah, the police chief needed stitches after he was 
hit in the head with a rock and the mayor was shown on camera 
grabbing a man and punching him several times. 
</P>
<P>
	Under existing policy, foreigners who reach U.S. shores are  
allowed to seek asylum, while those intercepted at sea are 
generally kept out of the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The men say they set out from Cuba unaided last Thursday, using  
paddles and a sail to propel their small wooden skiff. The U.S. 
Border Patrol is investigating and the Coast Guard has promised an 
internal probe of its actions. 
</P>
<P>
	The men will be allowed to stay with family members while  
awaiting a ruling on their asylum application. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard has picked up 826 Cubans so far this year,  
compared with 1,047 in 1998. That was the first year to break 1,000 
since the exodus of more than 37,000 Cubans in 1994. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
