<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- A maverick opposition governor could upset  
Mexico's long-ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party in the 2000 
presidential election, a new poll showed Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Vicente Fox of the pro-business National Action Party would be  
in a near tie with the top two contenders from the ruling party, 
known as the PRI, if the vote were held today, the Indemerc Louis 
Harris poll said. 
</P>
<P>
	If the PRI nominated Tabasco state Gov. Roberto Madrazo, he  
would narrowly beat Fox 37 percent to 33 percent. Former Interior 
Minister Francisco Labastida, widely believed to be President 
Ernesto Zedillo's favorite, would be in a statistical tie against 
Fox, 36 percent to 34 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Indemerc Louis Harris, a Mexican firm associated with New  
York-based Louis Harris, questioned 4,500 people between ages 18 
and 64 in cities and towns across the country in June. The margin 
of error was 2.5 percentage points. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A man who fired off a series of e-mails  
asserting the financial instability of a bank -- triggering a run on 
the institution -- was arrested for creating financial panic, 
authorities said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Omar Olaya, 24, allegedly sent numerous e-mails on May 27  
to individuals and employees of Davivienda Bank, urging all account 
holders to withdraw their funds because of pending government 
intervention. 
</P>
<P>
	Panicked account holders withdrew $11.4 million from the bank in  
a single day, forcing the government to lend Davivienda some 
reserves. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Six writers were selected as finalists  
Thursday for the prestigious Romulo Gallegos prize, awarded every 
two years for Spanish-language novels. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner of the $60,000 prize will be announced Friday.  
</P>
<P>
	Previous winners include Gabriel Garcia Marquez, Mario Vargas  
Llosa and Carlos Fuentes. The prize was first awarded in 1967. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- The leader of the salsa band Niche, one  
of Colombia's most popular musicians, has been sentenced to six 
years in prison for receiving money from the Cali cocaine cartel. 
</P>
<P>
	Singer-songwriter Jairo Varela, 48, had been freed by a judge  
who found him innocent of charges of accepting $27,000 from cartel 
boss Miguel Rodriguez Orejuela. 
</P>
<P>
	But prosecutors appealed and an appeals court on Wednesday  
overturned the lower court ruling and issued the sentence, imposing 
in addition a fine of $34,000. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) -- Natural gas started flowing to Brazil on  
Thursday after President Hugo Banzer opened the valves of a $2 
billion pipeline, the largest investment project in Bolivian 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a historic moment for Brazil and Bolivia and for the  
integration of other Latin American countries,'' Banzer said at a 
ceremony in Rio Grande, where the pipeline begins. 
</P>
<P>
	The pipeline took a little more than a year to build.  
</P>
<P>
	Banzer said Thursday that the pipeline will have an important  
impact on the economy and has already created 4,000 new jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	The pipeline extends 1,900 miles from Rio Grande, Bolivia,  
through Corumba, Brazil, to the cities of Sao Paulo, Curitiba and 
Porto Alegre. 
</P>
<P>
	``With this project, Bolivia will become a regional center in  
the Southern Cone for the sale of natural gas for the entire 
region,'' Banzer said. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
  	   	
</P>
