<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Broughton Dairy Plant To Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) -- Broughton Foods Co.'s new parent  
company plans to close its Charleston dairy plant later this year, 
idling about 120 workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Marietta, Ohio-based Broughton was acquired last week by Suiza  
Foods Corp. of Dallas, one of the nation's largest dairy 
manufacturers. Among Suiza's other holdings is Morningstar Foods 
Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Products made at the Charleston plant, including sour cream,  
dips, dressings and coffee creamer, will be made at Morningstar 
plants in Wisconsin, Maryland and Texas, said Dan LaValley, senior 
vice president of Morningstar Foods. 
</P>
<P>
	LaValley said Wednesday the plant will close in three to four  
months. 
</P>
<P>
	The Charleston plant dates to 1930, when it was run by Blossom  
Dairy. Broughton bought the plant in 1965 and converted it to its 
present use as a high-temperature processing plant. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a reflection of the employees. It's a reflection  
of the facilities, which are outdated and obsolete,'' said plant 
manager Ron Arthur. 
</P>
<P>
	A nearby Broughton distribution center is unaffected by the  
move, company officials said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
