<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *Jane Beadon    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Jane Beadon, one of the leading witnesses in the  
sensational divorce case of the 11th Duke of Argyll, died 
Wednesday. She was 85. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Beadon was Jane Wigham in 1963 when she gave evidence  
against her stepdaughter Margaret, the Duchess of Argyll. 
</P>
<P>
	The divorce of Ian Douglas Campbell, 11th Duke of Argyll, chief  
of the Clan Campbell and Hereditary Master of the Royal Household 
in Scotland, and his wife made headlines worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	The case became notorious because of the mysterious ``headless  
man'' photographs. The pictures showed the duchess, wearing only 
three strands of pearls, taking part in a sex act with a naked man, 
whose head had been cut off by the camera. He has never been 
identified. 
</P>
<P>
	The duke sought a divorce on grounds of adultery and Jane Wigham  
testified on his behalf. 
</P>
<P>
	The duke was granted a divorce. The duchess, who the judge  
called promiscuous and ``wholly immoral'' in his ruling, died in 
1993 at age 80. 

</P>
<P>
                        *William M.B. Berger    	
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- William M.B. Berger, the white-bearded founder of  
the Berger Funds, died Tuesday. He was 74. 
</P>
<P>
	Berger came from a long line of bankers. His grandfather founded  
the Colorado National Bank in 1862. At age 26, Berger began 
managing a $100 million stock portfolio for the bank. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1960, Berger discovered the Centennial Fund, the first  
tax-free exchange fund. It allowed investors to trade their shares 
of stock for shares of the fund without incurring a tax liability. 
The Internal Revenue Service later changed its rules to stop the 
practice. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1966, he merged his Centennial Management Co. with Founders  
before starting the funds that bear his name eight years later. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to his own commercials, Berger made appearances on  
Wall Street Week and on several of CNBC's financial talk shows. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Cindy Duehring    	
</P>
<P>
	EPPING, N.D. (AP)-- Cindy Duehring, who won international honors  
for environmental research while being confined to her North Dakota 
home, died Tuesday. She was 36. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Duehring died in her home where she lived in isolation  
because of an extreme sensitivity to chemicals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Her organ system just broke down,'' said her husband, Jim, who  
was forced to live in a nearby cabin because the smells that clung 
to him after a day at work made his wife sick. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Duehring was among five people honored in Sweden in 1997  
with the Right Livelihood Awards, known as the ``alternative 
Nobels.'' Her husband flew to Sweden to accept her award. 
</P>
<P>
	She founded the Environmental Access Research Network, a group  
to help people suffering from chemical sensitivity, and answered 
hundreds of research requests per month. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Duehring traced her illness to the mid-1980s when an  
exterminator sprayed her Seattle apartment for fleas. Tests by a 
specialist in environmental medicine found pesticides had damaged 
her immune system. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Frank Gach    	
</P>
<P>
	ELKHART, Ind. (AP) -- Frank Gach, an American imprisoned at  
Auschwitz for selling commodities on the Polish black market, died 
Monday. He was 83. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1942, Gach and a group of friends were discovered by the  
Nazis and arrested and taken to the concentration camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Gach suffered severe injuries to both legs, but instead of being  
killed, he was let go. Of thousands of Americans imprisoned by the 
Nazis, Gach was among the approximately 200 who made it out alive. 
</P>
<P>
	He stayed in Poland until 1959. He and his family settled in  
Chicago, where Gach worked at Marshall Field &AMP; Co. before retiring 
in 1978. He and his wife, Helen, moved to Elkhart in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his wife, two daughters, two sons, 20  
grandchildren and 22 great-grandchildren. 

</P>
<P>
                            *John P. Howe    	
</P>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- John P. Howe, a physical chemist who helped  
develop the world's first nuclear reactors as part of the famed 
Manhattan Project team, died June 13. He was 88. 
</P>
<P>
	Howe was a 32-year-old chemistry professor at Brown University  
when he was recruited to study nuclear energy under physicist and 
Nobel Prize laureate Arthur Compton at the University of Chicago.	   Using the code name ``Metallurgical Laboratory,'' the team 
sought to create the world's first self-sustaining nuclear chain 
reaction. On Dec. 2, 1942, the Manhattan Project succeeded. By 
1944, large plutonium-producing reactors were operating in Hanford, 
Wash. Howe moved there to act as the Metallurgical Laboratory's 
liaison. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Walter Johnson    	
</P>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Walter Johnson, a former defensive lineman for  
the Cleveland Browns, died Tuesday after suffering a heart attack. 
He was 56. 
</P>
<P>
	Drafted in 1965 out of California State-Los Angeles, the  
6-foot-5, 265-pound tackle, once played in 167 consecutive games. 
He retired after the 1976 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson insisted on playing in the entire 1969 title game  
despite suffering frozen fingers in 8-degree weather in 
Bloomington, Minn. Minnesota beat Cleveland 27-7. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Joshua Nkomo    	
</P>
<P>
	HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Vice President Joshua Nkomo, the father  
of Zimbabwe's fight for independence from white colonial rule, died 
early today, the government said. He was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	State radio interrupted morning programs to play the national  
anthem and liberation songs, and broadcast a tribute by President 
Robert Mugabe. 
</P>
<P>
	Nkomo suffered from prostate cancer, and poor health forced him  
to largely withdraw from political life last year. Mugabe said 
Nkomo's health deteriorated sharply on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Nkomo was regarded by many as the guiding light of the nation's  
black nationalist movement, which fought a guerrilla war against 
white colonial rule for nearly three decades in the former British 
colony of Rhodesia. 
</P>
<P>
	But the traditional leader of the minority Ndebele tribe failed  
to achieve his goal of becoming the first black leader when 
Rhodesia became independent Zimbabwe in 1980. 
</P>
<P>
	``The old lion,'' as supporters fondly called him, wept when  
Mugabe's Zimbabwe African National Union party swept to victory in 
the first democratic elections. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
