<DOCNO> APW19990701.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 22:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Monsanto To Sell Sweetener Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Monsanto Co., seeking to reduce debt and focus  
strictly on life science products, is getting out of the artificial 
sweetener business. 
</P>
<P>
	The search for a buyer or buyers of the company's tabletop  
sweeteners, which include the best-selling NutraSweet brand, begins 
immediately and will be completed as quickly as possible, Monsanto 
spokeswoman Scarlett Lee Foster said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials with the St. Louis-based pharmaceutical and  
agricultural products company also announced plans Thursday to sell 
off the biogum division. Earlier this year, Monsanto said it would 
sell its algins food ingredients business. Biogums and algins are 
used mainly to improve the texture and processing of foods. 
</P>
<P>
	Together, the artificial sweetener, algins and biogum businesses  
had sales of $1 billion last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Proceeds from the divestitures will be used to reduce the  
company's debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Monsanto discovered aspartame, used to make NutraSweet, which is  
200 to 400 times sweeter than sugar and has just a trace of 
calories. Nutrasweet hit the market in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale of the artificial sweeteners business had been expected  
for some time. 
</P>
<P>
	``NutraSweet is very profitable, but the bulk of its growth is  
behind it,'' said analyst William Fiala of Edward Jones in St. 
Louis. ``It was really driven by the rapid growth of the diet soda 
market, and that has really started to taper off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Foster said Monsanto does not release specific sales figures for  
NutraSweet, but noted that it remains the world's best-selling 
artificial sweetener. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been an outstanding product,'' she said. ``It's just a  
shift in focus for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Monsanto said it planned to sell all divisions that  
aren't directly related to the company's agricultural or 
pharmaceutical business, which together are called the life 
sciences. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Monsanto's best sellers is its arthritis drug Celebrex.  
</P>
<P>
	Monsanto also announced several organizational changes Thursday.  
Hendrik A. Verfaillie, 53, was named chief operating officer and 
will continue as Monsanto president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990701.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 21:30:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil 4, Nigeria 3, OT </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANDOVER, Md. (AP) -- Sissi scored the first sudden-death  
overtime goal in Women's World Cup history, a 22-yard free kick in 
the 104th minute to give Brazil a 4-3 victory over Nigeria in 
Thursday night's quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
	After blowing a 3-0 halftime lead, Brazil advanced to meet the  
United States in the semifinals when Sissi's blast found the upper 
right corner of the net for her tournament-high seventh goal. 
</P>
<P>
	The victory put the Brazilians into a Fourth of July semifinal  
against the United States at Palo Alto, Calif --the same date and 
same venue as the Brazil-United States second-round match at the 
men's World Cup five years ago. The United States advanced with a 
hard-fought 3-2 victory over Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil, the prohibitive favorite, won that match 1-0 and went on  
to capture the Cup. When the women meet, the United States will be 
the favorite -- but not overwhelmingly so -- because of a Brazilian 
team with plenty of flair and a midfielder with a powerful free 
kick. 
</P>
<P>
	Sissi was involved in every Brazil goal, getting two assists and  
helping set up another score in addition to her ``Golden Goal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cidinha scored twice and Nene once, all in the first half, for  
Brazil before Nigeria rallied with goals from Prisca Emeafu, Nkiru 
Okosieme and Nkechi Egbe against a suddenly flat Brazilian defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Before 54,642 at Jack Kent Cooke Stadium, Sissi set up the first  
score in the fourth minute with a free kick from the right of the 
penalty box. 
</P>
<P>
	Goalkeeper Ann Chiejine headed the kick straight to Brazil's  
Raquel. Raquel's first shot was blocked by a defender, but her 
second was deflected by teammate Cidinha into the net. 
</P>
<P>
	Cidinha got her second goal in the 22nd minute when she headed  
Sissi's chipped cross at the far post. 
</P>
<P>
	Sissi got another assist in the 35th, making the final pass  
before Nene's 40-yard chip shot from the right of the box. Chiejine 
jumped too soon, allowing the ball to float over her head at the 
far post. Four minutes later, she was replaced in goal by Judith 
Chime. 
</P>
<P>
	Emeafu put Nigeria on the board in the 63rd with a short solo  
run after a defensive blunder, and Okosieme put in her own rebound 
after a cross from Patience Avre in the 72nd. 
</P>
<P>
	Nigeria tied the game on Egbe's 14-yard strike inside the far  
post in the 85th minute. 
</P>
<P>
	Nigeria played the final minutes with 10 players after Avre was  
ejected in the 87th when she received a second yellow card. 
</P>
<P>
	As a consolation, Nigeria qualified for the 2000 Olympics with  
its second-half rally. A 3-0 defeat would have eliminated the 
Nigerians, but a one-goal loss makes Russia the lone World Cup 
quarterfinalist not to earn a place in Sydney. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990701.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 08:09:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Queen Opens Scottish Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) -- In a colorful ceremony melding  
populism with ancient tradition, Queen Elizabeth II today opened 
Scotland's first Parliament in nearly 300 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``My prayers are with you all as you embark on this new and  
historic journey,'' the queen declared, inaugurating the 129-member 
assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have trust in the good judgment of the Scottish people ... I  
am confident in the future of Scotland,'' she added. 
</P>
<P>
	The non-political monarch made no direct reference to the hopes  
of independence-seeking nationalists that the new body will lead to 
the breakup of her kingdom, which unites Scotland with England, 
Wales and Northern Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Minister Tony Blair's Labor Party, the largest group in  
the assembly, hopes the restoration of the Parliament will preserve 
the United Kingdom -- but in a new form, with power decentralized 
from the government in London. 
</P>
<P>
	Due to speak at the Edinburgh opening, Blair canceled to remain  
in Northern Ireland, where he struggled to persuade Protestants and 
Catholics to set aside their differences and form the local 
government envisioned in last year's peace accord. 
</P>
<P>
	The queen opened Wales' new assembly last month.  
</P>
<P>
	In Edinburgh, the monarch rode to the Parliament building in an  
open, horsedrawn carriage, escorted by members of the Household 
Cavalry from the Palace of Holyroodhouse, her Scottish residence. 
She was accompanied in the carriage by her husband, Prince Philip, 
and heir, Prince Charles. 
</P>
<P>
	In an informal note, lawmakers strolled to the ceremony in  
brilliant sunshine, wading through crowds that included 
schoolchildren carrying banners from across Scotland. 
</P>
<P>
	They all -- monarch and subjects -- followed the same steep,  
cobbled Royal Mile that lawmakers walked or rode when Scotland's 
Parliament last met three centuries ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The queen did not wear the crown or glittering robes in which  
she opens Parliament in London. Instead, she sported a purple coat 
and hat over a green dress, topped with a stole incorporating a 
design based on the Scottish emblem of the thistle. 
</P>
<P>
	During the ceremony, the key song was the 18th-century poet  
Robert Burns' ``A Man's a Man For A'That,'' instead of the ``God 
Save The Queen,'' the British anthem. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've waited 300 years for this -- I feel so proud,'' said  
Deborah Gillespie, 26, as she watched the Duke of Hamilton, head of 
Scotland's top aristocratic family, bring the Crown of Scotland to 
the Parliament. 
</P>
<P>
	Parachutists floated down and a 21-gun salute boomed over the  
city, decked out with Union Jacks,the British flag, and Scotland's 
blue and white flag of St. Andrew. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollywood legend Sean Connery, an ardent Scottish nationalist,  
arrived in full Highland dress, after declaring the event was 
better than winning an Academy Award. 
</P>
<P>
	Power devolved formally to the Parliament on Thursday, enabling  
it to raise taxes and legislate on a range of domestic functions, 
including education, health, legal affairs and local government. 
</P>
<P>
	England and Scotland have shared a monarch since 1603, a century  
before their 1707 union under a single Parliament in London. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990701.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 08:09:55 </DATE_TIME>
