<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Continues Abortion Funds Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate voted Thursday to continue barring  
federal workers' health-insurance plans from covering most 
abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	By 51-47, senators approved language banning the benefit and  
included it in a $27.7 billion measure financing the Treasury 
Department and several smaller agencies in the coming fiscal year. 
The overall bill was approved by voice vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also leaves open the possibility that members of  
Congress will allow themselves a cost-of-living pay raise of about 
$4,600 next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a 1989 law, lawmakers get an annual pay raise unless they  
vote to deny it. The Treasury bill is the traditional vehicle for a 
provision doing that, and so far it contains no such prohibition. 
</P>
<P>
	A House version of the measure, approved only by a subcommittee  
so far, also lacks language that would block the pay raise. 
Lawmakers currently earn $136,700, a level they reached two years 
ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The abortion prohibition for federal employees would allow  
exceptions for cases of rape, incest and when the woman's life is 
in jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, sponsored the abortion ban, saying 73  
percent of the cost of federal workers' health plans comes from 
taxpayers' dollars. He said abortions ``violate the conscience of 
many taxpayers'' and federal dollars should not be used to pay for 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., said the 1.2 million women  
affected by the prohibition would lose coverage for a procedure 
that privately employed women have. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you can't repeal her right to choose, take away her ability  
to pay for what is legal,'' Boxer said of her opponents' tactics. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton administration officials said in a written statement the  
White House ``would strongly oppose'' the prohibition, but did not 
mention a veto threat. The ban has been included in the bill all 
but two years since 1983, DeWine said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury bill includes $8.2 billion for the Internal Revenue  
Service, nearly $200 million less than this year. And it would cut 
President Clinton's $195 million request for an anti-drug media 
campaign by $50 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate also moved toward approving $411 million in federal  
contributions to the District of Columbia's city budget. The 
measure bans the use of federal or district funds for most 
abortions. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the House Appropriations Committee approved a $14.1  
billion measure financing federal land and cultural programs, and 
an $8.45 billion bill for military construction projects. 
</P>
<P>
	The land bill provides nearly $1.2 billion less than Clinton  
wants, cutting his requests for land and water conservation, 
purchase of property for federal and state parks, restoration of 
Florida's Everglades and energy conservation efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	The committee approved an amendment by Rep. Lucille  
Roybal-Allard, D-Calif., that would allow women to breast-feed in 
national parks or cultural institutions covered by the bill. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
