	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- A former Stanford football star was  
sentenced to two years in prison Wednesday for sex crimes involving 
boys. 
</P>
<P>
	Eric Abrams, 25, pleaded no contest earlier this year to false  
imprisonment and child molestation for posing as a Nike salesman 
and luring a 14-year-old boy into his apartment. 
</P>
<P>
	Abrams also faces charges in San Francisco, where he allegedly  
impersonated a police officer and ordered a 13-year-old boy to 
strip for a drug search. Prosecutors also have accused him of 
trying to order two other boys into his car on the same day. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, he pleaded no contest to charges of posing as a  
Stanford recruiter and for telling high school football players 
that he needed nude photos of them to evaluate their physical 
condition. 
</P>
<P>
	The former placekicker, who played for the Cardinal from  
1992-95, is Stanford's career scoring leader with 282 points. 

  	   	
