<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Scher's Conviction Overturned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- After spending nearly two years in prison for  
the 1976 shooting death of his friend, Dr. Stephen Scher has been 
set free by a court ruling that overturned his murder conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	A smiling Scher walked out of a state prison Wednesday, saying  
he felt ``wonderful'' as he climbed into the back of a gold 
Cadillac to meet his wife -- the dead man's widow. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today is obviously a very happy day for everybody,'' his  
lawyer, John Moses said. 
</P>
<P>
	Scher, 59, was serving a life sentence after being convicted in  
1997 of shooting his friend, Martin Dillon, at Dillon's hunting 
camp. Scher had claimed that Dillon was chasing a porcupine, 
tripped and shot himself. 
</P>
<P>
	The shooting originally was ruled an accident and, two years  
afterward, Scher married Dillon's widow, Patricia. 
</P>
<P>
	Dillon's father pressed prosecutors to reopen the case and  
authorities exhumed Dillon's body in 1995. They conducted an 
autopsy and decided to charge Scher, citing new evidence that 
undercut his claim that he was more than 100 feet away when 
Martin's shotgun went off. 
</P>
<P>
	During the trial, Scher changed his story and acknowledged he  
had been having an affair with Dillon's wife. He testified the gun 
went off in a struggle that started when he told Dillon about the 
affair. 
</P>
<P>
	Scher said he lied about the shooting for more than two decades  
to protect Dillon's widow, and the dead man's two children, whom 
Scher raised. 
</P>
<P>
	A state court panel ruled June 7 that the 20-year interval  
between the shooting and Scher's arrest was too long and violated 
Scher's due-process rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The court said the conviction was tainted by memories that had  
faded, evidence that had disappeared and witnesses who had died 
between Dillon's death and Scher's arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	The state Supreme Court ruled Monday that Scher could be  
released, but required him to post a $750,000 bond to allow 
prosecutors time to appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	As additional conditions of his release, Scher was required to  
surrender his passport and limit his travel. 
</P>
<P>
	Pennsylvania Attorney General Michael Fisher intends to appeal  
Scher's release, a spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will argue that the conviction should be reinstated and he  
should be returned to prison to serve out his life sentence for 
first-degree murder,'' said Fisher's spokesman, Kevin Harley. 
</P>
<P>
	Moses said Scher was eager to be reunited with his family and  
will apply to get his North Carolina medical license back. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
