<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aircraft Parts Maker Pleads Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A Miami aircraft parts maker and a company  
executive pleaded guilty to taking safety shortcuts on parts sold 
to military and commercial buyers, federal prosecutors said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a plea agreement, Air-Pro Inc. agreed to pay a $200,000  
fine, notify its customers and offer to replace the parts. John 
Wilson, vice president and operations manager, faces up to five 
years in prison and a $250,000 fine at sentencing Sept. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	Both pleaded guilty Wednesday to making false representations on  
the sale of nonconforming aircraft parts. 
</P>
<P>
	An investigation found Air-Pro employees changed so-called cure  
dates by as much as five years on hose tags to make them look 
newer, fooling buyers about the life expectancy of crucial fuel, 
oil and hydraulic hoses. The military rejects the rubber hose 
assemblies after six to eight years. 
</P>
<P>
	In another instance, Air-Pro applied a weaker coating to chafing  
sleeves on landing gear hose assemblies when a Teflon coating was 
required. The substitute was less resistant to abrasives and failed 
at a lower temperature. 
</P>
<P>
	Air-Pro also failed to properly clean and test systems supplying  
oxygen to pilots and passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	The company had contracts with the Defense Department, Air Force  
and Defense Logistics Agency and was approved by the Federal 
Aviation Administration as an aviation hose manufacturer. 
</P>
<P>
	Wilson had no comment when contacted Thursday; his attorney was  
out of town and not immediately available for comment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
