<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Agrees to New Telecom Bidding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States reached a trade agreement  
Thursday with Japan aimed at making sure that U.S. and other 
foreign telecommunications companies will be treated fairly when 
they compete for sales to Japan's Nippon Telegraph and Telephone 
Co. and its successor companies. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky said the United  
States had achieved all of its objectives in the four days of talks 
held in San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	NTT is being broken up into four companies. Barshefsky said the  
new deal will ensure that U.S. and other foreign companies will not 
be discriminated against in competition for sales of 
telecommunications equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	NTT purchased more than $10 billion of telecommunications  
equipment in 1997, the latest year for which data is available; of 
that total, $1.5 billion was purchased from foreign companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``U.S. companies, world leaders in the new technologies in  
demand worldwide, are well positioned to increase their sales to 
the NTT successor companies,'' Barshefsky said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials said the main sticking point in the marathon  
bargaining sessions was the insistence by the American side that 
Japan's government play an active oversight role in monitoring 
whether the Japanese companies were fulfilling their obligations 
under the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior U.S. trade official said the final agreement satisfied  
U.S. demands in this area, including annual meetings between the 
two countries to review purchase data. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
