<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Automakers Make Gains in US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Foreign automakers continued to increase their  
U.S. market share last month as demand for many new cars and light 
trucks exceeded the robust sales of June 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales at the Chrysler unit of DaimlerChrysler AG, meanwhile,  
were off 5 percent compared with its record sales a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think we've got a little blip,'' said sales executive Jamie  
Jameson. ``We're fully expecting the numbers to whipsaw right back 
in July.'' 
</P>
<P>
	General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co. planned to report their  
June sales today. 
</P>
<P>
	Each of Japan's Big Three posted gains: Toyota Motor Corp. and  
Nissan Motor Co. were up 5 percent, while Honda Motor Co. edged up 
just over 1.5 percent. The biggest percentage improvements once 
again came from European automakers, several of which posted 
double-digit gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Volkswagen AG reported its strongest June in 26 years and its  
best month overall since May 1979. Its sales were up 23 percent 
over a year ago, due in large part to the success of its redesigned 
Jetta compact sedan -- the nation's best-selling European car. VW 
sold 13,101 Jettas in June for its best month since the nameplate 
was introduced 19 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Audi AG had its most successful June since 1987 with a 44  
percent sales increase from a year ago. Its new TT sports car was 
off to a strong start in its second month. Saab AB, meanwhile, had 
a 34 percent sales increase last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the drop in June sales for DaimlerChrysler's Chrysler,  
Plymouth, Dodge and Jeep brands, the German-American automaker said 
the unit posted a record first half with just over 1.39 million 
sales, and had its best quarter ever in April through June. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think the market continues to show strength, and we have a  
robust production schedule planned to match that demand,'' said 
James P. Holden, executive vice president of sales and marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	The comparison to June 1998 was tough for DaimlerChrysler. Big  
``loyalty coupon'' discounts that the three Detroit automakers 
offered to consumers that month generated unusually strong sales; 
the former Chrysler Corp. set an all-time monthly record in June 
1998, a mark that stood until last May. 
</P>
<P>
	Car sales took the hardest hit at DaimlerChrysler last month,  
down 14 percent, while truck sales were off about 1.5 percent. Much 
of the decline was due to a 19 percent drop in minivan sales, which 
Jameson blamed on low inventories after a big dealer incentive 
program in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Toyota's gain gave the automaker its strongest June and  
best-ever second quarter. Though Toyota's U.S. car sales were off 
10 percent, its truck sales soared 35 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Most ominous for Detroit's automakers was the news that Toyota's  
new Tundra full-size pickup had the best first-month U.S. sales of 
any Toyota model ever. Toyota sold 8,011 Tundras last month, 
breaking the previous first-model record of 3,339 set by the Tercel 
subcompact in October 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford, GM and Dodge have dominated the full-size pickup market  
for decades. The V8-powered Tundra, assembled in Princeton, Ind., 
is the first serious challenge by a foreign automaker in the 
full-size pickup market. 
</P>
<P>
	New models also helped boost Nissan's sales. The Xterra sport  
utility vehicle had one of the best first month's sales figures in 
the company's history, with 5,470 sold. The Nissan Crew cab pickup 
and Quest minivan also sold well, offsetting an 11 percent decline 
in car sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Honda set June and half-year records. The biggest percentage  
gain was for Honda's redesigned Odyssey minivan; its sales were up 
277 percent. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
