<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Federal Judges Getting Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- After a delay of many months, President  
Clinton's judicial nominees are beginning to trickle through the 
Senate confirmation process. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate confirmed five judges Wednesday, and the Senate  
Judiciary Committee sent three additional appointments to the floor 
in a brief meeting Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The action comes after a delay of many months in which Sen.  
Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, the committee chairman, blocked action on the 
administration's appointees in an attempt to have a citizen of Utah 
appointed to the bench. Hatch's selection, gubernatorial aide Ted 
Stewart, drew opposition from environmentalists. 
</P>
<P>
	But one Republican source, who spoke on condition of anonymity,  
said the FBI has completed its background check on Stewart, and a 
report on Stewart is due back from the American Bar Association 
shortly. Both steps are part of the customary pre-nomination 
routine. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The five appointees confirmed by the Senate Wednesday include W.  
Allen Pepper Jr. of Mississippi, a college roommate of Senate 
Majority Leader Trent Lott at Ole Miss. Also confirmed was Karen E. 
Schreier of South Dakota, the home state of Senate Democratic 
Leader Tom Daschle. 
</P>
<P>
	Also approved were Keith Ellison of Texas, Stefan Underhill of  
Connecticut and Gary Feess of California. 
</P>
<P>
	Only two other judges had been confirmed by the Senate since the  
beginning of the year, and they were holdovers from the last 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	The nominees approved by the committee included Marsha L. Berzon  
of California, named to the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. She 
was approved on a vote of 10-8, with Hatch and Sen. Arlen Specter, 
R-Pa., siding with the Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	The other two were Robert Katzmann, named to the 2nd U.S.  
Circuit Court of Appeals; and T. John Ward, nominated to be a 
district judge for the Eastern District of Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	According to statistics kept by Democrats, there are still 37  
Clinton judicial nominees pending in the Judiciary Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch promised Democrats there would be at least one day for  
judicial nomination hearings in July, but declined to promise a 
second. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. John McCain, GOP presidential contender and leading  
advocate of an overhaul of campaign finance laws, drew some 
unusually blunt advice from Lott during the day. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Arizona lawmaker expected to demand a debate on  
campaign finance laws next month, Lott told reporters that 
``Senator McCain should concentrate on his presidential campaign, 
on Y2K liability (legislation). ... He's got a lot of work that 
needs to be done that the country needs and it would serve him 
better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not quite finished, Lott went on:  
</P>
<P>
	``When you're out there raising money right and left and then  
you're talking about how you need to reform the system, it rings a 
little hollow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a written statement, McCain responded that he has raised  
money following the spirit of the reforms he has proposed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to try to keep the majority leader's attention  
focused on this issue so that he won't make any other uninformed 
mistakes on national television,'' he said. 

</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic political strategists in both the House and Senate  
are still waiting to hear from Rep. Bernard Sanders, an independent 
lawmaker from Vermont, about his election plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders, who is serving his fifth term in the House, has flirted  
for months with jumping into the race against GOP Sen. Jim 
Jeffords, and Senate Democrats have made no secret of their 
interest in having him run. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand, Democrats who are gunning to take control of  
the House would like to see him seek re-election to his current 
job. While elected as an independent, Sanders sides with Democrats 
on organizational matters, and they, in turn, protect his committee 
seniority. 
</P>
<P>
	Party officials earlier in the year said they expected Sanders  
to make up his mind by the end of June. But that date has passed, 
and now he's promising a decision later this summer. Democrats also 
said Sanders told them he intends to commission a poll to gauge his 
standing in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	House Democrats got some good news on the political front  
recently, when New Jersey Rep. Frank Pallone gave up on his plans 
to run for the Senate. His decision means one less open seat for 
Republicans to target and for Democrats to defend. 
</P>
<P>
	Another Democratic lawmaker, Rep. David Minge of Minnesota, is  
exploring a race for the Senate. He said in an interview he hopes 
to make a decision by the end of the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	A switch of six seats in next year's elections would deliver  
control of the House to the Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Shades of impeachment.  
</P>
<P>
	Monica Lewinsky was the subject of discourse in the Senate  
during the day for the first time since Clinton's impeachment trial 
ended in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., was arguing against legislation to  
limit Y2K lawsuits, and referred to a late-night negotiating phone 
call that fellow Sen. Chris Dodd, D-Conn., had made to the White 
House late one night. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who can call the president after midnight other than Monica,''  
Hollings asked? ``For heaven's sake. 
</P>
<P>
	``The senator for Connecticut.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
