<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stock Prices Close Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks gained in Thursday trading, riding  
an overnight rally on Wall Street sparked by the Federal Reserve's 
decision to nudge up interest rates. The U.S. dollar edged lower 
against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose a sharp 331.01  
points, or 1.89 percent, to 17,860.75 at the close of the afternoon 
session. On Wednesday, the average closed down 252.05 points, or 
1.42 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.82 yen at 3 p.m. (0600 GMT), down 0.04 yen  
from late Wednesday in Tokyo and below its late New York level of 
120.93 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tokyo stock market started higher in a follow-through move  
from New York where the Dow Jones industrial average rose 155.45 
points, or 1.4 percent, to close at 10,970.80 on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
exchange's first section rose 31.21 points, or 2.20 percent, to 
1,447.41 at the end of the afternoon session. The TOPIX closed down 
9.04 points, or 0.63 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	Among international and high-technology blue chips, Sony and  
Softbank hit all-time high levels. Volume on the First Section of 
the Tokyo Stock Exchange was estimated at 626.15 million shares, up 
from 572.11 million shares Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Market participants now await the results of the Bank of Japan's  
quarterly ``tankan'' survey of business sentiment, due out Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Further stock market rises require gains in shares linked to  
domestic demand,'' said Kunihiro Hatae, general manager at Tokyo 
Securities Co. ``The tankan should confirm an improvement in 
confidence, and boost domestic-demand stocks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As expected, the Fed raised short-term U.S. interest rates by a  
quarter point -- an anticipated move that did not have a major 
impact on currency trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese officials applauded the hike.  
</P>
<P>
	``I believe the ... decision to hike rates was appropriate. It  
was made in line with the status of the U.S. economy,'' said 
Haruhiko Kuroda, head of the international bureau at Japan's 
Finance Ministry. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed did surprise markets, however, by announcing it was  
abandoning its bias toward raising rates further. 
</P>
<P>
	News that the Fed was adopting a neutral stance toward interest  
rates -- meaning it was no longer leaning toward raising them -- sent 
some investors away from the U.S. currency. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher interest rates mean higher returns on liquid investments  
held in that currency, so the prospect that U.S. rates may not 
increase for a while made the dollar less attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the greenback moved lower from its New  
York level after U.S. funds sold dollars to invest in Japanese 
stocks, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 125.36 yen, up from  
125.06 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese government bond fell to  
1.7600 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.8500 percent, driving 
its price up to 100.34 yen from 99.57 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
