<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Rise; Dow Closes at 11,066.42 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average extended its  
stunning gains today, flirting with a new record as investors 
reveled in the new interest rate environment. 
</P>
<P>
	At the close of trading on Wall Street, the Dow was up 95.62 at  
11,066.42. The blue-chip index held steadily above 11,000 for the 
first time in weeks, and inched within 28 points of its May 13 
record close of 11,107.19. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators including the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 and  
Nasdaq composite index also rose, hitting record highs for a second 
consecutive session. 
</P>
<P>
	Tthe Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 8.07 to 1,380.78, and the  
Nasdaq composite index rose 20.09 to 2,706.21. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 11-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,697 up, 1,385 down and 487 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE volume totaled 828.57 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs. 1.11  
billion in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 3.32 to 651.45, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index fell 3.28 to 794.65. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 3.26 to 454.42.  
</P>
<P>
	``There is an extraordinary amount of enthusiasm,'' said William  
Meehan, chief market analyst for Cantor Fitzgerald. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors again applauded the long-expected decision Wednesday  
by the Federal Reserve to raise short-term interest rates 
one-quarter percentage point. The market was especially heartened 
by the Fed's policy shift to a ``neutral'' bias on the need for 
future rate increases. 
</P>
<P>
	``Greenspan, by removing his bias to tighten, has flashed a red  
cape in front of the bull market,'' Meehan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Leading the charge today were semiconductor stocks including  
Intel and financial-services stocks, which thrived on the hope that 
interest rates may remain stable for at least the near future. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Shobin, a technical analyst with Lehman Brothers Inc.,  
said the market's big gains were somewhat surprising in light of 
the Dow's 155.45 point rise Wednesday, when the S&AMP;P 500 and the 
Nasdaq hit new closing highs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really a sign of great strength that this market  
continues to be able to reach new levels,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock prices faltered this morning in tandem with bonds, which  
dropped after the National Association of Purchasing Management 
reported the manufacturing sector expanded at a 
stronger-than-expected pace in June. The report suggested the 
threats of inflation that first prompted the Federal Reserve to 
raise interest rates Wednesday may not have evaporated. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices plunged following the report, pushing the yield on  
the 30-year Treasury bond to 6.02 percent, up from 5.96 late 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks shrugged off the bond market's concerns. ``A little  
hiccup in bond land is not likely to end the mania on Wall 
Street,'' Meehan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gourmet coffee company Starbucks tumbled after surprising Wall  
Street with a forecast of lower than expected earnings for the next 
two quarters and for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Drug stocks were mostly higher, led by Eli Lilly. Lehman  
Brothers added the stock to its ``10 Uncommon Values'' list of 
recommended stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	A number of smaller companies had wild price swings as the Frank  
Russell Co. shuffled the component stocks of its indexes, which 
include the widely-followed Russell 2000. The changes mean that 
portfolios modeled after the indexes have to be adjusted as well. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
