<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 66.18 at 11,036.98 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher today, with blue chips  
inching back toward record levels, as investors got their bearings 
in the new interest rate environment. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 66.18 at 11,036.98 after searching for a direction in morning 
trading. Since hitting a new closing high of 11,107.19 on May 13, 
the Dow has struggled to revisit the 11,000 level. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators also reversed early losses. The  
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 6.09 to 1,378.75, and the Nasdaq 
composite index was up 23.42 to 2,709.54. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock prices briefly faltered in tandem with bonds, which  
dropped after the National Association of Purchasing Management 
reported the manufacturing sector expanded at a 
stronger-than-expected pace in June. The report suggested the 
threats of inflation that first prompted the Federal Reserve to 
raise interest rates Wednesday may not have evaporated. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock and bond markets both rallied Wednesday after the Fed  
followed through on expectations and raised rates one-quarter 
percentage point. But the purchasing managers' report rattled bonds 
today, pushing the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond to 6.02 
percent, up from 5.96 late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks shrugged off the bond market's concerns. ``A little  
hiccup in bond land is not likely to end the mania on Wall 
Street,'' said William Meehan, chief market analyst for Cantor 
Fitzgerald. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the Dow rose 155.45 points and the S&AMP;P 500 and the  
Nasdaq hit new closing highs. More than the rate increase, which 
was frequently telegraphed by Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan, 
investors applauded the Fed's policy shift to a ``neutral'' bias on 
the need for future rate increases. 
</P>
<P>
	``Greenspan, by removing his bias to tighten, has flashed a red  
cape in front of the bull market,'' Meehan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gourmet coffee company Starbucks tumbled after surprising Wall  
Street with a forecast of lower than expected earnings for the next 
two quarters and for the year. Starbucks fell 11 3/4 to 25 13/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Drug stocks were mostly higher, led by Eli Lilly, which gained 3  
9/16 to 75 3/16. Lehman Brothers added the stock to its ``10 
Uncommon Values'' list of recommended stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	A number of smaller companies sustained wild price swings as the  
Frank Russell Co. shuffled the component stocks of its indexes, 
which include the widely-followed Russell 2000. The changes mean 
that portfolios modeled after the indexes have to be adjusted as 
well. 
</P>
<P>
	Pitt-Des Moines, a construction subcontractor that trades on the  
American Stock Exchange, was down 26 at 36 1/2 after rising 30 points 
in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 on the New  
York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 658.05 million shares, 
behind Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 1.62 at 649.75, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was down 4.83 at 793.10. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 was down 4.14 at 453.54.  



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
