<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gun Control Delay Decried </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and some Democrats on  
Wednesday accused Republicans of trying to kill Senate-passed gun 
controls by putting off negotiations on the issue until mid-July. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've learned what delay means to gun bills,'' said D.C.  
Delegate Eleanor Holmes Norton. ``The goal of the (GOP) leadership 
is not delay; the goal of the leadership is to defeat the bill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert had told reporters June 24 he would  
name negotiators this week to iron out differences in the House and 
Senate bills. 
</P>
<P>
	But Republican leaders decided this week to wait until after  
Congress returns July 12 from its July Fourth holiday recess to 
begin the process. 
</P>
<P>
	The preliminary staff work needed for the negotiations ``is just  
taking longer than we expected,'' said Hastert's spokesman, John 
Feehrey. 
</P>
<P>
	``The intention is to appoint conferees and have this matter  
resolved one way or the other,'' Senate Judiciary Committee 
Chairman Orrin Hatch said Wednesday. ``My goal is to have this 
conference report voted on before (we) go out for August recess.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate passed White House-backed gun control legislation  
last month in response to shootings at a Colorado high school and 
elsewhere. The same provisions -- including mandatory background 
checks for all gun show sales -- were rejected by the House. The 
House later killed a measure that contained weaker curbs. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, since both the House and Senate have approved legislation  
dealing with juvenile crime, negotiations on a compromise are 
expected. Hastert told reporters June 24 that ``the American people 
intend us to'' address guns as part of a bill responding to high 
school shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, told reporters that the  
negotiators would not be named until Congress returns in mid-July.	   President Clinton called the delay ``a grave mistake'' and 
pushed for the Senate restrictions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Congress should make such measures the law of the land without  
further delay,'' Clinton said in a three-paragraph letter Wednesday 
to Hastert. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of Democratic women lawmakers said they would beat the  
drum for gun control back home in their districts over the break. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
