<DOCNO> APW19990701.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 12:10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Advises on Fireworks Caution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fourth of July fireworks should be enjoyed  
from afar and beneath the stars to avoid hospital emergency rooms, 
federal safety officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Consumer Product Safety Commission issued its annual warning  
about the dangers of fireworks by demonstrating the hazards of 
popular, and usually illegal, devices such as sparklers, bottle 
rockets, M-80s and M-1000s. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we near the year 2000, more of us than ever before will  
celebrate with fireworks,'' said Ann Brown, the commission 
chairwoman. ``These devices are best left to the professionals 
because even those that seem innocent can cause serious injury.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just ask Matthew Scott, a 38-year-old paramedic from Absecon,  
N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, Scott became the recipient of nation's first hand  
transplant. On Thursday, he said he wished he was never in the 
position to make such medical history. 
</P>
<P>
	Scott lost his hand 14 years ago during ``a little horseplay''  
with friends and an illegal M-80 during the December holiday 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``My life was never the same, and it never will be the same,''  
he said. ``Yes, I was lucky enough to be selected to get the hand 
transplant on my left hand but all things considered, I wish I 
never had to make that choice. I wish I never picked up that device 
and I wish I never lit it. In an instant, my entire hand was gone. 
It affected not only me, but my family, my friends who were there 
with me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The CPSC noted that emergency rooms treated 8,500 fireworks  
injuries last year, about 40 percent of the them suffered by 
children under 15. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency, working with the Customs Service, has seized more  
than 400 million unsafe fireworks at U.S. docks since 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	To reduce the risk of injuries from fireworks, the CPSC  
suggested consumers should: 
</P>
<P>
	--Never allow children to play with fireworks.  
</P>
<P>
	--Read and follow all fireworks warnings and instructions.  
</P>
<P>
	--Never try to relight fireworks that have not fully functioned.  
</P>
<P>
	--Keep a bucket of water nearby in case of accident or fire.  
</P>
<P>
	--Only light fireworks on a smooth, flat surface away from  
houses, dry leaves and flammable materials. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990701.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 15:31:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Barron Davis Arrives in Charlotte </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- It wasn't hard to pick out the newest  
member of the Charlotte Hornets at the team's headquarters 
Thursday. Baron Davis was the one walking around with the big 
smile, and with good reason. 
</P>
<P>
	Less than 24 hours after the Hornets made Davis the third  
overall selection in the 1999 NBA draft, he was starting to 
appreciate the events that landed him in what looks like a 
relatively charmed spot. 
</P>
<P>
	The nature of the NBA draft is such that the high picks  
generally go to the worst teams, and this year's draft followed 
that course -- with the exception of the Hornets and Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	While the other top choices found themselves taken by such  
struggling teams as the Bulls, Grizzlies and Clippers, Davis landed 
with a franchise that has posted three consecutive winning seasons. 
The Hornets rallied in the second half of last season to finish at 
26-24, one game short of a playoff berth. 
</P>
<P>
	But because they failed to qualify for the postseason, they  
wound up in the draft lottery, seemingly destined for no better 
than the 13th selection. But they beat the odds by winning the 
third pick, and now Davis has done the same thing by landing with a 
team that doesn't face a long rebuilding process. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got the sweet end of the deal,'' a beaming Davis said. ``I  
feel sorry for those other guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Immediately ahead for the 20-year-old point guard is acclimating  
himself to the NBA and the Hornets, who already have a starting 
point guard in six-year pro David Wesley. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's going to help Baron tremendously,'' coach Paul Silas  
said. ``He'll get a chance to work himself in, learn the league, 
learn what he can do and what he can't. There's going to be 
virtually no pressure on him to come out of the gates smoking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis doesn't plan to be tentative about the start of his NBA  
career. He was known as a tough, physical player at UCLA, and he 
intends to continue that style with the Hornets. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm trying to take your head off,'' said Davis, who bounced  
back from knee surgery to lead UCLA in scoring, assists and steals 
in 1998-99, his second and final season with the Bruins. ``I'm 
trying to go at you all night. If it gets physical, it gets 
physical. That's what I like,'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, a California native who was raised in the Los Angeles  
area, said staying close to home would have been a preference for 
his pro career. Since that didn't work out, Davis said he's excited 
about coming to Charlotte and adapting to the East Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	``I look at it as an adjustment, a new beginning in life,'' he  
said. ``It's an opportunity to get away, to be out on my own, get a 
feel for life and grow as an individual. I'm looking forward to the 
challenges ahead.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990701.0244 </DOCNO>
