<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Speaks on Bush, Fundraising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush, banking a record  
$36 million for his presidential race, would be lining up with 
Republicans ``unanimously hostile'' to campaign finance reform if 
he rejects federal spending limits, President Clinton said today. 
</P>
<P>
	``The American people will have to make up their minds about  
whether this is an important issue or not,'' the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the nation's most avid political watcher, he refused to  
handicap the race and speculate whether Bush already has the GOP 
nomination sewn up. ``I don't have a clue,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush broke ahead of the entire 2000 pack when he announced this  
week that he had raised over the last four months a stunning $36 
million for Campaign 2000. Clinton's hand-picked successor, Vice 
President Al Gore, has raised just $18 million in the first half of 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush's haul heightened speculation that he would forgo federal  
matching funds for his primary campaign and the spending limits 
that go with them. Advocates of campaign finance reform have 
worried that such a move would undercut attempts at tighter finance 
rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``The leadership of the Republican Party in general are  
unanimously hostile to campaign finance reform. They don't believe 
in it. And so if he did that, he would have that in common with the 
other leaders who won't let us bring'' campaign finance reform 
legislation to a vote in Congress, Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Professional politicos were wowed by Bush's cash tally, but  
Clinton brushed aside its impact. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most valuable commodity in an election in a democracy ...  
even more valuable than money, is ideas,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	On ideas, Clinton added, Gore wins. ``He is the only candidate  
who has yet told the American people what he wanted to do if he got 
elected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president added, in response to a later question, that he  
did not intend his comments to be ``a dig'' at Gore's only 
Democratic rival for the nomination, former New Jersey Sen. Bill 
Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about news reports that Clinton was furious with Gore for  
campaign statements explicitly and repeatedly distancing himself 
from the president's personal behavior in the Monica Lewinsky 
affair, Clinton said he was ``bewildered'' by the stories and 
didn't know their source. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are not in my heart or my mind,'' Clinton said.  
</P>
<P>
	The president spoke in a joint news conference with Egyptian  
President Hosni Mubarak. 
</P>
<P>
	With Middle East tensions dominating their private talks, the  
two presidents exchanged before the news cameras congratulations 
for their respective commitments to renewing the Mideast peace 
process. 
</P>
<P>
	``Valuable time has been wasted,'' Mubarak said.  
</P>
<P>
	Clinton said he wants to give Israeli Prime Minister-elect Ehud  
Barak ``more freedom of movement to move aggressively ahead'' on 
the peace track. ``I do think that the time is right,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about the lingering stalemate with Iraqi President Saddam  
Hussein, Clinton reiterated that he supports relaxing an 
international embargo for strictly humanitarian reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never wanted the Iraqi people to suffer because of their  
leader,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	But, he added, ``I do not believe we should give up on an  
attempt -- an insistence, indeed -- that the United Nations, in 
return for this'' should demand strict arms control measures. 
</P>
<P>
	On another foreign policy matter that has claimed his attention  
throughout his 6 1/2-year presidency, Clinton addressed the peace 
talks in Northern Ireland, which are once again at a crisis point. 
</P>
<P>
	The president, who has a personal stake in the implementation of  
last year's Good Friday accord, brokered by his own peace envoy, 
has worked the phones in the last 24 hours trying to break the 
stalemate in Belfast. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a very difficult problem for the parties, but it will be  
very hard for the world to understand if this breaks off, since 
everyone's agreed to the fundamental elements of the Good Friday 
agreement,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	``To call it a tragedy would be a gross understatement.''  
</P>
<P>
	He added that the British, Irish and political leaders of  
Northern Ireland ``do seem determined to work it through to a 
positive conclusion.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
