<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Chief Tackles Population Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The head of the World Health Organization  
spoke out for greater access to sex education for young people 
Thursday, addressing a special U.N. session on population. 
</P>
<P>
	Gro Harlem Brundtland, the former prime minister of Norway,  
broke a deadlock at the U.N. Population Conference in Cairo 1994 
with an impassioned keynote speech calling for family planning and 
reproductive health programs for women. 
</P>
<P>
	She was equally outspoken at the special session to decide on  
new proposals to implement the Cairo plan, taking on one of the two 
issues that have stalled agreement on a final document. 
</P>
<P>
	``Young people especially, as they embark upon their sexual and  
reproductive lives, must be able to protect themselves from 
disease, abuse and exploitation,'' she told the General Assembly. 
``They have a right to information and to services.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As the conference headed towards its close on Friday, delegates  
from 180 countries were still debating at what age young people 
should receive sex education in school and whether children have a 
right to confidentiality on sex-related problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The other issue blocking agreement is whether countries should  
be asked to review laws that punish women for having illegal 
abortions. The most vocal opposition comes from the Vatican and its 
supporters Argentina, Guatemala and Nicaragua, as well as Libya and 
Sudan. 
</P>
<P>
	Every year worldwide, Brundtland said, there are 333 million new  
cases of sexually transmitted diseases, and one in 20 adolescents 
gets one. More than half of the 5.2 million people infected 
annually with HIV are under the age of 24. 
</P>
<P>
	She said respecting young people's right to information is  
essential in reducing disease, avoiding unwanted pregnancies and 
controlling the growth of the world population, now approaching 6 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Giving young people information does not encourage  
promiscuity, rather it fosters mutual respect and shared 
responsibility,'' Brundtland said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Assistant Secretary of State Julia Taft said the United  
States endorses a strong role for families. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are urging strong involvement, however, of young people in  
programs that affect them, and in the confidentiality that 
sometimes medical services have to be provided with. We think this 
has to be with strong support of parents and the guidance of 
parents throughout the process,'' Taft said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
