<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Up 95.62 at 11,066.42 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks vaulted higher Thursday, with the Nasdaq  
composite and Standard and Poor's 500 indexes again setting 
records, as investors reveled in the new interest rate environment. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average rose 95.62 to close at  
11,066.42. The blue-chip index held steadily above 11,000 for the 
first time in weeks, and during the session, inched within 28 
points of its May 13 record close of 11,107.19. So far this week, 
the Dow has gained 513.86 points. 
</P>
<P>
	A resurgence in technology stocks boosted the Nasdaq 20.06 to  
2,706.18, topping the record it set Wednesday. The S&AMP;P 500 index 
rose 8.25 to 1,380.96, also beating its Wednesday record high. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is an extraordinary amount of enthusiasm,'' said William  
Meehan, chief market analyst for Cantor Fitzgerald. 
</P>
<P>
	Once again, investors applauded the long-expected decision by  
the Federal Reserve to raise short-term interest rates one-quarter 
percentage point. The market was especially heartened by the Fed's 
policy shift to a ``neutral'' bias on the need for future rate 
increases. 
</P>
<P>
	``Greenspan, by removing his bias to tighten, has flashed a red  
cape in front of the bull market,'' Meehan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Leading the market Thursday were semiconductor stocks such as  
Intel, up 3 3/8 to 62 7/8. Technology stocks had slumped in the weeks 
leading up to the Fed's decision, as traders moved money toward 
lower-priced stocks that looked like better bargains in case higher 
rates began crimping profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Shobin, a technical analyst with Lehman Brothers Inc.,  
said he might have expected profit-taking to set in after three 
consecutive days of steep gains. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really a sign of great strength that this market  
continues to be able to reach new levels,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	As trading began Thursday, stocks appeared to have ended their  
big run. Prices faltered in tandem with bonds, which dropped after 
the National Association of Purchasing Management reported the 
manufacturing sector expanded at a stronger-than-expected pace in 
June. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds initially plunged, as the report suggested the threats of  
inflation that first prompted the Federal Reserve to raise interest 
rates may not have evaporated. Prices ultimately recovered, ending 
only modestly lower. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond settled 
at 6.00 percent, up from 5.96 late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock investors shrugged off the bond market's concerns. ``A  
little hiccup in bond land is not likely to end the mania on Wall 
Street,'' Meehan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Drug stocks, which have languished for much of this year, were  
higher across the board. Eli Lilly led the sector, rising 3 1/4 to 74 7/8 
after Lehman Brothers added the stock to its ``10 Uncommon Values'' 
list of recommended stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Gourmet coffee company Starbucks tumbled 10 5/8 to 26 15/16 after  
surprising Wall Street with a forecast of lower than expected 
earnings for the next two quarters and for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	A number of smaller companies had wild price swings as the Frank  
Russell Co. shuffled the component stocks of its indexes, which 
include the widely-followed Russell 2000. The changes mean that 
portfolios modeled after the indexes have to be adjusted as well. 
Pitt-Des Moines, a construction subcontractor that trades on the 
American Stock Exchange, was down 28 7/8 at 33 5/8 after rising 30 points 
in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 11-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where composite volume totaled 1.02 
billion shares, compared with 1.33 billion in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 3.20 to 651.33, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index fell 2.98 to 794.95. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies fell 3.26 to 454.42. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1.89 percent to its  
highest close since September 1997. European indexes also gained 
strength from the U.S. interest-rate decision. Germany's DAX index 
gained 1.7 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 rose 2.7 percent, and 
France's CAC-40 rose 1.6 percent. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
