<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	It was mostly clear over the Midwest, while some showers fell in  
parts of the Plains this morning. Extreme heat was expected in the 
Southwestern states later today. 
</P>
<P>
	Clouds were expected to move into parts of the Midwest later  
today, while clear and dry conditions were predicted in the 
Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	A clash of warm, moist air from the Gulf of Mexico and cooler,  
drier air from the north is expected to cause numerous shower and 
thunderstorm activity from North Carolina west into the Central 
Plains. Strong to severe storms may occur, with up to 2 inches of 
rainfall, large hail and damaging winds. 
</P>
<P>
	The forecast calls for mostly clear skies and dry weather in the  
western United States, with highs into the 100s in the desert 
Southwest. Cooler, pleasant conditions are expected along the 
California coast, while some clouds and light rain may fall in the 
Rocky Mountain states. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's forecast highs: in the 80s in the Northeast; in the 80s  
and 90s in the mid-Atlantic states and the Southwest; in the 60s 
and 70s in the Pacific Northwest and the northern Plains; in the 
80s to 100s in the Southwest; and in the 70s and 80s in the central 
Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest temperature in the U.S. mainland Wednesday was 113  
in Blythe, Calif. The lowest temperature was 39 in Yellowstone, 
Wyo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
