<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cable Car Crash Kills 20 in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAINT-ETIENNE-EN-DEVOLUY, France (AP) -- A cable car gondola  
crashed hundreds of feet to the ground today near the top of a ski 
resort in the French Alps, killing all 20 people aboard. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said no tourists were riding the private cable car  
that was carrying workers to the Pic de Bure space observatory. The 
gondola fell 262 feet onto a rock-studded grass slope above 
Saint-Etienne-en-Devoluy, 400 miles southeast of Paris. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the worst cable car disaster in the country's history.  
Eight people died in a 1989 accident in the Isere region of the 
French Alps. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said it was not yet known what caused the accident  
on the lift. 
</P>
<P>
	Cable car accidents have hit other regions of the Alps in recent  
years. 
</P>
<P>
	In February 1998, 20 people were killed when a U.S. Marine jet  
cut a cable of a ski lift, sending a gondola plunging to the ground 
near Cavalese, Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	Jean-Charles Simiand, chief representative of the cable car  
union, told LCI television that the cable car was built in the 
1980s and recently passed a safety inspection. ``It was in perfect 
working order,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Those killed in the 7:30 a.m. accident were employees of the  
space observatory, which is atop the mountain at 8,887 feet, or 
construction crews, France Telecom phone company workers and 
employees of a cleaning service. 
</P>
<P>
	All 20 victims on board were French. The Pic de Bure observatory  
specializes in radio astronomy -- the use of radio technology for 
space communication. 
</P>
<P>
	Simiand said the private lift consisted of one cable car with  
room for 20 passengers and another smaller one used to transport 
equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	Stunned local residents gathered this afternoon at the town  
hall. 
</P>
<P>
	``These mountain communities have a lot of heart,'' said Marcel  
Lesbros, a lawmaker for the Hautes-Alpes region. ``We're all 
personally touched.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Interior Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement was expected to arrive  
at the site later in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	``Technical investigations should shed light on the  
circumstances that led to this catastrophe, which the region and 
the entire country are mourning,'' French President Jacques 
Chirac's office said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Yvan Chaix, director of the tourism office in  
Saint-Etienne-en-Devoluy, said: ``We know most of the victims. The 
whole region is in shock.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The accident at Saint-Etienne-en-Devoluy was the latest disaster  
to hit the French Alps, where massive avalanches killed 12 people 
and swept away 23 chalets Feb. 9 near the ski resort of Chamonix. 
</P>
<P>
	A month later, a fire that broke out on a truck in the Mont  
Blanc tunnel killed 45 people. 
  	   	
</P>
