<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel Backs Trade With China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House's trade policy committee gave its  
support Thursday to President Clinton's decision to extend normal 
relations status with China for another year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Ways and Means Committee, by a voice vote, reported  
``adversely'' to the full House a motion to override the 
president's June 3 action to give China access to low tariffs for 
another year. 
</P>
<P>
	The full House is expected to take up the issue in mid-July and  
go along with the president, but not before hearing arguments that 
China does not deserve normal trade status because of its trade, 
weapons proliferation and human rights policies. 
</P>
<P>
	Extending China's trade status, formerly called  
``most-favored-nation'' status, has been an annual issue since 
1980, but Congress has never succeeded in overturning a president's 
decision to continue normal trade. 
</P>
<P>
	The debate is expected to be even more heated this year because  
of growing anger here over allegations of Chinese espionage in U.S. 
nuclear weapons labs and illegal Chinese political contributions as 
well as China's growing trade surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Chinese are using their $60 billion annual trade surplus  
with us to modernize their armed forces, including building nuclear 
missiles aimed at the United States,'' said Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, 
R-Calif., who introduced the motion to disapprove the trade status 
extension. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rep. Phil Crane, R-Ill., chairman of the Ways and Means  
trade subcommittee, said starting a trade war now would probably 
derail negotiations that would open China's markets and make them 
eligible for entry into the World Trade Organization. ``It is not 
only in the U.S. commercial interest, but in our strategic interest 
to renew normal trade relations with China.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The committee also reported adversely a motion to disapprove of  
another June 3 presidential decision making Vietnam eligible for 
U.S. government credits for another year. 
</P>
<P>
	Crane likewise argued that continued engagement with the  
Vietnamese has borne results in increased trade and the accounting 
of missing U.S. servicemen. Vietnam won't be eligible for normal 
trade status until the two countries conclude a bilateral trade 
agreement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
