<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marines Install Jones As Commandant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Marine Corps' new top general is a veteran  
of both the jungles of Vietnam and the corridors of Congress, a 
military man who also happens to be fluent in French and trained in 
diplomacy. 
</P>
<P>
	He is Gen. James L. Jones Jr., a 32-year veteran of the Marine  
Corps who on Wednesday became its 32nd commandant. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Corps is well,'' he declared simply, indicating he  
intended no major changes of direction for a service that has fared 
well during Gen. Charles C. Krulak's four years as leader of the 
Marines. 
</P>
<P>
	In an emotional change-of-command ceremony at the historic  
Marine Barracks -- the oldest post in the Marine Corps -- Defense 
Secretary William Cohen thanked Krulak for his tenure as 
commandant. 
</P>
<P>
	``The epic life of Chuck Krulak is one of brilliance and  
courage,'' Cohen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Krulak's father is Victor H. ``Brute'' Krulak, a veteran of  
World War II and the Korean and Vietnam wars who rose to the rank 
of Marine Corps lieutenant general but never held the top Marine 
post. The younger Krulak, who served two tours in Vietnam, became 
commandant in July 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Krulak's retirement means there will be no member of his family  
in the Marines for the first time in nearly 70 years. His son, 
David, is a lieutenant in the Navy. 
</P>
<P>
	In remarks to an audience of active and retired military  
officers, members of Congress and Marine families, Krulak quoted 
his father on the importance of maintaining public confidence in 
the Marines. 
</P>
<P>
	``We flourish today ... not because of what we know we are, or  
what we know we can do, but because of what the grassroots of our 
country believes we are and believes we can do,'' Krulak said. 
</P>
<P>
	Krulak rejected the notion advanced by some critics that the  
Marines have become too isolated from American society. 
</P>
<P>
	``Although we do stand a breed apart, we have not lost touch  
with the American people,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones, 55, had been Cohen's personal military aide until  
President Clinton nominated him to be commandant. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen's friendship with Jones began in the early 1980s when  
Cohen was a senator from Maine and Jones was the Marine liaison 
officer to the Senate. When Cohen became defense secretary in 
January 1997 he made Jones -- then the Marines' deputy chief of 
staff for plans -- his senior military assistant. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones is a native of Kansas City, Mo., but spent his formative  
years in France. He returned to the United States to attend the 
Georgetown University School of Foreign Service, where he received 
a degree in diplomacy in 1966. He was commissioned a second 
lieutenant in the Marines in January 1967. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1991, as commanding officer of the 24th Marine Expeditionary  
Unit, Jones helped carry out Operation Provide Comfort, the 
U.S.-led humanitarian mission to protect and resettle Kurdish 
refugees in northern Iraq and Turkey after the Persian Gulf War. 
</P>
<P>
	Among his personal decorations: the Silver Star Medal and a  
Bronze Star Medal with combat ``V'' for valor. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990701.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 15:04:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU Opposed to Ocalan Death Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Turkey's prime minister on Thursday  
brushed aside European criticisms of a death sentence against 
Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan, saying efforts to influence 
the courts could produce a backlash. 
</P>
<P>
	The European Union's 15 member nations, all of which have  
abolished the death penalty, have warned that hanging the rebel 
leader would hurt Turkey's bid to join EU. 
</P>
<P>
	``The European Union has not even accepted us as a member,''  
said Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit. ``We are not in the position to 
take any political decision to please the European Union.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan was sentenced to death Tuesday, convicted of treason for  
leading a Kurdish rebellion. Death penalties in Turkey are 
automatically appealed. If the verdict is upheld, parliament and 
President Suleyman Demirel also must approve it. Turkey has not 
executed anyone since 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecevit warned that ``those who try to influence the legal  
proceedings in Turkey will meet with opposition from Turkish public 
opinion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Turkey's ties with the EU were strained after the group told  
Ankara in 1997 that it must improve its human rights record and 
resolve its disputes with Greece, an EU member, before joining. 
Turkey responded by saying it would not discuss its internal 
affairs, including human rights, with the EU. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Thursday, Ecevit said his government was pressing for a  
law aimed at encouraging Kurdish rebels to come down from their 
mountain hideouts and surrender their weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	The so-called ``repentance law,'' would grant lenient punishment  
to rebels who surrender and give information to security forces. 
</P>
<P>
	But hours later, Ecevit withdrew the draft law from parliament  
after his far-right coalition partners said they would not support 
it, the Anatolia news agency reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Sevket Bulent Yahnici, deputy leader of the Nationalist Movement  
Party, said such a law would have little public support. 
</P>
<P>
	The far-right party has opposed any concessions to the rebels in  
the past. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecevit said the proposed law would help defeat Ocalan's  
Kurdistan Workers Party, or PKK, which has been waging a 15-year 
war for autonomy in Turkey's southeast. Ocalan is not expected to 
benefit from such a law. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for the PKK in Brussels refused to comment on the  
proposal until the full details were known. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkish security forces have been successful in pushing the  
rebels from urban areas into the rugged mountains of the southeast, 
but fighting has continued. The rebels have threatened to increase 
attacks if Ocalan is hanged. 
</P>
<P>
	Although there is widespread pressure to hang Ocalan, a public  
debate over the death sentence intensified Thursday with many 
analysts arguing that hanging the guerrilla leader would harm 
Turkey. 
</P>
<P>
	Other analysts urged the government to grant cultural rights to  
the Kurds, a call the PKK repeatedly has made. 
</P>
<P>
	``The state should ... meet the language, broadcasting and  
education demands of its citizens of Kurdish origin,'' wrote 
commentator Tuncay Ozkan for the newspaper Radikal. ``It is not 
Abdullah Ocalan, it is the issues discussed behind his name that 
are important.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Broadcasting or teaching in Kurdish is illegal. Speaking the  
language was only legalized in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Police on Wednesday arrested 10 Kurdish militants who were  
allegedly preparing to stage bomb attacks to protest Ocalan's 
conviction, the Anatolia news agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency said 40 bombs were seized in operations in slum areas  
of Istanbul where Kurds live. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
