<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Maloofs Gain Control of NBA's Kings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- The Maloof family officially gained a  
controlling interest of the Sacramento Kings and Arco Arena from 
Jim Thomas on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The NBA Board of Governors approved the ownership change on May  
7 and it went into effect Thursday. The Albuquerque family, headed 
by brothers Joe and Gavin Maloof, already has been exerting control 
over the franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very exciting day for the Maloof family,'' Joe  
Maloof, president of the Maloof Companies, said during a signing 
ceremony in Los Angeles. ``We are proud to rejoin the NBA family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Maloof family, which owned the Houston Rockets from 1979 to  
1982, purchased a one-quarter interest in the Kings last year for 
$37.5 million, with an option to purchase the rest of Thomas' 53 
percent interest within five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas is a Los Angeles-based developer who purchased the team  
in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	The Maloof family owns the Fiesta Casino Hotel in North Las  
Vegas, Nev. Their other holdings include a beer distributorship in 
Albuquerque and several banks, a transportation company and other 
businesses operating in New Mexico, Colorado and Nevada. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kings had their first winning season this year since Thomas  
bought the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we bought the team we weren't looking for a winner, but  
looking to help make a winner. We're used to being the underdog, 
but we are also used to coming out on top,'' Joe Maloof said. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas restructured the team's finances two years ago by  
obtaining a $70 million loan from the city, secured by the 
franchise and the arena. 
</P>
<P>
	The WNBA's Sacramento Monarchs and the Sacramento Knights indoor  
soccer team are included in the ownership transfer to the Maloof 
family. 
</P>
<P>
	``Joe and Gavin Maloof are two young, energetic and hard-working  
men and will continue to transform the Sacramento Kings into a 
successful, nationally admired franchise,'' Sacramento Mayor Joe 
Serna said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
