<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton's Trips Under Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The Republican National Committee chairman  
criticized Hillary Rodham Clinton today for using government 
aircraft and resources for campaign-style visits to the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, expected to seek the Senate seat being vacated  
next year by retiring Democratic Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, has 
made 12 trips to New York in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	The cost to taxpayers is estimated at more than $220,000, said  
the top Republican, Jim Nicholson. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hillary's flying military jets, but at $20,000 per trip, it's  
the taxpayers who are being taken for a ride,'' Nicholson said in a 
statement distributed by aides as he began a four-stop trip across 
traditionally Republican upstate New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Marsha Berry, a spokesman for the first lady, has said that, on  
the advice of the Secret Service, Mrs. Clinton will continue to fly 
military jets to New York for as long as she is first lady. Berry 
said the government would be reimbursed for Mrs. Clinton's own 
political travel. 
</P>
<P>
	Other campaign committees have paid for some of Mrs. Clinton's  
costs when she participates in fund-raising events for them. But 
taxpayers have covered all other expenses, including Secret Service 
protection, when she travels. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton is expected to file papers next week with the  
Federal Election Commission creating an exploratory committee that 
will allow her to raise and spend money for campaign-related 
purposes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
