<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Air Canada Mediators Appointed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Canada has appointed two mediators to try to  
resolve an Air Canada labor dispute that could lead to a strike 
this month by the 5,100 flight attendants of Canada's largest 
airline. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline and the attendants' union have until July 7 before  
they are in a legal position for a strike or lockout. Each side 
says it is willing to resume negotiations prior to the deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Canada says it will ground its planes in the event of a  
strike and customers will need to seek other travel arrangements. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the Labor Ministry said it would not appoint a  
conciliation board to impose a settlement, but it did appoint two 
mediators to assist if negotiations resumed. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Canada's most recent strike was in September 1998, when its  
2,100 pilots walked out for 13 days. 
</P>
<P>
	The attendants' latest proposal, which the airline rejected June  
20, sought a pension increase of more than $3,000 a year. The 
airline said last week it refuses to consider the union's proposal 
unless pensions are taken off the table. 
</P>
<P>
	The two sides have agreed on wage increases totaling 12.5  
percent over a three-year contract. The company has also offered a 
lump sum payment which the union says falls far short of the 
requested pension improvements. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
