<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Daewoo Group Dismisses 33 Executives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Daewoo group dismissed 33 of its 50  
subsidiary presidents as part of an effort to speed up 
restructuring at the conglomerate, company officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The move came one day after all of the 50 presidents tendered  
resignation letters and vowed to work without getting paid until 
the business group's planned restructuring is completed. 
</P>
<P>
	The remaining 17 presidents will work without salary as  
promised, Daewoo officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim Tae-gu, who has been in charge of corporate restructuring,  
became new president of Daewoo Motor. Former president for the 
carmaker, Kang Byong-ho, was appointed president of Daewoo Telecom. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, Daewoo announced plans to sell its shipbuilding and  
other businesses to improve its financial position. 
</P>
<P>
	Daewoo plans to reduce the number of its subsidiaries to eight  
from 34 in the automobile, trading and finance sectors and reduce 
its debt-to-equity ratio sharply by October. 
</P>
<P>
	At the end of 1998, Daewoo had $63 billion in total assets and  
$50 billion in debt. 
</P>
<P>
	In early June, Daewoo agreed to sell the Hilton Hotel in Seoul  
to General Mediterranean Holding Co., an investment firm based in 
Luxembourg, for $215 million, its first sale of a major asset. 
</P>
<P>
	President Kim Dae-jung has been urging more corporate  
restructuring at the nation's top five conglomerates -- Hyundai, 
Daewoo Samsung, LG and SK -- to improve efficiency and boost foreign 
investors' confidence. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korea was forced to accept a $58 billion bailout fund from  
the International Monetary Fund in late 1997 to save its faltering 
economy. Structural reforms were a key condition of the rescue 
package. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
