<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CDC Warns of Alaskan Flu Outbreak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Federal health officials are urging older  
tourists to consult a doctor before traveling this summer to Alaska 
and the Yukon, where a flu outbreak has sickened hundreds of 
tourists for the second straight year. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of 428 cases have been reported among tourists on seven  
cruises since May 22, the Centers for Disease Control and 
Prevention reported Thursday. That's about 4 percent of 10,110 
passengers got sick. 
</P>
<P>
	Those most vulnerable -- people over age 65 or with chronic  
respiratory and heart problems -- should get advice from a doctor 
before traveling to the region, the CDC said. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency issued a similar warning for the area last August,  
after flu had sickened nearly 2,000 tourists and killed two. 
</P>
<P>
	Flu spreads easily on cruise ships because tourists travel in  
close quarters. A constant influx of new tour groups allows the 
bugs to circulate over extended periods. 
</P>
<P>
	Supplies of flu vaccine are low during summer, making outbreaks  
more worrisome. But doctors can prescribe drugs that blunt the 
effects. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
