<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson: 31 Ks, 0-2 Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Randy Johnson has clammed up as tight as the  
Arizona Diamondbacks offense. 
</P>
<P>
	The left-hander kept his thoughts to himself Thursday, a day  
after he pitched another dominating game and wound up with another 
tortuous loss. Johnson struck out 17 in a 2-0 loss to the 
Cincinnati Reds that was painfully familiar. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson's line for his last two starts: 31 strikeouts, two  
complete games, no wins, no comment. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have anything to say,'' Johnson said before Thursday's  
game. 
</P>
<P>
	His problem is that he isn't getting any help from his offense.  
</P>
<P>
	In his start last Friday, Johnson struck out 14 Cardinals and  
allowed only one run but wound up with a 1-0 loss. St. Louis rookie 
Jose Jimenez threw a no-hitter to upstage him. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the Reds' turn on Wednesday, when Ron Villone and Scott  
Williamson held the Diamondbacks to one hit in a 2-0 win. 
Afterward, Johnson made himself scarce. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked how Johnson was taking it, manager Buck Showalter said,  
``I would think not very well. In fact, I know he isn't.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When reporters finished with Showalter, public relations  
director Mike Swanson told them, ``He isn't taking it so well that 
he's got nothing to say.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The numbers say it all.  
</P>
<P>
	In his last two starts, Johnson has thrown two complete games,  
struck out 31 and allowed only three runs on 12 hits and two walks. 
Meanwhile, the Diamondbacks have managed one hit. 
</P>
<P>
	The 17 strikeouts on Wednesday night were a season high, a  
Diamondbacks record and the fourth 17-strikeout game of his career. 
The last time he struck out 17 was Aug. 8, 1997 against the Chicago 
White Sox. 
</P>
<P>
	His two-game total of 31 strikeouts is two shy of Kerry Wood's  
National League record set last year. He needs 12 strikeouts in his 
next start Monday to tie the NL mark for three consecutive games. 
Dwight Gooden fanned 43 in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	All that domination has gotten him is two losses. Although the  
Diamondbacks have one of the top offenses in the NL, it has gone 
flat since the no-hitter. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last five games, Arizona hit only .138 and scored eight  
runs. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can never figure it out,'' outfielder Bernard Gilkey said.  
``That's what makes it so great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson probably would choose another adjective -- if he were  
inclined to talk. 
</P>
<P>
	The only bright moment in Johnson's latest loss came when he  
struck out Barry Larkin during a five-strikeout spree in the middle 
innings. Larkin started swinging at what he thought was a fastball, 
then wound up contorted when it turned out to be a down-and-in 
slider. 
</P>
<P>
	It was one of the worst swings of Larkin's career. Both of them  
laughed about it on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was coming in about a billion mph, then it broke at the  
last second,'' Larkin said. ``I tried to adjust my swing. I just 
couldn't believe it. That's how good his stuff was.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Good, but not good enough.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of hard. It's rare that you ever see that,'' Gilkey  
said of Johnson's two-game heartbreak. ``He's been pitching great 
for us. It's unfortunate we haven't been able to pick up a couple 
of runs for him. Those are the breaks, I guess. I feel bad for 
him.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
