<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nemechek Captures Daytona Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- First, owner Felix Sabates switched  
crew chiefs. In the back of his mind, Joe Nemechek must have 
wondered if Sabates was thinking about making a change in drivers 
as well. 
</P>
<P>
	Nemechek got a boost to open the second half of an otherwise  
dreary season Thursday, winning the pole position for the Pepsi 
400. 
</P>
<P>
	With a speed of 194.860 mph on Daytona International Speedway's  
2.5-mile trioval, Nemechek earned his first pole in more than two 
years. It confirmed the wisdom of Sabates' decision to reassign 
Tony Glover to Nemechek's team last month. 
</P>
<P>
	The two were together in 1997, when Nemechek earned the nickname  
``Front Row Joe'' after taking a pair of poles and qualifying 
second three times. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has been through so much here and knows how to call a  
race,'' Nemechek said of Glover. ``We communicate real well. He can 
say something and I know what he says. I can say a different word 
back to him and he knows how far the car is off. We've been able to 
capitalize on that in the past, and hopefully we will Saturday 
night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It would be a startling turnaround for Nemechek, who is in 37th  
place in the points standings and has just one top 10 finish this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Starting outside of Nemechek will be Ricky Rudd, an owner-driver  
who qualified at 194.574 mph just hours after learning his 
nine-year sponsorship deal with Tide will be terminated after this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no way to do it but go out, get mad about it, fight  
harder and try harder,'' Rudd said. ``I'm a firm believer that if 
you work hard, something will work out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the third position will be Mark Martin, who qualified at  
194.376 mph. Martin is seeking his first restrictor-plate victory 
since 1997 at Talladega, when his Ford averaged 188.354 mph in an 
accident-free race on the circuit's fastest track. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really feel like we've got the best shot at a race at  
Daytona that we've ever had,'' said Martin, who has never won a 
main event at the track. ``We've got great horsepower. This is the 
most I've had on any restrictor plate that I can ever remember.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Next to Martin will be Chad Little (193.690 mph), with Rusty  
Wallace and Tony Stewart in the third row. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Gordon, who won the pole and the Daytona 500 in February,  
qualified 11th. Dale Earnhardt was 10th and series points leader 
Dale Jarrett was 12th. 
</P>
<P>
	Nemechek has made 170 Winston Cup starts without a victory. Like  
any driver, he would like to break that string at NASCAR's most 
famous track. Of course, he knows that qualifying and the actual 
race are always different at Daytona, where carburetor restrictor 
plates are set in place to reduce speeds. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a whole different setup,'' Nemechek said. ``Qualifying is  
made for two laps. You can just barely hang onto it. Race mode, 
you've got to hang on and hold that throttle open all day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 25 fastest qualifiers locked up starting spots in the 43-car  
field, with the rest of the lineup to be set tonight in the final 
round of time trials. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the drivers who failed to make the top 25 and will have to  
either try again tonight or stand on their first-day laps were 
Terry Labonte, who was 39th, and Steve Park, last among the 44 who 
made a qualifying attempt. 
</P>
<P>
	Kenny Wallace also failed to qualify. He had to use an untested  
car after getting into an accident in practice. Wallace was able to 
drive in qualifying, but the car did not survive the accident. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
