<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer: Financier Not Surrendering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- Fugitive financier Martin R. Frankel,  
accused of stealing at least $200 million from a bevy of insurance 
companies, was still on the loose Thursday and is not considering 
turning himself in, his lawyer said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense lawyer Hugh Keefe confirmed that he had spoken to  
Frankel in the past three weeks, but said ``none of those 
conversations had anything to do with surrender,'' Keefe said. 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel is wanted on federal wire fraud and money laundering  
charges. He is believed to be somewhere in Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	The list of countries that have extradition treaties with the  
United States is growing all the time, resulting in fewer places 
for Frankel to hide. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States currently has 115 extradition treaties in  
place, according to the Justice Department. Notable exceptions 
include Russia and China, spokesman John Russell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Professor Daniel Partan of the Boston University Law School said  
it is much more difficult to escape U.S. prosecution today than it 
was 10 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I watch treaty developments and I know the Department of  
Justice is interested in drying up any safe havens,'' Partan said. 
</P>
<P>
	But extradition treaties vary from country to country, and  
Frankel is believed to have tremendous resources at his disposal. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the moment, the chances of finding him and extracting him  
are not that good,'' Partan said. ``I would suspect that with his 
skills at financial affairs he has a pretty good shot at finding a 
haven. He has probably thought fairly carefully and competently 
about how to move his money around the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, when Frankel disappeared from his Greenwich mansion in  
early May, among the items left behind were a handwritten list of 
tasks, including the notation, ``Get $ to Israel get it back in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Frankel may be able to claim Israeli citizenship because he is  
of Jewish heritage. A similar claim was recently employed 
successfully by Samuel Sheinbein, a Maryland teen-ager accused of 
murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheinbein will not be extradited, but faces trial on the murder  
charge in Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	Many treaties give countries the option not to send their  
citizens back to the United States for trial, said Professor Ruth 
Wedgwood of the Yale University of School of Law. 
</P>
<P>
	``These treaties are handcrafted according to the political  
sensibilities of the particular country,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Insurance company regulators say Frankel's unlicensed brokerage,  
Liberty National Securities Inc., siphoned at least $215 million 
from small insurance firms in Mississippi, Oklahoma, Tennessee, 
Missouri and Arkansas. In the end, the losses could prove to be 
much higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Also missing is as much as $1.98 billion from the St. Francis of  
Assisi Foundation, which investigators say is a bogus Roman 
Catholic charity Frankel established last August. 
</P>
<P>
	The foundation's assets were kept in the British Virgin Islands,  
investigators said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
