<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Agencies Announce Egg-Safety Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration on Thursday  
proposed new warning labels for egg cartons and took steps to 
combat salmonella contamination. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposed safe handling instructions warn that ``eggs may  
contain harmful bacteria known to cause serious illness, especially 
in children, the elderly, and persons with weakened immune 
systems.'' It would advise consumers to keep eggs refrigerated, 
cook egg yolks until firm and thoroughly cook any food containing 
eggs. 
</P>
<P>
	The joint announcement by the Food and Drug Administration and  
the Agriculture Department, which together have responsibility for 
preventing food-bourne illnesses, came as a report criticizing 
their efforts was presented at a congressional hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	The report by the General Accounting Office found that too many  
federal agencies have done too little, too slowly to protect 
Americans from salmonella-contaminated eggs. It concluded that new 
national standards and better coordination among the several 
agencies with jurisdiction over the issue is needed. 
</P>
<P>
	Incidence of the digestive illness that can be caused by eating  
raw or undercooked eggs -- found in such favorites as runny fried 
eggs, thick-cut French toast, Caesar salad and unbaked cookie dough 
-- decreased by 44 percent since 1996 in selected areas. 
</P>
<P>
	But egg-bourne salmonella infections remain a public health  
concern. In 1997, the disease may have sickened as many as 300,000 
and caused 115 deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the new labels, the FDA and USDA proposed  
expanding a federal requirement that eggs and egg products be kept 
refrigerated at 45 degrees or below. 
</P>
<P>
	Such a requirement covering eggs from the time they are packed  
and shipped until they reach retail locations is set to take effect 
in August -- eight years after Congress mandated it. On Thursday, 
the FDA said it is moving to include eggs on store shelves, in 
restaurants and at nursing homes and schools as well. 
</P>
<P>
	The agencies also promised that the President's Council on Food  
Safety would complete by Nov. 1 a government-wide plan to further 
increase egg safety. 
</P>
<P>
	The new proposed regulations are being published in the Federal  
Register and will be open to comment for the next 75 days. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
