<DOCNO> APW19990701.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 13:30:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley To Get Kerrey's Endorsement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Bob Kerrey of Nebraska will formally  
endorse Bill Bradley's bid for the Democratic presidential 
nomination, the second senator to do so, Bradley aides said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Kerrey will issue his endorsement at a pancake breakfast Monday  
morning in Omaha, and the two will then travel to suburban Des 
Moines to repeat the announcement in the state where precinct 
caucuses launch the presidential nominating season. 
</P>
<P>
	That event -- at a private home -- will draw Democratic activists  
friendly to the campaigns both of Kerrey and Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	In the announcement, Kerrey will make it clear he is picking  
Bradley over Vice President Al Gore, said a Bradley aide who spoke 
on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore has the backing of much of the Democratic Party's  
establishment, including the leaders in both the House and Senate. 
Minnesota Sen. Paul Wellstone is the only other senator who has 
endorsed Bradley, who served for 18 years as a senator from New 
Jersey before stepping down. 
</P>
<P>
	In Kerrey, Bradley gets the backing of a decorated war hero who  
won the Medal of Honor for valor in Vietnam, and a former candidate 
for the Democratic nomination. There had been speculation he would 
run again this election cycle. 
</P>
<P>
	The endorsement does not come as a great surprise. There have  
been tensions between Kerrey and the Clinton administration. In 
addition, when announcing he had decided not to make the race, one 
of the reasons Kerrey cited was Bradley's presence in the field 
giving Democrats a choice of candidates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
