<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Outside Counsel in Shuster Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House ethics committee disclosed Wednesday  
that it will not name an outside counsel to handle its 
investigation of the House Transportation Committee chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	In rejecting a private group's request, committee leaders said  
such an appointment ``is neither necessary nor appropriate.'' No 
reason was given, but outside counsel appointments are rare. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa., is under investigation for his ties  
with Ann Eppard, a transportation lobbyist who was the lawmaker's 
congressional chief of staff for 22 years and remains his chief 
campaign fund-raiser. 
</P>
<P>
	The ethics committee late last year widened the inquiry to  
include Shuster's campaign operations over the past six years. The 
campaign has spent millions of dollars on travel, meals and other 
expenses even though he had no formidable opponent during that 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	Shuster has denied any wrongdoing.  
</P>
<P>
	The rejection letter came from the ethics committee chairman,  
Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, and the panel's ranking Democrat, Howard 
Berman of California. The letter was dated last Thursday and was 
received Wednesday by Ralph Nader's Congressional Accountability 
Project. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nader group's director, Gary Ruskin, said an outside counsel  
was necessary because of inherent conflicts of interest between 
Shuster and members of the ethics committee. Ruskin, who filed the 
complaint in September 1996, said the lack of an outside counsel 
leads to delays. 
</P>
<P>
	Shuster has considerable say over funding for highway and  
aviation projects across the country. Last year, he helped steer 
into law a $203 billion transportation measure containing several 
projects that benefit Ms. Eppard's clients. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
