<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> France's BNP Raises Bank Bids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- French bank Banque Nationale de Paris, locked in a  
takeover battle for rivals Societe Generale and Paribas, said 
Thursday it has increased its offer by 5 percent to $38.85 billion 
in cash and stock. 
</P>
<P>
	But BNP's hopes of a successful resolution to the four-month  
saga looked dashed after Paribas branded the new offer ``stingy'' 
and ``unambitious.'' 
</P>
<P>
	BNP launched its initial $37 billion hostile takeover bid for  
Societe Generale and Paribas in March. But the two banks, 
themselves in the midst of merging since February, have been 
fighting the offer. 
</P>
<P>
	The chairmen of the three banks met for talks last week with the  
governor of the Bank of France, Jean-Claude Trichet, to try and 
break the impasse. But no agreement had been reached when the 
discussions broke down late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on BNP's closing price Wednesday, the sweetened offer  
gives a 6.6 percent premium over Societe Generale's closing stock 
price on Wednesday and a 24.9 percent premium over its share price 
when BNP made its initial offer. 
</P>
<P>
	BNP's new offer to Paribas shareholders is 14.8 percent higher  
than Paribas's closing price on Wednesday and is 45.2 percent 
higher than Paribas' share price when the initial BNP offer was 
made in March. 
</P>
<P>
	BNP said it hoped the two banks' shareholders would approve its  
offer. 
</P>
<P>
	If the three banks merge under the new offer, ownership would  
include 32.3 percent for BNP shareholders, 32.7 percent for Societe 
Generale holders and 35 percent for Paribas. 
</P>
<P>
	A merger would also create the world's first $1 trillion bank in  
terms of assets. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
