<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reggie Jackson May Buy Into A's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Hall of Fame slugger Reggie Jackson, who  
helped the Oakland Athletics win three World Series championships, 
has joined the group trying to buy the team just a few days after 
Joe Morgan said he was pulling out. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson, known as ``Mr. October'' for his stirring World Series  
performances, played for the A's for nine years and was the 
American League's Most Valuable Player in 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	Andy Dolich, the former A's marketing director who is heading  
the group, said Wednesday that Jackson and six other investors have 
been added. Bob Piccinini, the owner of Modesto-based Save Mart 
Supermarkets, is the group's main financial backer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Baseball has been and will always be a part of me,'' said  
Jackson, who lives near Carmel. ``Partnering with this group at 
this time represents a unique opportunity for me to use both my 
business and baseball skills. I am committed to the group's 
philosophy of local ownership.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``On a daily operating level, Reggie will work with me and Bob  
on the baseball and business side,'' Dolich said. ``Reggie will 
continue with his other business ventures, but he will devote a 
significant amount of time to the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson currently is director of new business alliances for  
Viking Components, which makes computer memory. He is also a 
principal of Ulico Insurance Group of Washington, D.C., and from 
1993 until last year served as a special adviser to the New York 
Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan said he dropped out because he didn't want to give up his  
broadcast positions with ESPN and NBC, and was unable to work out 
an acceptable deal with the group. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is still an opportunity for us and Joe to work  
together,'' Dolich said. 
</P>
<P>
	One new investor is the Mugar family of Boston, headed by  
prominent businessman and philanthropist David G. Mugar. Dolich 
said Mugar's sons Jonathan and Peter will handle the family's 
involvement. 
</P>
<P>
	Dolich's group has offered $122.4 million to owners Steve Schott  
and Ken Hofmann. The price was worked out in a settlement with the 
city of Oakland and Alameda County. The sale must close by Sept. 21 
or Schott and Hofmann retain ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	Other new investors announced were restaurateur Dan Costa of  
Modesto; Jerry Kline, president and chief executive of Innovative 
Interfaces, Inc. of Emeryville; attorney Louis J. Giraudo; attorney 
Steven Kazan; and Kazan's partner David McClain. Others involved 
include The Oakland Tribune; Wind River Systems chairman Jerry 
Fiddler; Men's Wearhouse chief George Zimmer; advertising executive 
Jeff Goodby; and attorney Guy Saperstein. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale may be voted on by baseball owners at a Sept. 18  
meeting. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
