<DOCNO> APW19990701.0301 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 10:10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Pushes Everglades Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- An ambitious $7.8 billion, long-range rescue  
of the Florida Everglades was sent to Congress today and Vice 
President Al Gore called for ``a bipartisan effort ... to save this 
national treasure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the plan has been public for months. But now Congress  
must come up with the money -- an estimated $200 million a year for 
two decades -- to keep the onetime ``River of Grass'' that stretches 
across South Florida from being further devastated and destroyed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Everglades have been abused. We didn't see them for what  
they were worth,'' Gore during a ceremony in the U.S. Capitol. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida's congressional delegation -- both Republicans and  
Democrats -- have vowed to fight for the restoration plan, but Sen. 
Connie Mack, R-Fla., acknowledged ``there will be difficulties 
ahead'' in getting the Congress to approve the plan and provide a 
steady stream of funding. 
</P>
<P>
	The Everglades restoration has been marked by an undercurrent of  
presidential campaign politics. Gore, a longtime champion of 
Everglades restoration, made the unusual trek to Capitol Hill to 
mark the 4000-page recovery plan's formal presentation to Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	And an aide to Florida Gov. Jeb Bush, brother of GOP  
presidential derby front-runner George W. Bush, made clear 
Wednesday that the governor is going to push for the plan just as 
hard as Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know of no opposition. It would be politically  
unthinkable,'' said J. Allison Defoor, the governor's Everglades 
policy coordinator. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore called the plan ``the most critical step yet to restore the  
Everglades, one of America's true natural treasures.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No one had to say Florida is a key state in the presidential  
race in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government and state will evenly divide the cost of  
the 20-year restoration of one of America's most treasured, but 
severely threatened, environmental landmarks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am very concerned about the financing,'' Sen. Bob Graham,  
D-Fla., said, adding that a permanent federal funding stream of 
$150 million to $200 million a year will be needed. Comparing it to 
heart surgery, Graham, added ``We're going to go in with a knife. 
... Once you start that process, you can't stop in the middle of 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore said Wednesday he was confident Congress ``will join us in  
this historic effort'' and come up with the money. 
</P>
<P>
	``After three years of work, we now have a final plan that is  
terrific for the environment, terrific for communities, terrific 
for business, and saves a world and national treasure,'' Gore said. 
``I think the strength of that consensus will guarantee the money 
we need.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Graham said that while there is no need to panic, there is  
concern that House and Senate appropriations committees have not 
come up with as much money as the administration has projected for 
the Everglades this upcoming fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	Funding approved by the Senate panel falls 40 percent short of  
the $150 million requested for the Interior Department and also 
less than what had been sought by the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, 
which is in charge of the restoration. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest obstacle for restoration of the Everglades is  
getting a full commitment from Congress,'' said Ron Tipton of the 
World Wildlife Fund. The state of Florida also has not yet 
pinpointed how it will pay for the historic recovery program, 
although state officials said financing sources will be found. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida already has spent $2.3 billion since 1983, and the  
federal government another $1.3 billion, to try to revitalize the 
``River of Grass'' that spans more than 100 miles from north of 
Lake Okeechobee to Florida Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	The restoration plan calls for overhauling the plumbing of the  
Everglades by eliminating some 240 miles of levies and canals -- 
part of a 1,700-mile system built 50 years ago to artificially 
channel the water that once flowed naturally in sheets southward. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan calls for 60 specific projects, including construction  
of aboveground reservoirs, underground aquifers and development of 
new wetlands. The aim is to restore the natural flow of water and 
to collect water that now rushes into the ocean for nobody's 
benefit. 
</P>
<P>
	About 80 percent of the additional water would be used to  
revitalize the health of the Everglades ecosystem, which is home to 
1,500 varieties of plants and wildlife from wading birds to 
alligators, including at least 68 threatened or endangered species. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of the fresh water would go to cities and farms. The  
administration is asking Congress to approve the first round of 
projects this year at a cost of $1.2 billion over six years. The 
entire program is projected to be completed by 2020. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
