<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pub Owner Guilty in Larry Bird Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- The former owner of a downtown pub has been  
convicted of battery for evicting a woman who spoke with Indiana 
Pacers coach Larry Bird as he was drinking with an assistant coach. 
</P>
<P>
	In convicting Gordon Etchison, Marion Superior Court Judge Evan  
Goodman on Wednesday said there was overwhelming evidence Etchison 
was ``belligerent with her in an irrational manner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kay Williams, 43, was speaking with Bird at the Legal Beagle on  
Feb. 4, when the incident occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Williams and two witnesses testified that Etchison grabbed her  
and tried to push her away from the table where Bird was sitting. 
Etchison said he believed Williams was bothering Bird. 
</P>
<P>
	In his videotaped testimony, Bird reiterated his statement to  
police that Williams was not bothering him when she came to his 
table. He said Etchison came up to her and told her it was time to 
go. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, 'She's fine.' I could tell she was about done,'' Bird  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bird said he did not see Etchison physically grab Williams, who  
was treated at Methodist Hospital for bruises and soreness. 
</P>
<P>
	Etchison faces a maximum sentence of a year in jail and a fine  
of $5,000. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
