<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Mulls Asbestos Litigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- People who claim injury as a result of  
asbestos exposure would have to seek compensation in an 
administrative procedure instead of the courts under a plan 
lawmakers are considering. 
</P>
<P>
	During a House Judiciary Committee hearing Thursday, supporters  
praised the legislation as badly needed relief for a legal system 
now choked by hundreds of thousands of slow-moving asbestos-related 
lawsuits, many of filed by people who probably will never become 
sick. 
</P>
<P>
	``The courts of this land simply are not equipped to handle the  
more than 200,000 asbestos-related cases currently in the system 
and the 8,000 new filings thrust upon the courts on the last month 
alone,'' said Conrad Mallet, a former chief justice of the Michigan 
Supreme Court and president of a business group lobbying for the 
idea. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only losers are a few dozen powerful lawyers,'' said  
Christopher Edley Jr., a Harvard Law School professor. ``This bill 
benefits almost everyone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents called it an undeserved bailout of the asbestos  
industry that would deny compensation to people battling cancer and 
other disabling diseases. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not fair,'' said Richard Middleton, president-elect of  
the Association of Trial Lawyers of America. ``It is not fast, it 
is not efficient and it is not right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Supreme Court decision last week threw out a proposed $1.5  
billion asbestos agreement. The ruling urged Congress to create a 
better way to settle asbestos claims, saying current rules are not 
flexible enough to accommodate cases involving multiple claims. 
</P>
<P>
	The House bill would create a quasi-governmental agency, the  
Asbestos Resolution Corporation, to resolve asbestos injury claims. 
Asbestos companies would pay all the costs of the non-judicial 
administrative process, supporters said. No taxpayer dollars would 
be used. 
</P>
<P>
	For an applicant considered ill or injured and receiving a  
``certificate of medical eligibility,'' the case would go to 
mediation if a settlement with the potentially liable companies is 
not reached in 60 days. 
</P>
<P>
	If mediation fails, the claimant could sue or try arbitration.  
</P>
<P>
	The president would nominate and the Senate confirm the  
corporation's seven-member board of directors. A medical advisory 
board would provide expert advice. 
</P>
<P>
	Payments would go only to claimants who can show they are sick  
or injured as a result of exposure to asbestos using criteria 
spelled out in the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Punitive damages would be prohibited ``so as to ensure that  
funds would be available to compensate people who may in the future 
become impaired by asbestos-related diseases,'' said a Judiciary 
Committee statement explaining the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	Claimants could collect money for nonmalignant disease, such as  
asbestosis -- scarring of the lungs -- without losing their right to 
future compensation if they develop cancer later, supporters said. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal would cap attorneys fees and expenses at 25  
percent. Supporters of the plan said that as much as two-thirds of 
some asbestos awards today go to lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 1283.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
