<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.-U.K. Aviation Talks Off Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Formal talks between the United States and the  
United Kingdom about a new aviation agreement were supposed to 
resume next week, but instead have been postponed indefinitely. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials expressed disappointment Thursday about the  
decision announced by the British government in London. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been nine months since we last had formal talks with the  
British government ... and the time frame for accomplishing such an 
agreement is growing increasingly short,'' said Transportation 
Department spokesman Bill Schulz. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very clear from what we've seen from the other side is  
there's an inability to develop a position,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The hang-up reportedly stems from a dispute between British  
Airways and officials in the British Office of Fair Trading, as 
well as the country's transport offices. Both entities want the 
airline to surrender takeoff and landing slots at London's popular 
Heathrow Airport, but the airline apparently is balking at the 
number. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials have insisted on more slots since British Airways  
proposed an alliance with American Airlines in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the current aviation treaty, known as Bermuda II, only two  
U.S. carriers -- American and United Airlines -- are allowed to fly 
into Heathrow. Business travelers in particular like the airport 
because it offers the most connections to international points. 
</P>
<P>
	Under an ``open skies'' deal, an unlimited number of carriers  
could serve any U.S. or British airport. U.S. officials believe 
added access to Heathrow would drive down airfares and give 
customers more flight selections. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiations collapsed last fall after only three days of  
meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	In April, top transportation officials from both countries said  
preliminary talks would resume, with an eye toward returning to 
formal negotiations. Recently, both governments announced the 
formal talks would take place next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The British government said Wednesday in a statement: ``We are  
still refining our negotiating position in talks with the airlines. 
We've postponed our talks and no alternative date has been set.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
