<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 10:41:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Open Lower; Dow Down 18.04 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened lower today as investors pondered  
their course in the new interest rate environment. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 18.04 at 10,952.76. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were posting narrower losses. The  
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 4.69 to 1,367.97, and the 
Nasdaq composite index was down 5.58 to 2,680.54. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices responded most dramatically today to the Federal  
Reserve's decision to raise interest rates one-quarter percentage 
point. After a rally Wednesday afternoon, bond prices sank today, 
pushing the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond to 6.04 percent, up 
from 5.96 late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	That prevented stock prices from building on their own Wednesday  
rally. The Fed's decision and its accompanying policy shift to a 
``neutral'' bias on the need for future rate increases vaulted the 
Dow 155.45 higher to close at 10,970.80. The S&AMP;P 500 and the Nasdaq 
each raced to new record highs. 
</P>
<P>
	A major contributor to the Nasdaq's weakness today was coffee  
company Starbucks, which surprised Wall Street with a forecast of 
lower than expected earnings for the next two quarters and for the 
year. Starbucks shares fell 12 5/16 to 25 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 118.88 million 
shares, ahead of Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 2.11 at 646.02, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 1.08 at 796.85. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 1.89 percent to its  
highest close since September 1997. European indexes also gained 
strength from the U.S. interest-rate decision. In afternoon 
trading, Germany's DAX index was up 1.9 percent, Britain's FT-SE 
100 was up 2.3 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 2.1 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
