<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Probe Undersea Cable Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department said Thursday it has  
begun an antitrust investigation of the undersea cable business, in 
which groups of telecommunications companies band together to build 
and maintain undersea cables. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are looking at the possibility of anticompetitive practices  
in the international undersea cable industry,'' said department 
spokeswoman Jennifer Rose. She declined to give further details. 
</P>
<P>
	Undersea cables are used to transmit telephone and Internet  
information around the world, and telecommunications companies have 
worked together for decades to finance them. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wall Street Journal, which first reported on the  
investigation Wednesday, said Sprint Corp. and Level 3 
Communications -- members of a consortium building an undersea cable 
between the United States and Japan -- had received Justice 
Department letters demanding information in the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Post reported Thursday that AT&AMP;T Corp. also said  
it received such a letter. 
</P>
<P>
	The Journal also said Thursday the Federal Communications  
Commission was preparing to open an investigation of the undersea 
cable business. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
