<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 11:10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Comes Forward on Powerball Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROSEVILLE, Minn. (AP) -- A woman from central Minnesota came  
forward today and claimed a Powerball jackpot of $150 million, the 
third highest ever. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman from the Brainerd area came to lottery headquarters in  
this St. Paul suburb, and lottery officials confirmed she had the 
winning ticket from Wednesday night's drawing. Her name was not 
immediately released, pending a news conference set for this 
afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	The sole winning ticket had a jackpot worth $150 million if  
taken over 25 years, but the winner elected to collect all the 
money in a ``cash option'' lump sum worth $78.8 million, lottery 
director George Anderson said. 
</P>
<P>
	After state and federal tax withholding, he said, the winner  
will take home about $50.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The game, based in Iowa, is played in 20 states and the District  
of Columbia, and the sky-high pot attracted long lines of ticket 
buyers around the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``The sales are extremely out of control. It's just packed,''  
Deana Warner, manager at Pump N Pantry in Fond du Lac, Wis., said 
Wednesday. ``I don't know how to describe it. It's hard to explain 
the amount of business we're doing here. The ticket sales are 
astronomical.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The largest Powerball jackpot ever won was $295.7 million last  
July 29. The winning ticket was bought by 13 machinists -- the 
``Lucky 13'' -- who worked together in Westerville, Ohio. An 
Illinois couple set a record in May 1998 for a single-ticket winner 
by hitting a $195 million Powerball jackpot. 
</P>
<P>
	Players select five numbers from a field of one to 49 and a  
single Powerball from among the numbers one to 42. 
</P>
<P>
	The winning numbers drawn Wednesday night were 5, 10, 12, 20, 40  
and the Powerball was 3. In addition to jackpot, there were 49 
tickets sold that matched the five regular numbers but missed the 
Powerball. Those tickets are worth $100,000 each. 
</P>
<P>
	Would-be winners' dreams ranged from practical to escapist.  
</P>
<P>
	``I would probably pay off my immediate bills, set up college  
education fund my kids, my nieces and nephews, maybe pay off my 
folks' mortgage,'' said Bruce Lund of Ankeny, Iowa. ``And then I'd 
sit down and probably set up some kind of foundation that I could 
run and be philanthropic with the rest of the money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Kenworthy of Urbandale, Iowa, had something else in mind  
with the $5 he spent on Powerball. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd go to Tahiti where the women don't wear no tops,'' he  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
