<DOCNO> APW19990701.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 17:00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tennis Parents Behaving Badly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Gone are the days when Jimmy Connors' mom was considered a tough  
tennis parent because she sent hard-to-handle volleys whizzing 
toward her young son during practice at the net. 
</P>
<P>
	``If your own mother would do this to you,'' Gloria Connors  
warned the toddler, ``just imagine what your opponents will try.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A quick glance across the women's bracket at Wimbledon this year  
reminds us it's a good thing the kids still play one another 
instead of their parents. Because looming behind too many headlines 
about young players grabbing the spotlight, or older ones finding 
their way back in, are stories about grownups behaving badly. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why do so many parents seem to be crossing the line now?  
Because the stakes are higher than ever,'' said Nick Bollettieri, 
whose Florida-based tennis academy accepts full-time students as 
young as age 9. ``Because it's easier than ever to lose sight of 
what their duties are. 
</P>
<P>
	``More and more, especially on the girls' side, parents start  
out in a protective role. Then they get caught up in the money, or 
the glamour, or living through their child's success. And before 
they know it,'' he said, ``the parents are way more involved than 
they ever planned to be -- or should be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thursday's quarterfinal between 16-year-old Jelena Dokic of  
Australia and 18-year-old Alexandra Stevenson, suspended because of 
rain, was notable for several reasons. It not only matched two very 
young, very poised rising stars, it also marked the first time two 
qualifiers advanced to the quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
	But Dokic and Stevenson shared a troubling distinction, too.  
Both have parents who seem to be -- to borrow from Bollettieri's 
diplomatic vocabulary -- overinvolved in their children's careers. 
</P>
<P>
	Dokic's father, Damir, has been warned by the WTA Tour to be on  
his best behavior at Wimbledon. This followed his ejection from a 
recent tournament in Birmingham, England, for verbally abusing 
match officials then taking his protest outside the grounds where 
he was arrested for laying down in traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	Stevenson's surprising run through the bracket, meanwhile, has  
hardly been discussed during her interviews. She's been too busy 
answering questions about her mother Samantha's allegations of 
racism and lesbianism on the tour. And that was before the 
teen-ager was asked whether basketball great Julius Erving was the 
father who was never present in her life. 
</P>
<P>
	Answering questions about their parents was already a fact of  
life for three other quarterfinalists. 
</P>
<P>
	Steffi Graf's father, Peter, has slipped quietly into the  
background after serving a sentence for tax evasion. But he made 
such a mess of his personal life and her business affairs a few 
years ago that she nearly landed in jail along with him. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman Graf beat Thursday, Venus Williams, handles inquiries  
about her father, Richard, with such aplomb these days it's clear 
she's had too much practice. Say what you want about how the elder 
Williams trained Venus and sister Serena to play tennis -- but one 
thing they've learned is how to handle hostile questioning. 
</P>
<P>
	The last member of the not-so-exclusive club, Mirjana Lucic,  
fled her native Croatia late last year to escape an abusive father. 
Her story may be the saddest; she accused her father, Marinko, of 
beating her when she lost a match or didn't hustle in practice. 
Yet, parent problems aren't limited to the handful of women who 
reached the quarterfinals. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Pierce's father, Jim, was is back at WTA events under what  
the tour calls ``severe restrictions.'' Those follow his banishment 
from WTA events between 1993 and 1998 for what was termed ``abusive 
behavior.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And for all the pleasant echoes that Jennifer Capriati's return  
to Wimbledon brought, it also served as a reminder of the 
too-much-too-soon syndrome that dominating parents have foisted on 
talented kids. 
</P>
<P>
	No one has a better perspective on the problem than Bollettieri,  
for whom pushy parents are both a blessing and a curse. 
</P>
<P>
	``You want the discipline they bring,'' he said. ``Separating  
that from the rest of the baggage is what's tough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bollettieri gets $30,000 a year for housing each of his 200  
full-time students. That means he has to balance the parents' 
dreams with what's realistic for their children. He has collected 
some of those experiences for a book due out in September. 
</P>
<P>
	``Needless to say,'' he said, ``the chapter about parents is as  
touchy as it gets.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
