<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phillips Ups Interest in Oil Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BARTLESVILLE, Okla. (AP) -- Phillips Petroleum Co. announced an  
agreement Thursday that will expand its interest in a Venezuelan 
oil field and boost its worldwide reserves by 32 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips agreed to exchange its 18 percent working interest in  
the LL-652 oil field in Lake Maracaibo, Venezuela, for two-thirds 
of ARCO's 30 percent working interest in the Hamaca heavy oil 
project in Venezuela's Orinoco Oil Belt. 
</P>
<P>
	The exchange brings Phillips' share in the Hamaca project to 40  
percent, the company said in a news release. 
</P>
<P>
	Texaco has agreed to acquire the remaining one-third of ARCO's  
Hamaca interest. The other 30 percent is held by Petroleos de 
Venezuela S.A. 
</P>
<P>
	The three companies manage their interests through a joint  
operating company called Petrolera Ameriven. 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips expects the Hamaca project to begin producing 36,000  
barrels per day in mid-2001, then reach peak production of 190,000 
barrels in 2004 and continue that level of production for 35 years. 
The cost for the project to reach peak production is $3 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said the agreement supports a strategy of adding  
low-cost, long-life reserves to its portfolio. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
