<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Movie-Obsessed Youths Convicted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Two teen-age cousins who said they were  
inspired to kill by the teen slasher movie ``Scream'' have been 
convicted of murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Mario Padilla, 17, was found guilty Thursday in the killing of  
his mother, 37-year-old Gina Castillo. 
</P>
<P>
	A separate jury convicted Samuel Ramirez, 15, earlier this week.  
That verdict was sealed until Padilla's panel returned its verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge John Cheroske had banned any reference to the movie during  
the trial, but testimony at a preliminary hearing showed that the 
boys were obsessed with the film ``Scream'' and its sequel, 
``Scream 2.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the movies, teen-agers are knifed by killers in Grim Reaper  
costumes who are obsessed with horror movies. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Castillo was stabbed 45 times with four knives and a  
screwdriver in January 1998. Padilla and Ramirez said they attacked 
her while she was seated at her home computer. Padilla stabbed her 
and Ramirez held her down, according to their admissions. 
</P>
<P>
	During the preliminary hearing, one of the boys said that the  
slayings depicted were ``cool.'' And on the way home from one of 
many viewings, he told a pal: ``It was a perfect way to kill 
somebody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That testimony was not allowed at the trial, and when the taped  
confessions were played for the jury, their own mentions of the 
``Scream'' movies had to be edited out. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the defendants' ages, prosecutors are not seeking the  
death penalty. Padilla could get life in prison without parole. 
Ramirez, who was 14 at the time of the killing, faces up to 25 
years to life in prison. Both were tried as adults. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
