<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tapes Dropped From Cisneros Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government on Wednesday scaled back the  
number of tapes secretly recorded by Henry Cisneros' ex-mistress 
that it says are needed for the former housing secretary's upcoming 
conspiracy trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors initially said they intended to use 34 of the 88  
tapes that Linda Jones recorded and later handed to federal agents 
investigating whether Cisneros conspired with Ms. Jones and others 
to conceal more than $250,000 in alleged hush money payments to 
her. 
</P>
<P>
	But on the sixth day of a pivotal pretrial hearing on the tapes'  
admissibility, prosecutor Jim Fleissner said the government now 
intends to use only 26 recordings. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros' attorneys contend all 88 tapes -- which are copies of  
since-destroyed originals -- are inadmissible because they 
constitute ``tampered'' evidence and because Ms. Jones had an 
unlawful intent in making them. 
</P>
<P>
	The recordings are central to prosecutors' contention that  
Cisneros, while under consideration for a post in the Clinton 
administration, conspired with Ms. Jones and two aides to conceal 
the scope of his payments to her from the FBI agents who were 
conducting his Cabinet background check. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisneros, who headed the Department of Housing and Urban  
Development from 1993 through 1996, acknowledged to the FBI that he 
had provided financial support to Ms. Jones after publicity over 
their extramarital affair cost her marriage and career as a 
political fund-raiser. But prosecutors contend he falsely told the 
FBI that he never paid her more than $10,000 annually. 
</P>
<P>
	The 18-count indictment against Cisneros alleges that he paid  
her more than $264,000 between 1990 and 1993. He has pleaded 
innocent. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Jones testified last week that she began recording her phone  
conversations with Cisneros as their relationship soured and she 
scrambled for proof of his earlier verbal commitment to support her 
financially. 
</P>
<P>
	She ran afoul of Independent Counsel David Barrett in part for  
misrepresenting the tapes to his prosecutors, the FBI and Internal 
Revenue Service as originals and is serving 3 1/2 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Corroborating both prosecution and defense lawyers, a government  
tape expert testified Wednesday that all 88 tapes are copies. 
Prosecutors have acknowledged that five of the tapes they want to 
submit into evidence were altered by Ms. Jones, largely to 
eliminate passages in which she threatened Cisneros. 
</P>
<P>
	Tape expert Bruce Koenig testified that at least five others are  
copies of copies. Many show signs of having been halted 
mid-recording or have short gaps that in some cases can be 
explained by the voice-activation recorders she used, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Koenig said there are no signs of conversations being  
manufactured either by splicing or adding information. ``That, I'm 
positive, didn't happen,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But under questioning from Cisneros lawyer Barry Simon, Koenig  
acknowledged that because all of the tapes are copies, it may not 
be possible to detect every alteration. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
