<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UAW Chief Discounts Iowa Union Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The president of the United Auto Workers  
distanced the union Thursday from a decision by its Iowa affiliate 
to bestow an early endorsement on Al Gore's campaign for president. 
</P>
<P>
	``While they are entitled to their opinions, a group of less  
than twenty members in Iowa does not speak for the International 
Executive Board of the union and no one should think that they 
do,'' union president Stephen P. Yokich said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The unusual rebuke of the Iowa council representing 18,000  
active members reflected top union officials' displeasure with the 
unilateral action as well as lingering reticence in labor about the 
Clinton administration's record on trade. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore campaign spokesman Roger Salazar said the vice president  
was ``working to show the working men and women of the 
international UAW that Al Gore is their candidate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Iowa UAW endorsed Vice President Gore on Sunday, the second  
show of support from organized labor in the key presidential caucus 
state. The UAW event, coming on the heels of an endorsement from 
Council 61 of the American Federation of State, County and 
Municipal Employees, offered Gore key political muscle. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite occasional differences, union leaders have maintained  
friendly relations with the Clinton administration. But former Sen. 
Bill Bradley, Gore's only Democratic challenger, has made inroads 
with many unions, speaking recently to a Teamsters meeting in 
Orlando and Service Employees International Union members in Los 
Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts saw the Iowa endorsements as a sign that labor was  
ready to put aside its differences with the Clinton administration, 
but Yokich's statement and the debate among the leaders of other 
national unions showed that differences remain. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is the International Executive Board that is empowered to  
make endorsements for candidates for national office following a 
union-wide process of evaluation,'' Yokich said. ``That process is 
anything but finished at this point in time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Korman, the UAW regional director for nine states,  
including Iowa, stressed that under the union's charter, state and 
local councils do not have the authority to endorse presidential 
candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	While he backed Yokich's statement, he said it wasn't so much a  
rebuke as an effort ``to set the record straight -- that that was 
not a blanket endorsement of the Gore candidacy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a push by some AFL-CIO officials to move ahead with  
an early endorsement of Gore has run into resistance from several 
large unions, according to a half-dozen union officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Leading the call for an endorsement at the last AFL-CIO  
executive council meeting was AFSCME President Gerald McEntee, who 
garnered favor with top Democrats with an early endorsement of the 
Clinton-Gore ticket in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	But several unions, including the UAW, the Teamsters, and  
several building trades unions, angry about Clinton administration 
policies on trade and reticent to play such a big political chit 
early, spoke against an early endorsement. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are some people who think it would be a good bump for  
Gore to do that, but I think it would be contentious to say the 
least, and I don't think that does anybody any good,'' said Mike 
Mathis, the Teamsters' director of governmental affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	The AFL-CIO executive council is considering whether it should  
make a recommendation on an endorsement when it meets in August. If 
it does, the recommendation would have to be acted upon by the 
biennial convention in October. Clinton and Gore have addressed the 
convention in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	But several labor officials questioned whether that would  
happen. The Teamsters, the largest AFL-CIO affiliate with 1.4 
million members, are inclined to wait until after the primaries 
before officially endorsing a candidate, Mathis said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see a real strong push for an early endorsement,''  
Mathis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Salazar indicated that Gore recognized he had work to do to  
secure labor's backing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to work very hard to pursue the support of labor  
leaders and working men and women all across America because we 
think we can show them that Al Gore has fought very hard on issues 
that are important to them,'' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
