<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Fall / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) --Bond prices fell Thursday as traders cashed in on  
Wednesday's rally amid new inflation jitters and a reassessment of 
the Federal Reserve's latest interest-rate stance. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond, which shot up  
1 9/16 points Wednesday, fell 9/16 point on Thursday, or by $5.62 
per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the opposite 
direction, rose to 6.00 percent from 5.96 percent late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices had soared on Wednesday, even though the Federal  
Reserve raised a key short-term interest rate. The powerful rally 
was triggered by investor relief as the Fed suggested it won't 
raise interest rates for a second time later this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, traders re-evaluated the Central Bank's actions and  
speculation grew that rates still might increase beyond the 
quarter-point increase of Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	As rates rise on new Treasury securities, the value of bonds  
already held by investors is depressed. 
</P>
<P>
	New economic data also revived inflationary fears and the  
specter of future interest rate hikes aimed at preventing the 
economy from overheating. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association of Purchasing Management reported  
Thursday that the manufacturing sector expanded at a 
stronger-than-expected pace in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in the Treasury market, prices of short-term Treasury  
securities fell 3/32 point to 1/8 point, while prices of intermediate 
maturities fell 7/32 point to 3/8 point, reported Bridge Telerate. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills fell to 4.64 percent, while  
the discount tumbled 0.11 percentage point from Wednesday to 4.52 
percent. Six-month yields fell to 4.99 percent as the discount fell 
0.03 percentage point to 4.80 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	One-year yields remained at 5.05 percent, while the discount  
remained unchanged at 4.80 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 6.00 percent from 5.25 percent late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 7/32 to 118 23/32, with the yield 
rising to 5.54 percent from 5.53 percent. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
