<HEADLINE> Former NY Mayor Koch Hospitalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Former Mayor Edward Koch was taken by ambulance  
to a hospital today with chest pains and doctors found a blocked 
artery, his former press secretary said. 
</P>
<P>
	Koch, 74, arrived at his gym for his daily workout and began  
having pains, said George Arzt, his former spokesman and a close 
friend. He was taken to New York Weill-Cornell Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
	The former mayor, who served three terms, was being treated in  
the cardiac care unit after doctors found he had a blocked artery, 
Arzt said. 
</P>
<P>
	Koch was briefly hospitalized in March for low blood pressure  
when he showed up for a workout at the same gym. He had a minor 
stroke while he was mayor in 1987 and has worked out regularly 
since. 
</P>
<P>
	He was hospitalized briefly in 1991 when he collapsed during a  
workout and again in April 1997 after beginning a strict no 
carbohydrate diet and taking diet pills. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
