<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress To Get Olympics Documents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Atlanta Olympic organizers on Thursday pledged  
full cooperation with congressional investigators looking into 
possible corruption in the bid for the 1996 Games, although they 
said there was nothing to find. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Commerce Committee investigators, who opened their  
probe in the wake of bribery allegations involving the 2002 Games 
in Salt Lake City, will have ``unfettered access'' to all records, 
including eight sensitive boxes of documents, said Billy Payne, 
former head of the Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games. 
</P>
<P>
	He said another 6,000 boxes of records will be made available to  
the public July 19, the three-year anniversary of the Atlanta 
opening ceremonies, with the eight boxes kept private. The wait is 
to set up a procedure for viewing the records, which will include 
access and retrieval fees yet to be determined. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta organizers said the investigators will find no  
wrongdoing in the records. 
</P>
<P>
	``When this thing broke in Salt Lake City, people started to  
wonder about Atlanta, saying, `Billy, say it ain't so,' '' said 
A.D. Frazier, former chief financial officer for ACOG. ``I'm here 
to say that it ain't so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich., who chairs the subcommittee leading  
the investigation, welcomed the announcement of cooperation, even 
if it came after a harshly worded letter written to Payne Tuesday 
threatening subpoenas and other legal action. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know all too well the path Salt Lake City organizers chose.  
...'' Upton said in a statement. ``Taxpayers deserve to know if the 
same thing happened in Atlanta.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to both Commerce Committee and Atlanta officials,  
investigators always had access to the eight controversial boxes. 
</P>
<P>
	But since Atlanta officials maintain they contain private  
information -- such as lists of donors wishing to remain anonymous, 
letters subject to attorney-client privilege and personnel files -- 
they asked the investigators not to make copies. 
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta Journal-Constitution and state Attorney General  
Thurbert Baker have sued to see the records, saying they fall under 
the Georgia Open Records Act. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want our day in court to prove our case,'' Payne said.  
</P>
<P>
	Organizers also were fearful the documents would become public  
through release in a congressional report or through news leaks. 
</P>
<P>
	Commerce Committee Chairman Tom Bliley, R-Va., said Thursday the  
organizers' concerns about confidentiality would be taken into 
consideration, but no promises would be made. 
</P>
<P>
	Also at issue was who was to pay the $20,000 for copying all the  
documents. Payne said the Atlanta organizers would pay the bill and 
the investigators would get the copies they need. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was an administrative matter that has been resolved,''  
Payne said. ``We have been cooperating with them all along.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Payne, Frazier and former Atlanta mayor and ACOG co-chairman  
Andrew Young also announced that formal papers were filed Thursday 
to dissolve ACOG, a nonprofit corporation that had a $1.7 billion 
budget. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is something we always said we would do,'' Payne said.  
``In a sense, we now celebrate the conclusion of our mission of 
organizing and celebrating the Centennial Olympic Games.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
