<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 10:31:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Promise Massive Tax Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- With the federal government awash in money,  
House Republicans promised today to pass a massive tax cut that 
includes broad income tax relief and cuts in taxes on capital gains 
and estates. 
</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., said the size of projected  
federal surpluses should allow Congress and President Clinton to 
ensure the future solvency of Medicare and Social Security as well 
as cut taxes over the next decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``We now have the largest surplus in history,'' Hastert told a  
Capitol Hill rally. ``As we commit ourselves to finding ways to 
secure our retirement programs, we also commit ourselves to 
bringing fairness to the tax code.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Without announcing specifics, Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, the  
House Ways and Means Committee chairman, said the tax bill would 
include broad income tax relief for ``everyone who made this 
surplus possible,'' as well as changes to fix the ``marriage 
penalty'' in which millions of two-income couples pay more than 
they would if single. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican aides who spoke on condition of anonymity said that  
options for the broad-based income tax cut under consideration 
included reductions of 1 percent a year across the board -- for a 
total of 10 percent over the decade -- and upward adjustment of the 
lowest 15 percent bracket so that more people would pay at a lower 
rate. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Archer said the measure would phase out estate  
taxes, reduce capital-gains taxes on investments retroactively to 
today, increase the amount of money people can contribute to 
Individual Retirement Accounts and extend expiring business tax 
credits. 
</P>
<P>
	``Americans today are paying higher taxes than any time in  
peacetime history,'' Archer said. ``They have the right to pay 
less.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Archer this week had said the bill could reach $1  
trillion or more, new Congressional Budget Office forecasts for the 
10-year surplus would leave Republicans just short of that figure. 
The budget resolution passed earlier by Congress envisions tax cuts 
of $778 billion over the decade. 
</P>
<P>
	House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., called the plan  
``totally irresponsible'' because it would not eliminate the public 
debt and would prevent investments in areas such as education. 
</P>
<P>
	``They really have left out the important priorities that we  
ought to be dealing with,'' Gephardt told reporters. ``We do need a 
tax cut. It can be far less expensive than this one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, as budget surplus projections keep rising, fewer members  
of either party are seriously suggesting there should be no tax cut 
at all. The argument is increasingly becoming how large and who 
stands to benefit most. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's money for more things,'' said Sen. Daniel Patrick  
Moynihan of New York, top Democrat on the Senate Finance Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet moderate House Republicans told Hastert at a lunch Wednesday  
that they oppose using improving budget surplus projections to add 
to the $778 billion, 10-year tax cut already envisioned by the 
GOP's budget blueprint. 
</P>
<P>
	``We already have a very large tax cut,'' said Rep. Michael  
Castle, R-Del. ``We're struggling to increase all our 
appropriations bills for education, health, the welfare of the 
country. ... My own personal vote is we should not increase the tax 
cut at all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That sentiment is shared by many Senate Republicans, who say  
they would prefer a bill that can attract Democratic support and 
that could be signed by Clinton, as opposed to a political 
statement aimed at the 2000 elections. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have a decision to make,'' said Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga.  
``Do we align ourselves with some kind of symbolic statement ... or 
do we fashion a doable measure? Let's move this forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For conservative Republicans, a tax cut of up to $1 trillion is  
a clear signal to voters they want to stop government from 
expanding through new spending out of the surplus, which they 
consider an overpayment by taxpayers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're talking about a trillion-dollar overage,'' said Rep.  
J.D. Hayworth, R-Ariz. ``It's important for us to show that we are 
here to provide much-needed tax relief for American families.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many Democrats are also beginning to craft alternatives as the  
tide of surplus cash erodes their arguments that Social Security 
and Medicare cannot be made solvent for the future if Congress 
passes a massive tax cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., co-sponsor with Coverdell of a  
more modest tax package that embraces some of the House bill's 
concepts, said up to 15 Senate Democrats could support a tax cut if 
it is no larger than $500 billion over 10 years and is targeted to 
the middle class. Clinton has indicated he might sign a moderate 
bill as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``There clearly is considerable momentum building for a  
middle-income tax cut,'' Torricelli said. ``The fight is becoming 
not whether there should be a tax cut, but who gets the dividend.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990701.0343 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 14:30:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Corn, Soybeans, Pork All Lower  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Corn and soybean futures prices collapsed Thursday on the  
Chicago Board of Trade as moderating Midwest temperature forecasts 
set the stage for bumper fall harvests. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, natural gas futures fell sharply, while pork  
futures retreated once more. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors removed a weather premium that had buoyed the market  
earlier this week on fears that temperatures in the upper 90s 
across the Midwest and parts of the Plains would damage young 
crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Agronomists earlier had suggested corn crops in Illinois and  
Iowa, the two largest growing states, were particularly vulnerable 
since they are entering the crucial pollination period that sees 
ears beginning to fill out. 
</P>
<P>
	But while temperatures are expected to soar, beneficial rainfall  
has been and is expected to continue to fall across growing regions 
through the weekend. And the hot weather is expected to abate by 
midweek. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybean farmers this spring and early summer have  
enjoyed relatively few weather problems, putting them on track to 
harvest a record soybean crop and the fourth-largest corn crop on 
record, according to the U.S. Agriculture Department. 
</P>
<P>
	World inventories, meantime, remain high following bumper  
harvests for Brazil and Argentina and ample U.S. supplies. World 
demand has been rising amid recovering economies in Asia, but not 
quickly enough to reduce stockpiles. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn for September corn fell 8 cents to $2.08 1/4 a bushel;  
September wheat fell 5 1/2 cents to $2.58 3/4 a bushel; November soybeans 
fell 8 cents to $4.52 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas futures fell sharply on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange after an industry report showed supplies in storage rose 
at a sharper-than-expected rate last week. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Gas Association reported natural gas in storage  
rose 91 billion cubic feet to 2.03 trillion cubic feet last week. 
That put supplies 1.1 percent higher than this time a year ago and 
left them at 63 percent of storage capacity. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas is used to power turbines at electrical plants for  
air conditioning and heating. But with forecasters calling for 
moderating temperatures and industrial demand expecting to fall 
over the long Fourth of July holiday, there was little buying 
interest. 
</P>
<P>
	August natural gas fell 8.5 cents to $2.309 for each 1,000 cubic  
feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude and unleaded gasoline edged higher, posting new 19-month  
highs, as investors bet inventories later this year will dwindle as 
world oil producers continue to limit production. 
</P>
<P>
	August crude rose 10 cents to $19.39 a barrel; August unleaded  
gasoline rose .26 cent to 57.03 cents a gallon; August heating oil 
fell .20 cent to 48.82 cents a gallon. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork futures finished mostly lower on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, continuing a weeklong retreat brought on by concerns 
about large swine herds. 
</P>
<P>
	August lean hogs rose .03 cent to 44.60 cents a pound; August  
pork bellies fell .30 cent to 36.55 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
