<DOCNO> APW19990701.0344 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 07:50:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Does Gore Independence Bug Clinton? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As a political pastime, watching presidents  
and vice presidents for signs of stress or rifts between them is a 
Beltway favorite. Never more than now, as Al Gore tries to show his 
independence from President Clinton -- especially from his scandals 
-- for the 2000 campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton is said to have been angered at Gore's hard words about  
his personal conduct when the vice president kicked off his 
campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination two weeks ago. 
</P>
<P>
	But those reports come with no names on them, as is customary in  
such situations. Rift-watchers note that there has been no firm 
denial Clinton was miffed, and so judge that he must have been. 
That may well be the case. 
</P>
<P>
	The question is what it all means, and the answer is probably  
not much. Although not for lack of stoking, as in the New York Post 
commentary of sometime Clinton adviser Dick Morris, who calls it 
war and says Clinton is furious, livid. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House says not. ``I talked to him half a dozen times  
while we were in Europe about the Gore announcement, the speech, 
the coverage, and he never expressed any anger to me,'' said Joe 
Lockhart, Clinton's press secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	The pressure point was said to have been Gore's description of  
the president's conduct in the Monica Lewinsky affair as 
inexcusable, and his lament of all the time wasted from real 
business because of it and the impeachment. 
</P>
<P>
	That's certainly nothing Clinton hadn't heard before. But he had  
not heard it so vehemently from Gore, the loyal lieutenant who 
called him one of history's great presidents the day the House 
impeached him. 
</P>
<P>
	In these situations, it is not unusual for people around a  
president or a vice president to talk, without attribution, about 
friction. 
</P>
<P>
	White House chief of staff John Podesta told Clinton aides on  
Monday that the president is with Gore 100 percent, and that none 
of them should be suggesting otherwise. He said there should be no 
more gossip or speculation about the relationship. His instructions 
to aides who might do otherwise: ``Keep your mouth shut.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's staff got much the same message. For his campaign, rumors  
of a president miffed at his rebukes might not be a bad thing, 
given the polls reporting a certain weariness with Clinton. 
Whatever the mood swings, the president is pushing hard for Gore 
and accords him a share of the credit for a major political asset, 
the thriving economy and surplus budget. 
</P>
<P>
	It hasn't always been that way for vice presidents.  
</P>
<P>
	When Richard M. Nixon ran in 1960, he claimed that his two terms  
in the job had given him broad experience in making tough 
decisions. But President Dwight D. Eisenhower undercut that, saying 
that he'd made the decisions and no one else, although Nixon 
sometimes was consulted. Then he made it worse by saying that he 
couldn't remember a major idea of Nixon's the administration had 
adopted. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyndon B. Johnson kept his political thumb on Hubert H. Humphrey  
in 1968, balking when the vice president attempted even a minor 
break from administration bombing policy in the Vietnam War. The 
handicap was enough to prompt liberal Democratic governors to 
suggest to Humphrey that he resign as vice president and run as his 
own man. He said that was out of the question. Humphrey lost, 
narrowly, to Nixon. 
</P>
<P>
	Before he had to resign in a kickback scandal, Vice President  
Spiro T. Agnew took conservative issue with Nixon's initial 
openings toward China, complaining about exchange visits that were 
preludes to the reopening of official contacts. He did so off the 
record, but that cover didn't last a day. The White House silenced 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	There's always friction when a vice president starts campaigning  
to succeed the president he has served and needs to carve a role of 
his own. It is not an easy transition; George Bush, in 1988, is the 
only modern vice president elected directly from that job to the 
White House. 
</P>
<P>
	But the strains usually are concealed or denied, or have been  
for the past 60 years, since Vice President John Nance Garner's 
break with Franklin D. Roosevelt. Garner, no fan of the New Deal 
anyhow, wanted the Democratic nomination for himself in 1940, and 
declared himself a candidate a year in advance. To no avail. FDR 
broke tradition, ran, and won, with a new No. 2. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	Walter R. Mears, vice president and special correspondent for  
The Associated Press, has reported on Washington and national 
politics for more than 30 years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
