<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> False Call of Rifle by White House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Police closed streets near the White House and  
Secret Service agents checked several buildings after an unfounded 
report today that a man with a rifle was spotted on a rooftop. 
</P>
<P>
	Pedestrians were barred from the area around the White House  
where security already had been tightened because of Egyptian 
President Hosni Mubarak's visit with President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1 1/2-hour search was triggered by an anonymous phone call to  
the Park Police that a man with a rifle was seen on a rooftop 
across from the Treasury Department building. While authorities 
searched buildings, a Park Service helicopter surveyed from above. 
</P>
<P>
	``A search was made and we were unable to corroborate the story  
or that someone had a gun,'' said Secret Service spokesman John 
Tomlinson. ``We're saying it was unfounded and we're opening the 
streets back up to traffic. The search is over.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
