<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 22:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Headmaster After Fox Sitcom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KENT, Conn. (AP) -- It's been eight years since he graduated from  
prep school and Seth MacFarlane is still being scolded by the 
headmaster. 
</P>
<P>
	MacFarlane, a 1991 Kent School alumnus, is the creator of ``The  
Family Guy,'' an animated satire on Fox television that infuriates 
the Rev. Richardson Schell. 
</P>
<P>
	The head of the Kent School is leading a one-man campaign to get  
advertisers to drop their sponsorship of the show, which chronicles 
the travails of a doofus husband, his wife, their slacker 
teen-agers, homicidal toddler and trilingual pooch. 
</P>
<P>
	Schell, who was in London on Thursday and could not be reached  
by telephone, told The New York Times that he finds the show 
``obnoxious.'' He also objects to the fact that the name of the 
cartoon family, Griffin, is the same as that of his assistant at 
the Kent School. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no problem with Seth, and it is not a personal  
vendetta,'' Schell said. 
</P>
<P>
	Schell, headmaster at the Kent School for 18 years, has asked  
such major companies as PepsiCo., Philip Morris, DaimlerChrysler 
and Sprint to drop ``The Family Guy.'' Philip Morris and Sprint 
have withdrawn their ads. 
</P>
<P>
	Jokes on the show have touched on racism, politics and cult  
suicide. One gag involved a toy called ``G.I. Jew.'' In another, a 
boy shoots the head off a John F. Kennedy Pez dispenser, then says: 
``At least I have my Bobby Kennedy Pez dispenser to back him up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Fox spokeswoman did not return a message Thursday. MacFarlane,  
speaking through a Fox official, declined to comment, the Times 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Schell wrote the advertisers on behalf of ``Proud Sponsors  
USA,'' a group he acknowledges has a membership of one. 
</P>
<P>
	``Proud Sponsors, that's my name, that's me,'' he said. ``The  
reason I did it is I'm head of a school and I didn't want in any 
way to implicate the school in this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Shafer, a spokesman for Overland Park, Kan.-based Sprint,  
said letters from Schell and others prompted the company to 
undertake its own review of the show. 
</P>
<P>
	``The show is out there on the edge, in terms of subject matter  
and the way that it deals with controversial subjects,'' Shafer 
said. ``The show was risky enough that we felt it didn't match the 
advertising goals of our brand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Morris spokeswoman Mary Carnavale said the show was  
inconsistent with the company's emphasis on diversity, in part 
because the main characters are all white and in part because of 
the potentially offensive racial and ethnic subject matter. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
